the company that distributes the salk polio vaccine is asking for federal permission to test it against aids, after california physicians reported the vaccine lessened some symptoms of the disease
connaught laboratories inc., of swiftwater, filed an investigational new drug exemption petition with the food and drug administration on march 22
just two weeks ago, connaught stopped shipping the vaccine to california doctors who said they had used it to lessen symptoms in patients suffering from acquired immune deficiency syndrome. the company said it did not have fda approval to use the vaccine for anything other than the prevention of polio
west coast doctors complained their patients would be left without a treatment that had shown results against the deadly disease
in commenting on the fda petition tuesday, connaught vice president david j. williams expressed doubts about the experiments
while we know of no demonstrable clinical evidence for ipv other than the prevention of polio, the theoretical possibility has been raised by certain researchers and as such warrants that the company sponsor a study to determine if the vaccine has any potential in the treatment of aids,'' he said
a california doctor said the old polio vaccine has relieved some cancer lesions, herpes infections, swollen lymph nodes and fatigue among aids sufferers
dr. allen allen said statistics on more than 50 patients have shown the vaccine ``produces clinical benefits after six weeks.'' the halt in shipments forced him to delay a study he had planned, he said
the drug exemption petition requests authorization of a random, placebo-controlled study at lac-olive view medical center in sylmar, calif., directed by dr. glenn mathisen, chief of the center's infectious disease section and clinical research attending physician at the ucla aids clinical research center. poisoning</head>
food poisoning, possibly from fresh turkey fixed for lunch wednesday, sent at least 75 ellijay elementary school pupils to an overflowing hospital wednesday night
north georgia medical center administrator john downs said 24 pupils, mostly kindergartners through second graders, and one teacher were admitted for treatment of stomach cramps and dehydration brought on by vomiting. other pupils were being treated and sent home
it's not a serious thing. it just requires monitoring,'' he said. ``most are on intravenous feeding to replace the fluids they lost. we're listing it as gastritis due to food poisoning.''
downs said the 50-bed hospital already had about 40 patients when the schoolchildren started coming in wednesday afternoon
we've got them in the chapel and various treatment rooms,'' he said. ``we haven't had to use the halls yet, but we have beds available for that if we need it.''
if more pupils come in and are admitted, he added, ``we'll probably have to send some to other hospitals.''
gilmer county school superintendent j. homer hefner said the food poisoning apparently hit two classes the hardest and also struck some children from a few other classes at the 619-pupil school
lunch wednesday was fresh turkey and dressing, green beans and potatoes
downs said doctors suspected the turkey caused the illness. the turkey that remained after the meal was finished would be tested at a medical laboratory thursday, he said
i talked to the luncheon person and reviewed how they thawed and prepared the turkey and i saw nothing wrong with how they did it,'' hefner said, adding that he has asked the state department of education's food services division to help with his investigation into the problem
