long-time nbc spokesman m.s. ``bud'' rukeyser is leaving the network to go into business for himself
rukeyser, 56, said tuesday he would leave may 1 and plans to be a consultant to media companies
he has been at nbc for 30 years, the last 15 as executive vice president for communications
for 15 years, i've been whispering in the ears of four different chief executive officers. i thought if i was ever going to do something else, try something on my own, it was going to have to be now or never,'' rukeyser said
three people died in a fire that heavily damaged the cuban consulate on tuesday night. consular officials kept firefighters away for 15 minutes while they telephoned for permission to let them in, police said
the three victims _ two men and a woman _ were found in different rooms of the top floor of the four-story, 19th century mansion on the slopes of mount royal, said raymond therrien, a fire director
he said he presumed the three, whose identities were not available, were all consular employees and that they died of smoke inhalation
therrien said the fire was believed to have started on the top floor, where firefighters found unrolled fire hoses. the cause of the blaze was not known
consulate officials would not let firefighters battle the fire until about 15 minutes after they arrived, police said
they've got their own security and their own fire people working inside,'' police sgt. ulrich pilon told reporters at the scene. ``when they saw it was out of control they let the (firefighters) in.''
pilon said a security guard in a condominium across the street had phoned to say he saw smoke coming from the consulate's attic
there were one or two fire trucks there when we arrived,'' pilon said. ``after we talked with the consul and she checked with her officials in ottawa, they let the firemen in.'' the consul, whose name was not immediately available, took up her post a week ago
therrien said about 10 people were removed from the older part of the consulate where the fire raged, and that the fire-fighting effort was hampered by the consulate's barred windows
the blaze did not reach a recently completed wing of the building
the consulate is across the street from the house of former prime minister pierre trudeau and dozens of onlookers stood on his lawn to watch the blaze
the delay by the cubans is similar to an incident in january 1987 when soviet officials kept firemen waiting for a quarter of an hour before letting them fight a blaze that destroyed the soviet consulate in montreal
while firemen waited perched on ladders, soviet officials hustled boxes of documents out the back door into parked cars. others inside the building tried to douse the flames with chemical extinguishers and buckets of snow
