tv evangelist oral roberts said he will ask followers to donate another $8 million for his troubled medical school, but he did not repeat last year's warning that god would call him ``home'' if the drive failed
roberts, in a taped appearence tuesday on his son's program, ``richard roberts live,'' said he would reinstate the medical missionary program that the university canceled two months ago for lack of funds
now, by faith ... we will undertake a second year of scholarship. you heard me say it the way i said it, by faith, we will go for a second year,'' roberts said on the program, which was to be broadcast today
the evangelist agreed with his wife when she said their ``faith wavered a little'' when they announced cancellation of the scholarship program
the scholarships are provided to the students, who in return work in third world countries after graduation for several years as part of the roberts ministry
in 1986, roberts announced the drive to raise by march 1987 the $8 million needed to fund the scholarships and the medical school, saying he wanted his students to concentrate on their education without worrying about tuition
in announcing that fund-raiser, roberts said god told him, ``i want you to get this going in one year or i will call you home.''
on tuesday, roberts and his wife evelyn spoke via satellite from anaheim, calif., to a gathering of students, faculty members and university trustees in tulsa. the exchange was recorded for use on his son's program
the taped segment included statements from the chief financial officer of the university, and from auditor firms who said the $8 million raised last year was used to underwrite the total costs of the medical school for one year
medical students appeared confused when roberts made the announcement to reinstate the program. mark claussen, president of the junior class at the oral roberts university medical school, spoke out
i just want this to be clear, president roberts. two months ago, all of the students here were directly told that all money would be discontinued in may,'' claussen said
you fine young men and women ... have come face to face with the heart of christianity, living by faith,'' roberts responded. ``i've got no guarantees of what will happen in the future, as we try to serve our heavenly father.''
mrs. roberts interrupted her husband and said, ``two or three months ago, our faith wavered a little and that's what the confusion is.''
a girl in tawana brawley's school claimed 18 months ago that she had been abducted and sexually abused in a manner markedly similar to the details of miss brawley's story, according to a report published today
the teen-ager, who knew miss brawley, reported that she was grabbed by men in a green car and driven to a wooded area where she was sexually assaulted, according to a report in today's daily news, citing unidentified law enforcement sources
police in poughkeepsie investigating that case found that the charges were unfounded and that the girl had made up the story apparently to cover sexual abuse committed by a male relative
details of the 1986 incident have been turned over to the task force working on the brawley case under the direction of attorney general robert abrams
poughkeepsie police turned over the files after the earlier case was brought up by an anonymous caller on a local talk radio program, the report said
investigators are trying to determine whether the other student discussed the case with miss brawley as late as nov. 23, the day before miss brawley, who was then 15, claims she was abducted
miss brawley has said she was abducted nov. 24 in a green or blue car, taken to a wooded area and then sexually assaulted by at least six white men, including one who flashed a police-type badge
she was found after four days near her dutchess county home, covered with animal feces and with racial epithets scrawled on her body
