we were studying wisconsin and had visited a cranberry marsh about eight miles from here,'' ms. tabor said monday. ``we read about some students in massachussetts who had done the same thing for the corn muffin. i know it's a frivolous thing, but it's not frivolous to the children.''
a latin american organization condemned u.s. economic pressure on panama as outside interference, but also called on panama to adopt democratic reforms and hold elections
the 26-nation latin american economic system, based in caracas and created 12 years ago as a forum for latin american countries, ended an extraordinary two-day meeting on tuesday which had been requested by panama
it said the u.s. economic measures violated international law and the charters of the united nations and the organization of american states
the reagan administration has imposed economic sanctions on panama and made it clear that it wants panama's strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega, ousted as leader of that nation's military, known as the defense forces
noriega has been indicted in the united states on charges of drug smuggling and money-laundering, charges that he denies
washington still recognizes eric arturo delvalle as president of panama, though delvalle was stripped of his office by the noriega-dominated legislature after trying to fire noriega
foreign minister allan wagner of peru told the assemblage tuesday, ``we have not come to defend a regime, or even less a person who has been insubordinate to civil and constitutional authority
our solidarity is with the people of panama.''
wagner called for an end to panama's political crisis ``through free elections and the removal of any obstacles that prevent this clear expression of the will of the people of panama.''
the latin american economic system noted that foreign minister jorge abadia arias of panama promised the conference panama would ``deepen its democratic system.'' the economic system said a request for economic aid by panama will be considered ``with a spirit of solidarity'' by the organization's members
the nations said they opposed foreign intervention in panama and asked the united states to honor a treaty which turns full control of the panama canal over to panama in 1999
we urge the u.s. government to revoke immediately the coercive measures it has adopted against panama,'' they said in their final communique tuesday
we reaffirm the sovereign right of all nations to decide their own economic, social and political destiny in peace and liberty, free from foreign pressure, aggression and threats.''
two black communities are claiming victories after lengthy battles against the government, which had sought to relocate one group and change the political status of the other
in one case, an appeals court ruled tuesday that the government did not have the authority to incorporate the 120,000-member black community of moutse into a homeland dominated by a different tribe
also, the government said late monday it will not attempt to relocate the remaining 8,000 residents of oukasie, a township 30 miles west of pretoria
in the moutse case, the four-judge panel ruled that president p.w. botha exceeded his powers by incorporating the community into the kwandebele homeland on jan. 1, 1986. the court said the action was taken for ``administrative convenience'' rather than in the interest of moutse residents
most moutse residents belong to the north sotho tribe, and they argued that their language and culture differed sharply from the ndebeles, who make up most of kwandebele's 400,000 residents
moutse, located northwest of pretoria, previously was part of the lebowa homeland. but the white-led government excised moutse from lebowa when it incorporated the community into kwandebele
dozens of people were killed in the unrest that followed. moutse residents staged frequent protests, and battled both local police and vigilantes from the kwandebele government
moutse, at least for the time being, does not belong to any homeland. it is a 171-square-mile region that adjoins kwandebele, an impoverished, undeveloped homeland where many of the workers ride buses for up to eight hours a day, commuting to and from jobs in pretoria
meanwhile, minister of constitutional developlment chris heunis told parliament on monday that the government would no longer try to relocate oukasie residents to lethlabile, 12 miles away
heunis abolished oukasie by decree in october 1986, but only about 5,000 of the 13,000 residents moved to lethlabile, a newly established township with some upgraded facilities. most oukasie residents preferred their old home, where they could walk to their jobs in the white town of brits
about 8,000 residents have stayed even though the government at various times cut off the water supply, stopped garbage collection, tore down the school and halted bus service in an effort to make residents leave
the government also sent in bulldozers to destroy houses of people that moved from oukasie. the town has been run largely by community organizations for the past 18 months
the government's apartheid policy establishes a racially segregated society in which south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
