it was painted in 1910 and was one of 54 early works which the artist had to leave behind when, fearing nazi persecution, he left germany for good in 1937. he sent for them but they never arrived and were only recovered in 1984, 28 years after feininger's death, after negotiations the east germany. pvs, `police sources...'</note>
a bomb exploded early today near the south african embassy in paris after demonstrations protesting the killing of an african national congress spokeswoman. no injuries were reported
in the southern port city of marseille, at least six gunshots were fired tuesday night at the windows of a building in front of the south african consulate. the gunmen fled in a car and no arrests were made
the bomb, which caused only minor damage, exploded about 3 a.m. in paris at an office building a few blocks from the south african embassy. no one immediately claimed responsiblity for the bombing
the explosion occurred a few hours after police arrested more than 80 demonstrators who broke into the south african tourism office and protested outside the residence of the south african ambassador in paris
they were protesting the slaying of dulcie september, 53, the anc representative to france, switzerland and luxembourg who was found dead tuesday outside the door of her paris office from a gunshot to the face
police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at the time that the killing looked like ``the work of a professional.''
the anc, the main guerrilla group fighting white domination in south africa, blamed pretoria for the killing. the south african government denied responsiblity and said the attack was related to strife within the anc, which was banned by south africa in 1960 for its anti-apartheid activities
a french foreign ministry spokesman said on tuesday that no claim of responsiblity had been received
in marseille, the gunshots were fired at 11:15 p.m. tuesday at the windows of a building in front of the south african consulate. the building was painted with the slogan, ``botha, assassin, ss.'' the slogan was apparently referring to south african president p.w. botha
in paris, 41 protestors were arrested by police tuesday night after breaking into the south african tourism office after it had closed and smashing the interior. two officers and a french journalist were slightly injured in the scuffle to eject the protesters from the office
forty-six demonstrators were arrested tuesday night outside the residence of the south african ambassador in paris for painting anti-apartheid slogans on the wall of the building. police identified the protesters only as young leftists who supported the anc and all but four were released overnight
earlier, at least 1,000 people marched peacefully in separate protests of the killing in paris
president francois mitterrand said he would ask south africa about the attack and reaffirmed his ``categoric condemnation of the regime of racial segregation.''
a colleague of ms. september's claimed that the victim had requested protection from the interior ministry after receiving threats. she also said she had been followed for several days
the interior ministry denied she had requested protection
we were never called on for the least demand for protection,'' a spokeswoman said. ``if she had asked, we would have given it to her.''
at anc headquarters in lusaka, zambia, spokesman tom sebina called the killing ``part of a deliberate south african campaign to assassinate anc members and anc leaders.'' he said ms. september went to paris in 1983 and was among the anc's ``most vigorous activists.''
the anc maintains a worldwide network of about 20 ``information offices,'' including several in europe, to lobby for support and receive aid
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. 0772</first> rebels</head> 2 man in party. picks up 5th graf, `kintanar had ...'</note>
the military today said it captured the country's top rebel fighter and the no. 2 man in the communist party. president corazon aquino said the arrests marked the turning point in the battle against communism
maj. gen. ramon montano told reporters that romulo kintanar, commander of the communist new people's army, was among seven rebel leaders captured in tuesday's raids. he said authorities did not immediately realize who kintanar was because he gave a false name
the government-run philippine news agency quoted another military official as saying the chairman of the communist party of the philippines, benito tiamzon, had escaped by the time raiders arrived at his hideout in suburban quezon city
but his no. 2 man, party secretary general rafael baylosis, was among those arrested
the agency said tiamzon must have been tipped off by radio broadcasts on the arrest of his comrades in two raids at the manila suburb of san juan earlier tuesday
military officials said they believe the rebel leaders had just held or were about to convene a central committee plenum. they said search operations were continuing and they expected more arrests in the coming days
kintanar had long been wanted by the military. besides being the alleged head of the 24,000-strong new people's army, he is widely believed to be the organizer of communist urban assassination squads, called sparrow units because of the swiftness of their attacks
the sparrows first began operations in southern davao city in the early 1980s before moving out to the manila area and other urban centers
among those arrested with kintanar were baylosis and benjamin de vera, the central committee member in charge of operations on mindanao island. the others were new people's army logistics officer napoleon manuel; his wife inez; kintanar's wife gloria; and marco palo, a member of the party's liaison committee
mrs. aquino immediately hailed the arrests as ``happy news for our country'' and commended the armed forces chief of staff, gen. renato de villa, and other officers and enlisted men
it clearly demonstrates that we have turned the tide and are winning the war against the communist insurgency,'' she said in a statement read by press secretary teodoro benigno. ``the fact that they were arrested on the npa's 19th anniversary (on tuesday) attests to the admirable performance of our armed forces of the philippines. i am elated and so is our citizenry.''
montano announced the capture of kintanar when he presented the guerrilla leader and other captives to journalists at a suburban military camp where they were being held under heavy guard. the only captive not present was baylosis, who montano said refused to be photographed
montano would not let reporters ask the captives any questions
military officials did not mention the name of kintanar when they announced the arrests tuesday, identifying one of those arrested as mario asuncion _ apparently the alias kintanar used
montano told reporters that kintanar admitted his real identity when the officer confronted the rebel later. officials said the captured rebels refused to talk to interrogators and would only give their names
kintanar, baylosis and de vera were the fourth, fifth and sixth central committee members to be captured since mrs. aquino came to power in february 1986 in a civilian-military uprising that ousted president ferdinand marcos
former new people's army chief rodolfo salas, whom kintanar replaced, was arrested in 1986 while leaving a manila hospital following a checkup. last year, juanito rivera was captured in a raid on his mother's house in pampanga province north of the capital. and in february, tomas dominado was among 20 suspected rebels nabbed in a series of raids in the capital
tuesday's arrests came as the military was on a heightened state of alert in manila and several other regions in anticipation of attacks marking tuesday's 19th anniversary of the new people's army
no major rebel attacks were reported tuesday, but a japanese businessman was shot and killed in a manila suburb by an unidentified lone gunman who escaped, police said. the victim was identified as akihiro sato, 49, of tsuchiura city in japan's ibaraki prefecture
in luzon's bulacan province, two suspected communist assassins shot dead a policeman tuesday, while government troops captured a guerrilla in bataan province, military reports said
reports of attacks in the countryside often take days to reach manila. efforts</head>
tipper gore said she still supports efforts to establish a voluntary rating system for rock music lyrics as about 150 protesters, some sporting spiked haircuts and punk-rock clothing, demonstrated against the idea
mrs. gore, wife of tennessee sen. albert gore, a democratic presidential contender, spoke tuesday night to nearly 400 people at the 14th annual national issues forum, sponsored by pitzer college
the protesters, including musician jello biafra, were demonstrating against her efforts to initiate a rating system for rock music similar to that used by the movie industry
mrs. gore said she does not support censorship, but also said she is now more interested in helping the homeless and getting her husband elected president
at times chanting ``all we are saying is give rock a chance'' and ``no more censorship,'' the protesters lined two side entrances to the beverly wilshire hotel, where mrs. gore spoke
some waved signs proclaiming ``ozzy not albert,'' references to heavy-metal rock musician ozzy osbourne and to mrs. gore's husband
i just don't think any music should be censored by someone else,'' said kris wood, 20, of burbank
inside the beverly wilshire's grand ballroom, mrs. gore briefly acknowledged the demonstration
i understand that some people are outside protesting my efforts to call attention to violent and explicit song lyrics that are being peddled to children. that's certainly their privilege, but i think they've been misinformed about what my position is _ or possibly they don't care,'' she said
the author of ``raising pg kids in an x-rated society'' said she favors voluntary ``truth in packaging'' by the music industry and not censorship
most of her speech focused on the plight of america's homeless, however, a problem she said her husband would dedicate himself to solving if elected president
she showed a 12-minute video titled ``homeless in america: a photographic project,'' featuring poems and statements by homeless people. the tape was produced by several photographers working with the national mental health association and families for the homeless
we need a president who understands that homelessness isn't just a problem of those who are forced to live on the streets. it's our problem, yours and mine,'' she said
the annual national issues forum dinner sponsored by pitzer, one of the claremont colleges, has in past years featured such keynote speakers as former secretary of state henry kissinger and communications tycoon ted turner
the thunk of tennis ball machines is disturbing the serenity of some residents at this posh resort, and town officials ended up with the ball in their court
members of the ordinances, rules and standards committee pondered the issue tuesday: should use of the machines, popular with partnerless players on the peninsula's private estates and members-only clubs, be limited?
i think the people who now have them should be grandfathered in,'' mayor yvelyne ``deedy'' marix said. ``but i'm not sure that any more should be allowed.''
town council chairman nancy douthit lobbed back: ``it seems to me that when you begin regulating your neighbor's tennis game, it gets a bit heavy. supposing i had a noisy hair dryer _ should we then outlaw hair dryers in palm beach?''
three years ago, douthit was adamantly opposed to the high-pitched, whining noise made by leaf-blowers and had the town's noise ordinance amended to limit their use
the ordinance already prohibits the use during the winter season, when most part-time residents are in town, of pile drivers, jackhammers, sandblasters, dredges ``or any engines operated in such a manner as to emit odors or noises offensive or disagreeable to the inhabitants of the town.''
the committee agreed to recommend that the town council vote amend the noise ordinance to limit the use of tennis ball machines to between 9 a.m. and 5:30 p.m. during the winter and 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. the rest of the year
on sundays, they would be prohibited year-round
spot freezing can save the sight of many premature infants against a disease that causes 2,600 babies to lose their vision each year, say officials at the national eye institute
the technique of using a super-cooled probe to treat infants threatened with retinopathy of prematurity has been found to be effective in about half of the 172 babies treated in clinical trials at 23 medical centers, dr. carl kupfer, director of the national eye institute, announced tuesday
kupfer said a clinical alert has been mailed to 2,300 centers to notify doctors that the freezing treatment, called cryotherapy, is effective and safe in the treatment of the eye disease
retinopathy of prematurity occurs among very low birth-weight infants born prematurely. the disease causes an excessive growth of blood vessels in the retina, the light-sensitive organ at the back of the eye. this overgrowth of vessels can cause bleeding, scarring, retinal detachment and blindness
japanese studies in the 1970s suggested that this overgrowth of blood vessels could be halted and the eye allowed to develop normally if the sclera, the white of the eye, is frozen briefly
clinical studies in the united states began in 1986. officials at the eye institute said tuesday that the results will be published in the april issue of archives of ophthalmology and in the may issue of pediatrics
of 172 infants with the disease included in the study, the officials reported a 49.3 percent reduction in the loss of sight for those diseased eyes that were treated. in one group of infants, where both eyes were affected but only one eye was treated, the study found that 45.6 percent of the untreated eyes showed an ``unfavorable outcome,'' in comparison to only 24.1 percent of the treated eyes
the freezing treatment is accomplished by touching the eye briefly with a cold probe, an instrument with a ballpoint-like tip that is cooled by a refrigerant to about minus 80 degrees. a surgeon uses the instrument to freeze pinhead-size patches on the eye
dr. earl a. palmer, associate professor of ophthalmology and pediatrics at the oregon health sciences university in portland, was the chairman of the study
he said the results should ``greatly improve'' the ability of doctors to treat rop, but he admitted that medical science still does not know precisely what causes the disease nor why the freeze treatment seems to halt the disease
a new law that forbids bearded firefighters to enter burning buildings is worrying fire officials whose departments have amish volunteers
ohio requires firefighters to wear a self-contained breathing apparatus to enter a burning building or an area with harmful fumes
the apparatus has a face piece that provides clean air from a tank the firefighter wears on his back, said john wood, basic training coordinator for the ohio fire marshal's office
on march 1, a new law went into effect that prohibits bearded men from wearing the devices because facial hair can prevent a seal from forming between the face and the face piece
most amish men are bearded and won't shave because of their religious beliefs. there are several amish communities in northeastern ohio
it makes it hard for a lot of volunteer fire departments,'' wood said. ``i really don't know what we can tell them to do.''
in trumbull county's mesopotamia township, half the population is amish, said fire chief keith williams, and three of the community's four daytime firefighters have beards
the town can't afford to give up its amish firefighters, williams said tuesday
i put out a standing order. yet if they have a structural fire during the day, i know they're going to put the scbas on and go in. they're going to disregard my standing order,'' he said
under normal circumstances, that's grounds for disciplinary action. but on the other hand, i can't condemn them for doing what they're supposed to do _ saving life and property.''
wood said communities and firefighters won't be fined for violating the law. but if a bearded firefighter gets injured fighting a fire in which he needed a self-contained breathing apparatus, the state will be able to collect half his worker's compensation pay from the community
the soviet union is establishing a cooperative bank that will partially end the government's banking monopoly by providing services to a growing group of small, privately held businesses, an official said today
the bank, which is expected to open next year, would be operated as a cooperative to serve other cooperatives, according to an interview with viktor arkhipov carried by the official tass news agency
arkhipov, first vice-chairman of the soviet agri-industrial bank, said the cooperative bank should be allowed to offer higher interests rates to savers than the 2 percent to 3 percent offered by state-run banks and to seize the property of borrowers who fail to meet payments
thus the bank will have a vested interest in the high quality of the products put out by the cooperative, in it finding a ready demand,'' he said
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, who is encouraging the formation of cooperatives, said last week that nearly 14,000 of them have sprung up since legal restrictions were eased last year
cooperatives are approved by local authorities and taxed by the government, but are privately owned. each person who works in a cooperative venture owns a part of it
cooperatives have established restaurants, make clothing, pump gas and provide other goods and services to supplement the inefficient state-run economy
tass said the cooperatives had financial returns of almost 350 million rubles, about $560 million , by march
tass said that some soviet economists think a cooperative bank is a violation of the state monopoly of financial and credit operations introduced in 1918, just after the bolshevik revolution
but arkhipov told the news agency that under gorbachev's effort to restructure the soviet economy, the state financial monopoly has been restricted to foreign economic activity
the state monopoly ``is supposed only to coordinate the activities of the financial-crediting institutions and determine general financial policy,'' arkhipov said
the cooperative bank also could finance international contracts of cooperatives, tass said. under a draft of a new law, cooperatives would have the right to trade independently in foreign markets
north korea today claimed a south korean warship violated territorial waters off its coast, the north's official radio pyongyang said
radio pyongyang, monitored in tokyo, said coast guard boats were mobilized in response to an unidentified south korean warship which was spotted tuesday in the north's ``western territorial waters off changsan-kot.''
the report said the battleship fled toward the south
the act of a military provocation like this by the south is another planned scheme to intensify the situation on the korean peninsula,'' the radio said. north korea designates all areas within 50 miles of its coasts as being within its territorial waters
on tuesday, north korea charged that u.s. sr-71 high-speed, high-altitude reconnaissance planes had intruded its air space 12 times since joint u.s.-south korean military exercises began last month. graf pvs, he cited.</note>
democrat michael dukakis today thanked connecticut voters for the primary victory that gives him momentum heading into wisconsin and the next round of presidential contests
it was a good win for us. we won with a big, big margin,'' dukakis said on nbc-tv's ``today'' show. ``but it's not the first of my victories. i've won in the south. i've won in the midwest. i've won up here in the northeast ... i'm just very pleased that people who know me best were so supportive.''
the massachusetts governor defeated jesse jackson by a 2-to-1 margin in neighboring connecticut, and regained the lead in delegates to the democratic convention
the latest associated press count put dukakis at 647.55; jackson at 634.55 and uncommitted at 500.6. tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 364.8 and illinois sen. paul simon 169.5
the message ... is getting stronger and stronger every week this campaign goes on,'' dukakis told his backers tuesday night
he cited his commitment to job growth, education, housing, health care, the environment and ``a strong america that reflects our values and our principles.''
hands on his hips, dukakis also responded to those who have minimized his new england victories because of his regional advantage
it's as absurd to say this should be discounted as it is to say jesse's should be because (michigan) is next to illinois,'' he said upon returning to boston late tuesday after an evening in new york
he stuck closely to his chosen themes, avoiding any open criticism of jackson and refusing to speculate about the vice presidency
this sends us back to wisconsin and colorado with a very good boost,'' dukakis said, adding that each contest is different and that no candidate will win all of the remaining states
colorado's democratic caucus is monday and wisconsin's primary follows one day later
i look forward to going back out to wisconsin and colorado,'' both of which pick delegates next week, ``with that same strong message of economic opportunity and good jobs as someone who not only talks about those things but who's done them,'' dukakis said, underscoring the government experience that he has and jackson lacks
in a written victory statement, the dukakis campaign sought to draw attention to dukakis' vote among blue-collar white voters, who had helped jackson win in michigan
tonight, connecticut voters across all ideological lines _ and an overwhelming margin of blue-collar voters _ gave a resounding endorsement of the dukakis bid for the presidency,'' the campaign statement said
fielding questions from reporters, dukakis predicted that neither he nor jackson could hope to collect an outright majority of nominating delegates by the time the primary season ends in california on june 7
this is 15 rounds, and it's going to be a decision _ not a knockout,'' he said. ``i felt from the beginning that the field would narrow to two or three'' and that one candidate would have a ``substantial lead.''
asked how he felt after rebounding in connecticut from his surprising loss to jackson in the michigan voting four days earlier, dukakis said each race is different and ``it is the cumulative result that counts.''
israeli-backed militiamen stormed a pro-iranian guerrilla stronghold in south lebanon today after repulsing two attacks on their outposts, police reported
militiamen from the south lebanon army backed by israeli artillery fire inflicted heavy casualties on the guerrillas, police and united nations observers said
moslem radio stations in beirut said israeli soldiers also fought in the battle but police could not confirm that. the israeli army denied the reports
police said the attack occurred after the guerrillas, shiite moslems linked to the iranian-backed hezbollah movement, launched pre-dawn raids on militia posts near kfar roumman and the town of hasbaya
no accurate casualty figures were immediately available
police said a south lebanon army force, spearheaded by 12 soviet-designed t-54 tanks, drove the moslem guerrillas out kfar roumman after heavy fighting
the town, a base for the guerrillas of the islamic resistance movement, is about half a mile west of a south lebanon army base and two miles north of the shiite market town of nabatiyeh
most of kfar roumman's estimated 12,000 residents fled earlier as the battle raged. the town had come under repeated machine gun fire from hilltop army positions
islamic resistance fighters were seen withdrawing from kfar roumman. the town has been devastated by shelling,'' a police spokesman said
tanks from the south lebanon army advanced behind a fierce barrage of israeli artillery fire from u.s.-made 155-mm howitzers in the israelis' self-designated ``security zone'' north of the lebanese border, police said
the attacks, the latest in a chain of assaults by the islamic fighters, came as lebanon's moslems marked the 12th anniversary of land day, when the israelis killed six palestinians in 1976 in protests against land confiscation in the israeli-occupied west bank
a strike was also called in moslem sectors of the country to express support for the palestinians in the occupied lands. banks, schools, shops, restaurants, cinemas, government offices and other businesses shut down
palestinians in the occupied territories have been mounting violent protests against israeli rule since dec. 8. more than 110 palestinians and one israeli soldier have been killed
according to figures released tuesday by maj. gen. yossi peled, chief of the army's northern command, 236 lebanese guerrillas, mostly of the hezbollah movement, died over the past year in attacks on israelis and israeli-supported forces in lebanon. johnson</note>
the last of the nation's first test-tube quintuplets went home again after a week of observation for a breathing problem, a hospital spokeswoman says
veronica l'esperance left the hospital late monday after being observed for apnea, a condition in which she stopped breathing while eating, hospital spokeswoman carol jonson said tuesday
veronica, her brother and three sisters were born jan. 11 after their mother, michele l'esperance, was impregnated through in-vitro fertilization. the boy and two of the girls left the hospital march 7, jonson said
veronica and one of her sisters left the hospital 11 days later, but veronica went back into the hospital on march 21. she and the rest of the quints are doing fine, jonson said
officials say they can't be sure it was a prankster who planted green dye in a pool where highly radioactive nuclear fuel is stored, even though it happened on the eve of st. patrick's day
the 1,270-megawatt unit 2 reactor at palo verde nuclear generating station was not operating on march 16 when the 241,000 gallons of water turned green. the plant had been shut down feb. 20 for a three-month refueling outage
chemical analysis revealed the cause of the color change _ green dye _ but officials said it was still speculative to label the incident as the work of a prankster
we don't see any connection between the color change and the holiday,'' said don andrews, a spokesman for the arizona nuclear power project. ``we're investigating several possibilities. it may have been intentionally done. then again, it may not be.''
andrews said monday that plant security officials were investigating. he said the incident occurred in a 44-foot-deep stainless steel-lined pool that holds water in which highly radioactive fuel rods taken from the unit 2 nuclear reactor are stored after use
the rods are submerged in water that absorbs radioactive neutrons and gamma rays. andrews said the rods are being stored on-site until federal officials build an underground repository for permanent disposal
u.s. nuclear regulatory commission officials said they have determined that ``nothing harmful was added to the pool
greg cook, a spokesman for the nrc's region 5 office in walnut creek, calif., said the commission would deal harshly with anyone responsible for the prank at the $9.3 billion, triple-reactor plant
if it turns out that someone was playing a prank, that individual may need to have his sense of humor recalibrated,'' cook said. ``a nuclear power plant is the wrong place to horse around.''
since 1984, there have been at least 16 unusual incidents at palo verde, many involving unresolved mischief or suspected sabotage. but nrc and palo verde officials said they saw no connection between those incidents and the green water
