a kuwaiti communique declared that kuwait, which is the closest state to the iran-iraq war zone, ``reserves the right to respond to any assault on its territory or infringement on its sovereignty.''
the attack came only a few days after the kuwaitis had approached tehran, seeking to improve relations that deteriorated sharply seven months ago
police arrested 160 men and women protesting a pending labor bill that would restrict union rights, a top union official said today
frank meintjies, spokesman for the congress of south african trade unions, the nation's largest labor federation, said members of three unions were arrested tuesday as they responded to a call for lunchtime rallies
police had said in their daily unrest report they had arrested 124 men and women in industrial areas for gathering illegally and refusing to disperse. police gave no further details, except to say that they had used batons and dogs to disperse one group
meintjies said those arrested were members of the food and allied workers union, the paper and allied workers union and the national metal workers union. they were protesting the government's labor relations amendment bill, pending before parliament, which would make unauthorized strikes more difficult and require unions to pay employers' damages for illegal strikes
most of the congress of south african trade union's 750,000 members are blacks, who have no representation in parliament
the congress issued a statement tuesday listing incidents of what it termed ``state repression'' against union affiliates during the past mongth, including detentions, police raids on offices and removal of union property and records. it has been making similar complaints for the past year, accusing the government of harassment
police replied in a statement today, saying they do not comment on ``routine police duties, such as the visiting of premises, confiscation of property.''
it also said, ``the police do not act against people because they belong to certain organizations.''
however, in the few cases of emergency detainees which have reached the courts in the past 21 months, the government has often listed membership or participation in an organization as its reason for keeping people in detention without charge
one such case is that of zwelakhe sisulu, editor of the new nation newspaper, closed last week. answering his appeal to be freed or charged with a crime, the government said he was being held because of his participation in the national education crisis committee, a lawful organization, and because of his journalistic activities. sisulu denied he was a member of the committee
the american civil liberties union is challenging an order that blocked a woman from having an abortion because her estranged husband objected to her ending the pregnancy
the woman has a constitutional right to an abortion that the judge should not have interfered with, the group said, citing the supreme court decision legalizing abortion
the aclu said it would go to court today to ask state judge david s. young to vacate the restraining order he granted last week to michael jon reynolds, whose wife jennifer franks reynolds is about two months pregnant
utah is one of four states with laws requiring wives to notify husbands of abortion decisions, said planned parenthood spokeswoman mary carlson. however, utah is the only state in which the notification law hasn't been challenged in court or appealed
the aclu said if young doesn't change his ruling, it will take the case to the utah court of appeals
we feel (the order) is shocking and a restriction of personal liberties,'' said robyn e. blumner, aclu executive director. if the order is allowed to stand, ``utah will find itself once again a target of national mockery,'' she said
blumner said the case demonstrates that the state law should be repealed
aclu spokeswoman michele parish-pixler said the u.s. supreme court has ruled that no one can stop a woman from ending a pregnancy in its first trimester. ``it's over-reaching on the part of the judge to issue any type of restraint on the first trimester,'' she said
reynolds, who is seeking a divorce and custody of the couple's 10-month-old infant as well as the unborn child, obtained the restraining order because he is morally opposed to abortion, said his attorney, evan hurst
mrs. reynolds was served with the restraining order on the day she was leaving home to have the abortion performed
mrs. reynolds' attorney, julie bryan, said the u.s. supreme court ruled in the landmark roe vs. wade decision that husbands have no veto power over their wives' abortion decisions
the high court said that when a husband and wife disagree over an abortion, ``the view of only one of the two marriage partners can prevail. inasmuch as it is the woman who physically bears the child and who is the more directly and immediately affected by the pregnancy ... the balance weighs in her favor,'' bryan said, quoting from the decision
reynolds' attorneys plan to argue that the roe vs. wade case applies only to the state, not to private individuals
orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods fell 0.8 percent in february, the second consecutive monthly decline, the government reported today
the commerce department said that orders for durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent january decline
the february drop was the largest since a 1.4 percent setback in august. the back-to-back declines were the first such since the summer of 1986
but analysts said they were not overly concerned about the setbacks, contending that manufacturing will still be one of the top performing sectors this year
they said the declines did show that economic growth slowed in the first three months of the year as businesses cut back on orders in an effort to work down a high level of unsold goods
but the production cutbacks have been less severe than once feared and economists are now much more confident that the country will be able to get through this year without a recession
the february setback included a drop of 1.1 percent in orders for durable goods, which fell to a seasonally adjusted $118.5 billion. in an advance report last week, the government had put the decline at a slightly larger 1.8 percent
orders for non-durable goods, items not expected to last three years, fell 0.4 percent in february to $97.9 billion
in the major categories, defense orders dropped 8.2 percent to $8.4 billion. without that decline, orders would have fallen 0.5 percent last month
orders in the key category of non-military capital goods fell 3.9 percent last month to $33.4 billion. this category is expected to provide major strength this year as manufacturers boost spending on expansion projects to meet growing export demand for american goods
orders for transportation equipment were one of the few categories showing strength last month, climbing 3.5 percent to $30 billion, with the aircraft component showing an even larger 6.8 percent increase
shipments of manufactured goods edged up a slight 0.1 percent in february to $207.4 billion
the basque separatist organization eta claimed responsibility today for the shooting death of a retired air force general
two men shot and killed brig. gen. luis azcarraga perez-caballero, 81, sunday as he left santa maria church in salvatierra in alava province with his family and other worshipers
azcarraga perez-caballero was the second victim in political violence in spain this year. eta also claimed the shooting death last week of a civil guard officer in the basque town of durango
eta seeks independence from spain for the three-province northern basque region. since taking up arms in 1968, eta has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600 people, mainly police, military and civil guard officers
eta stands for homeland and liberty in the basque language
in a note sent to basque newspapers, eta claimed responsibility for the slaying and said it would stop its campaign of violence if prime minister felipe gonzalez agreed to talks that would include the issue of self-determination
the gonzalez government has said it will not talk with the eta as long as the eta continues launching terrorist attacks
the government also has said talks with eta would exclude any political concessions and focus solely on a plan to get the group to give up its arms and reintegrate its members into society. universities</head>
the justice department has refiled a massive desegregation suit against alabama's public universities, alleging that state officials deliberately continued a system of separate colleges for blacks and whites
the refiling of the 21-page lawsuit on tuesday was prompted by a ruling last year by the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals in atlanta, which found that significant errors had been made before and during trial in federal court in birmingham in 1985. the case was initally filed in 1983
u.s. district judge u.w. clemon had ruled that alabama maintains vestiges of a dual school system. but before he could begin the remedy phase of the case, his ruling was appealed by the state
the 11th circuit ruled that clemon, alabama's first black federal judge, should have stepped down because he took part in landmark civil rights cases when he was a private attorney
i would not agree that the case is starting from ground zero again,'' nathaniel douglas of the justice department's civil rights division said tuesday from washington
there have been efforts to resolve the case by negotiation, and we are ready to continue to do that.''
the suit filed by douglas and his staff again charges that state education officials have ``perpetuated a racial dual system in public higher education.''
the justice department said two of alabama's predominantly black schools _ alabama a&amp;m in huntsville and alabama state in montgomery _ operate near predominantly white schools and were intended for black students only, while whites attended the other institutions
justice department lawyers said evidence exists of intentions by state authorities to maintain the vestiges of the dual school system
federal attorneys cited a 1975 planning document of the alabama commission on higher education that said ``with alabama state and alabama a&amp;m to meet the needs of the state's negro citizens and with the university of alabama and auburn university as major state institutions, the state seemed relatively well served.''
the justice department said state officials continue to allocate ``far greater resources'' to the major white schools than to the predominantly black institutions
state authorities said the predominantly white and black schools in huntsville and montgomery are the result of decades-old patterns of preference by students
the reputed leader of the mafia in southern california and six associates have pleaded guilty to extortion or racketeering charges, but they denied being members of an organized crime syndicate
the plea bargains were accepted tuesday by u.s. district judge ferdinand fernandez on what was to have been the first day of the men's trial
prosecutors said the guilty pleas meant the government avoided a $1 million trial that could have lasted four months
the plea bargains were approved by justice department officials in washington after u.s. attorney robert bonner refused to accept the length of the negotiated prison terms
when the federal indictment was announced last may, bonner said, ``the main body of la cosa nostra in los angeles has been severely gutted.''
chief defendant peter john milano, 62, of westlake village, whom officials allege controls organized crime on the west coast, never admitted he was a mafia member. neither did any of the other defendants
milano, who owns rome vending co., pleaded guilty to involvement in a criminal enterprise and committing two racketeering acts. but his attorney, donald marks, said that could mean any criminal group, not just the mafia
milano faces up to a six-year prison sentence when he and the others are sentenced may 16
milano's brother, carmen, 58, of tarzana; brothers charles caci, 51, and vincent caci, 62, both of palm springs; rocco zangari, 54, of palm springs; stephen cino, 51, of las vegas; and albert nunez, 57, of camarillo, all pleaded guilty to extortion conspiracy
nunez also pleaded guilty to conspiring to distribute cocaine, and cino also pleaded guilty to making false statements
in return, prosecutors agreed to drop additional charges against the defendants and not institute any civil proceedings that could result in lawsuits or property forfeitures
nunez faces a 10-year term, cino an 18-month sentence, vincent caci and charles caci face one year, and carmen milano faces six months. under the agreement, zangari could receive probation
the trial of three more defendants was postponed until april 5 to give their attorneys time to reorganize. the trial of an 11th defendant was postponed indefinitely because he is ill
the indictment involved violations of the federal racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations statute. the los angeles case was one of several rico indictments nationwide that stemmed from a 1982 crackdown on organized crime
the prosecution was based on hours of secretly recorded tapes made in san fernando valley restaurants and parking lots in which the defendants allegedly discussed cocaine deals and plans to shake down gamblers or bookies
the indictment followed an undercover fbi investigation during which milano allegedly ordered the killing of two suspected informants, according to the indictment. the murders never occurred because of tips from informants, officials said. in israel</head>
in an effort to prove that jews and arabs can live in harmony, oil tycoon armand hammer and local jewish groups have pledged to build a $30 million community center in an impoverished arab suburb of tel aviv
we will set an example for the rest of israel and the arab world that jews and arabs can live together,'' hammer said tuesday
hammer and fellow industrialist guilford glazer said they will raise $1.6 million to help build the schools and recreation facilities in ajami-lev yaffo, a blighted suburb of tel aviv where more than 12,000 israeli arabs live
the jewish federation council of greater los angeles hopes to raise $10 million for the project
hammer, chairman of occidental petroleum, said recent violence in the predominantly arab west bank and gaza strip had nothing to do with the center's conception. the territories were captured by israel in the 1967 mideast war
planning for the community center began more than two years ago, he said
this center will bring people together,'' hammer said. ``it will restore pride and provide education and essential social services so they can have peace of mind and body. then, and only then, can they hope to plan for the future.''
the complex will feature upgraded elementary and high schools, recreation and sports facilities, a library, and an auditorium
two companies have been fined $130,000 each for the improper removal of asbestos during the demolition of an old factory, a federal prosecutor said today
the fines were imposed for violations of the clean air act, and the combined $260,000 penalty was the largest ever imposed in the nation for violation of the act's asbestos regulations, said u.s. attorney stanley a. twardy jr
consent decrees between the government and big apple wrecking corp. of middle village, n.y., and general datacomm industries inc. of naugatuck were filed tuesday in federal court in new haven
general datacomm owned the former uniroyal corp. shoe plant in naugatuck when it was razed about two years ago. big apple was the demolition contractor
the federal government charged in a june 27, 1986, complaint that the two companies failed to provide adequate notification to the environmental protection agency before removing asbestos from the demolition site. the complaint also alleged that the contractor failed to wet the asbestos during the removal and disposal process
after the complaint was filed, an injunction was imposed requiring the remaining demolition to be completed in compliance with federal regulations
in a state such as connecticut, with its constant renovation and demolition of aging industrial facilities,'' twardy said, ``it is crucial that proper precautions be taken by contractors in order to prevent asbestos from being emitted into the air.'' also calling for meese resignation.</note>
senate majority leader robert byrd called today for the resignation of attorney general edwin meese iii, calling meese ``the crown jewel of the sleaze factor in reagan administration history.''
he ought to get out,'' byrd, d-w.va., told reporters. ``the country cannot have confidence in the justice department when the top law enforcement officer obviously has to spend an inordinate amount of his time defending himself.''
he should be spending his time fighting the war on drugs, crime,'' byrd said
byrd opened his regular morning meeting with reporters by saying: ``mr. meese has become the crown jewel of the sleaze factor in reagan administration history.''
byrd said he usually would not call on any official to resign who hadn't been indicted for a crime, ``but we're talking about the top law enforcement officer in this country.''
it's just cloud after cloud after cloud, building in layers over his head to the point where all confidence in this agency is being seriously eroded,'' byrd said
the president ought to ask somebody, if he doesn't want to ask him himself, to ask mr. meese to step aside, step down,'' byrd said
a republican senator also called today for meese to step aside
you finally reach a place where there is a cloud of suspicion, a sufficient cloud of suspicion, that i think you owe it to the president to remove yourself,'' sen. bob packwood of oregon told reporters at an informal news conference
packwood said he did not expect reagan would ask meese for his resignation
the president will clearly not fire a friend,'' packwood said. ``the president does not do that to a friend.''
deputy attorney general arnold burns, assistant attorney general william weld and four of their aides abruptly resigned on tuesday. burns and weld offered little public explanation, but told associates they were concerned that the nearly year-long criminal probe of meese is hurting the entire justice department, according to several department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity
i don't really see how he (meese) can expect to continue to lead the department after resignations and circumstances like this,'' former attorney general elliot richardson said on the cbs show ``this morning.''
this man is the head of the chief legal agency, the law enforcement agency of the united states government. and there comes a point at which the mere fact that he is not indicted is insufficient,'' said richardson, who was attorney general during the nixon administration
i think it's just an extraordinary disaster,'' rep. barney frank, d-mass., said of the resignations. ``...the attorney general should quit. ...it's now clear that he can't run that department, that we're paying a very high price for his stubborness.''
an earthquake shook southwest iran early today and initial reports indicated there were casualties and damage
iran's official islamic republic news agency said relief teams were dispatched to dehdasht, 340 miles from tehran in the boyer ahmed province, to ``help the victims and estimate the damage.'' it did not give a casualty figure
dehdasht has a population of 105,000
it said the geophysics center in tehran registered the epicenter near dehdasht
the quake measured 5.2 on the richter scale
an earthquake of 5 can cause considerable damage. a 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage. main street</head>
the national governors' association told congress today that a sales-tax advantage held by mail-order sellers ``threatens the future of main street america.''
thousands of small retail businesses that support our communities and local citizen programs and generate jobs will not be able to compete in a market in which mail-order firms have a price advantage that is greater than the actual profit margins of these community businesses,'' said gov. george sinner of north dakota
sinner, speaking for his fellow governors, urged a house judiciary subcommittee to give the states authority to tax mail-order sales to out-of-state customers
that authority was wiped out by a 1967 supreme court ruling. the court held that a state could not require a mail-order seller to collect sales tax if the company's only contacts with the state were in mailing catalogs and delivering merchandise by mail or public package service
as a result, such giant mail-order companies as maine-based l.l. bean can sell by mail to the other 49 states for prices on which no taxes are collected. the decision does not affect companies such as sears, which have outlets in every state
representatives of state and local governments say they are losing more than $2 billion in sales taxes each year because of the inability to collect on sales by out-of-state catalog companies, television shopping clubs and the like
a house ways and means subcommittee already has approved a bill by rep. byron dorgan, d-n.d., that would allow states to require large out-of-state retailers to collect the tax. similar bills are pending before the judiciary subcommittee on commercial law
rep. jack brooks, d-texas, a judiciary member, said his bill would allow a state to require a retailer to collect sales tax only if the company regularly solicits sales in that state. it would apply only to companies whose annual gross receipts exceed $12.5 million or whose sales in a state exceed $500,000
william j. park, president of george w. park seed co., inc., greenwood, s.c., opposed the bills. he said his company's average mail order is $32 which, assuming a sales tax averaging 5 percent nationwide, would generate a $1.60 tax
it would be prohibitive to collect the estimated tax of $1.60 if the customers did not voluntarily send it. we certainly could not afford to pay it ourselves,'' park said, adding that his company averaged an after-tax net return of 3.5 percent last year
mayor bob isaac of colorado springs, colo., speaking for the national league of cities, said representatives of state and local governments are close to agreeing on how to divide revenues from mail-order tax collections among affected states, cities and counties. such an agreement is essential, he said
isaac said he does not take lightly a concern expressed by some state officials about being ordered by congress to channel some tax revenues down to cities and counties. but a reading of the supreme court sales-tax decision ``provides the rationale for concluding that such a requirement does not amount to an interference with a state's prerogative,'' isaac said
the head of the environmental protection agency has banned use of the insecticide diazinon on golf courses and sod farms because it kills too many birds, the agency said today
the decision by administrator lee m. thomas overrules an administrative law judge, who on jan. 25 found that the benefits of using diazinon outweighed the risks and recommended continued use under certain restrictions
the decision, effective on publication in the federal register in a few days, represents the first time that the use of a pesticide has been canceled solely because it killed birds, said spokesman al heier. however, the harm to birds was a large part of the reasons behind the 1972 ban on ddt
about 8 million pounds of diazinon are used each year to control insects on farms, in nurseries and around homes and gardens as well as on golf courses and sod farms. the two banned uses account for about 572,000 pounds
in september 1986, the agency announced intent to cancel golf course and sod farm use. at the time, it said it knew of 60 instances in 18 states where diazinon was a known or suspected cause of large-scale bird killings. many involved golf courses, which some species favor as feeding sites
four hundred ninety-four companies hold federal licenses to sell diazinon products. the major manufacturer is ciba-geigy corp
suzy says ... revson's a rat
but _ why should we care?
well, that's entertainment in the world of new york gossip
new york post columnist suzy, it seems, is just a little, eentsy bit miffed over a column by her upstart rival in new york newsday, james revson
revson wrote last week that he was ``a bit heartbroken'' to find that _ horrors _ suzy had written about a posh party at the metropolitan museum without attending it
specifically, revson wrote, ``suzy ticked off the names of 32 well-known people who, she wrote, had attended the party. ... well, there's a sad truth here. not one of those boldfaced folks showed up at the museum. none. zero. zilch.''
suzy (who actually has two real names, aileen mehle) wasn't pleased
yes, suzy admitted in today's column, she used a press release to write about the party in advance so she could slip away for ``a little vacation on the beautiful, windswept isle of mustique in the caribbean. it was heaven.''
and yes, she said, it's true that some of the people she said were at the party never showed up, even though they were listed in the press release
and yes, she said, ``i should have yanked the whole thing or at least the names the release said would attend.''
but is suzy contrite? not on your life
i bow in accuracy and meticulousness and decency to no one,'' she wrote. ``that is the reason i have survived as a star all these long years _ that and because in my field i am the best and the brightest there is
and dear readers, fans and publicity-seekers, i would like to go on record as telling the world that any place ... revson is, i will not be. do not invite me anywhere if you invite him. just call it a boycott _ or even a suzycott.''
revson's column made such a splash that even the august times took notice, printing a story and a picture of revson
not only did revson show himself to be a rat, suzy said today, he gave himself away as ``malicious, sneaky, ugly-mean.''
