orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods fell 0.8 percent in february, the second consecutive monthly decline, the government reported today
the commerce department said orders for durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent january decline
the february drop was the largest since a 1.4 percent setback in august. the back-to-back declines were the first consecutive drops since the summer of 1986
but analysts said they were not overly concerned about the setbacks, contending that manufacturing will still be one of the top performing sectors this year
the factory data followed a pair of upbeat economic reports released tuesday, which combined with a more stable dollar and lower interest rates to lift the stock market out of its slump
the government reported tuesday that its chief economic forecasting gauge, the index of leading indicators, posted a 0.9 percent increase in february in a performance which analysts said should lay to rest fears of a 1988 recession
there also was good news on sales of new homes. they shot up 20.3 percent in february _ the biggest monthly gain in almost two years _ after falling for three straight months
the positive economic reports helped spark a broad-based rally in stocks. the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 18.57 points to 1,998.34, following steep declines last thursday and friday and a slight gain monday
about 13 stocks rose in value for every six that fell on the new york stock exchange, with 1,015 up, 467 down and 482 unchanged
the dollar surged upward from its lowest point since early january, jumping to 125.26 japanese yen in late new york trading from 123.84 yen late monday
interest rates declined, meanwhile, as bond prices rose. the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond jumped about ~ point, or $8.75 for every $1,000 in face value. its yield, which moves inversely to its price, tumbled to 8.75 percent from 8.83 percent late monday
weakness in home sales and in the leading indicators in the months following the oct. 19 stock market crash had raised fears that the 5-year-old economic recovery was in imminent danger of collapsing
housing is often the first sector to weaken in a new downturn and the index of leading indicators is designed to forecast turning points in the economy. for that reason, the february rebounds in both were greeted as good news by economists. pvs, ``he also said...</note>
jesse jackson huddled today with the top ranks of washington's political establishment, a summit meeting one participant called ``a bonding of the democratic party'' with the preacher-turned-politician
with such party luminaries as clark clifford and john white at his side, the democratic presidential candidate said the meeting was totally positive. clifford and white denied there were discussions of fears that jackson could drag the party's ticket down in the fall
no, not at all,'' said white, a former chairman of the democratic national committee, told reporters after the meeting
we only see that in the press,'' said california assembly speaker willie brown, jackson's national campaign chairman. ``maybe people don't want to say that in front of us.''
jackson said the breakfast session was ``bringing together democrats who have traditional investment in the interests of the country and the party and those who are new to the process
in this instance, we bring together old wineskins and new wine, but the old wineskins are expanding and making room for new wine,'' he added, using one of his favorite phrases from the 1984 campaign
jackson picked up the backing of white
this meeting is a new maturing of the political process in america,'' white said. ``it represents a growing-up of america. it represents a bonding of the democratic party and a bond that recognizes no class.''
the one negative that came up at the meeting, according to participants, was a question to jackson about his relationship with black muslim leader louis farrakhan
white said jackson ``quoted jesus about casting the first stone and forgiveness and so anybody who hasn't made mistakes...let's not be casting stones at each other about the past.''
farrakhan campaigned with jackson early in the 1984 campaign, but the tie was cut after the black muslim leader called judaism as ``gutter religion'' and called adolf hitler ``a great man.''
many of those attending were already jackson supporters, including former federal budget director bert lance, texas agriculture commissioner jim hightower and brown
jackson's campaign manager, gerald austin, said attendance did not indicate they were endorsing jackson, but it would give them a chance to get to know him
a lot more people want to talk to jesse jackson now than they did a week ago,'' he said in reference to jackson's big win in michigan on saturday
the victory was followed tuesday by an equally big loss in connecticut to massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
jackson, however, hailed connecticut as a victory anyway, because he got 70,000 votes. he said that showed his campaign is expanding
he also said he would not react to the sharp criticism leveled at him tuesday by rival albert gore jr., but instead would ``let the people speak.''
in the first harsh attack by a jackson rival, gore, the senator from tennessee, said jackson has a ``complete and total lack of experience in the national government. he hasn't served a single day in the national government, or had a single day's experience in foreign policy.''
answering questions in new york, gore added, ``i also cannot disagree more with jesse jackson's views on many foreign policy issues. i categorically reject his notion that there's a moral equivalence between israel and the plo. ... and i am dismayed by his embrace of arafat and castro.''
jackson said he was unaware of ``any organized `stop jackson' movement'' but that in the face of his success, some democrats ``are reacting with a sense of history, others are reacting with a sense of hysteria.''
the most prominent non-candidate, new york gov. mario cuomo, said it was wrong to talk of a ``stop jackson'' movement
i reject the suggestion that it somehow presents us with a dilemma if jesse jackson wins,'' said cuomo. ``the person who gets the most votes should be the candidate and all talk of introducing somebody to stop gore, to stop dukakis or to stop jackson, that's all equally wrong.''
today's meeting, according to white, was set up even before the michigan contest
he said jackson had indicated an interest in ``meeting with the party regulars and talking about the parts of the political world he might not be familiar with.''
ann lewis, an adviser to jackson said, ``the original idea was to get jesse together with the washington establishment ... to listen to them talk about issues and policies and then to answer any questions they might have about him.'' strike</head> opening, government saying banks to reopen. no pickup</note>
the nation's three largest supermarket chains reopened their stores today, signaling a major rupture in a 10-day general strike aimed at toppling strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega
the government announced that the nation's banks, closed since march 3 because of a cash shortage brought on by u.s. economic sanctions, would reopen thursday with limited service
it announced tight restrictions on withdrawals from savings and checking accounts
the gago, rey and super 99 markets in the capital were doing brisk business after panamanians rushed to buy food and essentials that have been virtually unattainable
the weakening of the strike came two days after a harsh crackdown on leaders of the national civic crusade, which is leading the anti-noriega fight. more than 20 crusade directors were arrested monday in a raid by soldiers and state security agents. most were detained overnight, then released
owners of the reopened stores could not be reached for comment. crusade leaders, who vowed to continue the strike until noriega left panama, have been reluctant to talk since their arrests. some of those not detained were said to be in hiding
the roman catholic church tuesday joined opposition leaders in calling for noriega's resignation. but noriega, leader of the 15,000-member defense forces and the power behind the civilian government, said tuesday night he had no intention of stepping down
here, it is not one man who is the problem,'' said noriega, who blames his problems on what he considers a u.s. slander campaign against him. ``this is a matter of dignity and conviction involving the entire hemisphere.''
in a speech to delegates of a solidarity with panama conference in the capital, noriega condemned the presence of the u.s. helicopter carrier okinawa on the pacific end of the panama canal. it passed through the canal tuesday on its way to its home port, san diego
the u.s. defense department said in washington that the passage was ``routine.'' but noriega called it ``a threat and an aggression.'' there was no immediate indication how long the vessel would stay in the area
noriega claimed the united states had spent more than $100 million in the effort to topple him. ``but with all the gold in the world they have not been able to bring this people or this commander or these defense forces to their knees,'' he said, shaking his fist to wild applause
delegates from about 25 latin american and caribbean countries attended the conference, but few represented governments. about 400 spectators were on hand in the convention center
noriega's forces used a harsh irritant sprayed from water cannons, tear gas and birdshot to break up a march monday by 10,000 anti-government protesters. many people were beaten with rubber hoses and dozens were arrested
almost all those detained were released by tuesday. but carlos gonzalez de la lastra, a top leader of the opposition national civil crusade, was still held at a military intelligence center early today
he had not been allowed access to a lawyer or visits by family members
we're worried. we have been told by sources in the defense forces that he has been beaten,'' his wife vilma, told the associated press
gonzalez de la lastra apparently was not released with the others because he had been out on bond on a previous sedition charge
a church spokesman told a news conference on tuesday that panama city archbishop monsignor marcos mcgrath contacted noriega and the opposition and the archbishop had ``a positive impression'' about prospects for mediation
but the spokesman, auxiliary archbishop mons. oscar brown, said there's still a lot to be done, ``and because of that we cannot have an excessive optimism.''
in a statement, the church said a committee of bishops met with noriega last week and asked him ``to separate himself from his position as soon as possible.'' the statement said noriega failed to respond to the request
this critical phase of panama's 10-month-old political and economic crisis began feb. 26, when noriega orchestrated the ouster of president eric delvalle. hours earlier, delvalle had tried to fire noriega, who has been indicted in the united states on drug-trafficking charges
the reagan administration continues to recognize delvalle, who is in hiding, as president. it has frozen panamanian government funds in u.s. banks, denying this country a supply of its official currency, the u.s. dollar
indian peacekeeping troops killed 11 tamil rebels, captured three others and recovered 17 ak-47 automatic rifles from a hideout in the jungles of north central sri lanka, officials said today
sri lankan military officials, who cannot be identified under briefing rules, said the attack late tuesday was in mankulam, near the district capital of anuradhpura, about 105 miles northeast of colombo. it came after rebels killed 10 sinhalese farmers in the region
the sri lankan government, meanwhile, announced a ban on all meetings opposing elections in four of the island's nine provinces
the cabinet discussed a report that certain political parties were planning to hold meetings exhorting the people not to vote in the elections,'' an announcement by the information ministry said
as this is an undemocratic step and may lead to public unrest in those areas, it was decided that no permission for such meetings should be granted by the police,'' it said
the elections are scheduled for april 28 and 436 candidates from three parties are running for 155 seats. sri lanka freedom party, the largest opposition party, is boycotting the polls and demanding the government hold general elections
the attack in north central sri lanka came after suspected tamil militants tuesday planted a bomb on a passenger bus in the same area, killing 10 sinhalese farmers and injuring 15 others
the haul of ak-47 rifles is regarded as the largest single haul of the this type of weaponry by the indian troops,'' a military official said
more than 50,000 indian troops are in sri lanka to disarm tamil militants under a peace accord signed last july. the accord grants some autonomy to minority tamils living in the north and east but it has been opposed both by tamil and sinhalese extremists
tamils say it does not give enough autonomy while sinhalese nationalists claim it grants too many concessions to the tamils
in another incident, sri lankan police today opened fire ``at a mob of more than 2,000 people who tried to storm the trincomalee police station and a nearby army camp,'' a military official reported
three policemen were seriously injured and many in the mob were wounded, the official said. trincomalee is an important port town in the eastern province
the crowd was demanding the release of all tamil political prisoners and withdrawal from the area of sri lankan security forces. the security forces are protecting sinhalese settlements in the east
more than 135 sinhalese civilians have been killed this month in attacks blamed on tamil militants of the liberation tigers of tamil eelam. the group is the largest and most powerful rebel organization
the government says the rebels are launching these attacks to drive out sinhalese and moslems from the eastern province and establish complete dominance. tamils say the government has deliberately settled sinhalese people in the area to upset the tamils traditional majority in the area
tamils, who are mainly hindu, make up about 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people while the sinhalese, who are buddhists, comprise 75 percent
tamils say they are discriminated against by the sinhalese, who control the government and the military
a court reporter for the federal judge who sentenced millionaire industrialist victor posner in a tax evasion case has been in contact with posner's organization for a job, the judge said in court today
u.s. district judge eugene p. spellman, visibly perturbed, said he first learned of conversations between court reporter mario contillo and posner on monday afternoon
i'm not saying his conduct was illegal, but i feel it was reprehensible, especially involving a friend of 30 years,'' said spellman, referring to contillo, who the judge said was offered ``a substantial amount'' to work for posner. details of the job were not disclosed in court
posner pleaded no contest sept. 29 to evading more than $1.2 million in federal taxes by inflating the value of land he donated to a bible college as a tax exemption
posner, who had faced up to 40 years in prison in an income tax evasion case, was ordered to pay more than $4 million in back taxes and fines and to give $3 million to help florida's homeless in an income tax evasion case
the miami beach businessman, whose holdings include controlling interests in royal crown cola and arby's, also was sentenced to 5,000 hours in community service over five years
spellman called u.s. attorney leon kellner, assistant u.s. attorney neal cartusciello, who prosecuted the case, and mary clark, an attorney for posner, to a special hearing in his courtroom to discuss his findings
contillo announced last friday that he was giving up his court position, spellman said. spellman said he wanted kellner to ``to evaluate and comment if he wishes,'' on the disclosure
i don't know all the facts but i felt that as a member of the federal judiciary it was incumbent upon me to draw attention to this matter so it could be made public as quickly as possible,'' the judge said
when i found out, i went through a series of emotions ... distress and outrage ... that a member of my staff is guilty at the very least of impropriety,'' he said
efforts by the associated press to reach contillo at his office or at home by telephone today were unsuccessful. renee mottram, a spokeswoman for posner, said that contillo is not employed by posner at this time
spellman said the job conversations took place sometime after the feb. 12 sentencing of posner
posner's 1986 conviction was set aside because of jury irregularities, and he entered the no contest plea a month before he was to be retried
spellman said today it was his understanding that the court reporter gave the impression the judge condoned his job discussions, but the judge said, ``i had no knowledge of the conversations and i do not condone them.''
the judge noted that the 69-year-old posner is on probation and said: ``i have not taken this up with probation service. if they feel that mr. posner violated his probation, they have the means to bring it to the court's attention
i have no reason to believe it was other than an unthinking and stupid act.''
after the judge left the bench, kellner was asked if he intended to bring the actions to the attention of a grand jury
i am hearing this for the first time as you are. all i can say is we will take a look at it.'' up in 12th graf pvs, with 100</note>
michael dukakis celebrated his 2-to-1 connecticut primary victory over jesse jackson today as jackson met with democratic party elders and dismissed his tuesday loss as merely due to the massachusetts governor's ``home field advantage'' in new england
george bush, with the gop nomination all but in hand, called on republicans to ``keep together and get to work.'' bush won overwhelmingly in connecticut _ as he had been expected to do even before principal rival bob dole dropped out of the race on primary day
jackson met privately in washington with leaders of the party establishment, then said afterward, ``in this instance, we bring together old wineskins and new wine, but the old wineskins are expanding and making room for new wine.''
participants said the meeting was positive all around, with no discussion of reports that some democrats fear nominating jackson would lead to crushing defeat in the general election
we only see that in the press,'' said california assembly speaker willie brown, a jackson supporter. ``maybe people don't want to say that in front of us.''
democrat albert gore jr., who finished a distant third in connecticut, said today while campaigning in wisconsin that he expected no backlash from the comments he made tuesday about what he said was jackson's ``complete and total lack'' of the experience needed to be president
other candidates have been slow to criticize jackson, but gore said his own comments ``were really not that different from what i've been saying for several months.''
dukakis, on nbc-tv, said of the connecticut primary, ``we won with a big, big margin, but it's not the first of my victories.''
but this is a marathon and it's going to be all the way to the finish line. i'm just very pleased that people who know me best were so supportive,'' he said
jackson, who has beaten dukakis in two states in the last two weeks _ michigan and illinois _ congratulated the massachusetts governor but suggested geography and campaign finances played a key role
you did well with your home field advantage,'' said jackson, who also appeared on the nbc program
sen. paul simon, who barely contested connecticut, made the same point tuesday night. ``we assumed this was dukakis territory,'' he said
with 100 percent of the connecticut precincts reporting, dukakis had 58 percent to jackson's 28 percent. gore trailed with 8 percent, and simon had 1 percent
that restored dukakis' lead in the national delegate race. the latest ap count put dukakis at 647.55; jackson at 634.55 and uncommitted at 500.6. gore had 364.8 and simon 169.5
jackson swept the black vote and won about 20 percent of the white vote, according to television network exit polls. his share of the white vote was put at 5 percent in 1984
however, primary-day surveys of voters by wnbc-tv in new york suggested only one-fifth of the democrats believed the nation was ready to elect a black president. abc found that one-third of the democrats would switch to the republican side if jackson were nominated
only last week dukakis was suggesting he was the inevitable democratic nominee. now he is saying he expects a long duel with jackson
this is 15 rounds and it's going to be a decision, not a knockout,'' he said tuesday night. ``it's going all the way to the final round.''
some party heavyweights may have come to the same conclusion. jackson was meeting in washington today with the front rank of the democratic establishment to discuss issues and policy
former party chairman john white, who set up the ``summit,'' said it would allow jackson to talk with democratic leaders about ``the parts of the political world he might not be familiar with.''
jackson came under fire tuesday from gore, in the first serious attack on him by a democratic opponent. gore said jackson has a ``complete and total lack'' of experience needed to be president
we're not choosing a preacher, we're choosing a president,'' the tennessee senator said. jackson retorted: ``i assume that he is stimulated by his own status in the campaign to attack me.''
the exchange came as the two were in new york, jockeying for position in new york's delegate-heavy contest on april 19. gore was in wisconsin today, making an early-morning visit to a dairy farm where he was to milk cows and do farm chores
on the republican side, dole's departure left bush with only a nominal opponent _ former television evangelist pat robertson, who acknowledged, ``it seems obvious now that george bush will be the winner.''
as the kansas senator bowed out tuesday, he put aside his differences with the vice president
i return to the senate as the republican leader ... ready to do all i can to elect republicans in november and doing all i can for our nominee, george bush,'' he said. bush beat dole by a lopsided 71-20 margin in connecticut
if dole's delegates _ now in the uncommitted column _ go to bush, the vice president is likely to clinch the delegates needed to nominate in the next few weeks
with the republican nomination a nearly done deal, republicans were holding the first of three platform hearings today, this one on foreign policy and defense. gop chairman frank fahrenkopf and the president's daughter, maureen reagan, were among those attending
rep. richard gephardt, who dropped out of the democratic race on monday, filed tuesday for re-election to his house seat from missouri, saying he was somewhat relieved to have life return to a more usual pace
now we can go to the drug store and the movies and be fairly normal,'' he said
the senate foreign relations committee, by a vote of 17-2, today gave its approval to the historic treaty eliminating u.s. and soviet medium-range nuclear missiles
the vote sends the treaty to the full senate, which is expected to vote next month after returning from its easter recess. leaders of both parties say the treaty will win far more than the two-thirds margin it needs to be ratified
but some republicans said today the pact may be in jeopardy because of a democratic-backed amendment outlining how the treaty can be interpreted by the white house. the only dissenting votes today were cast by sens. jesse helms, r-n.c., and larry pressler, r-s.d
the treaty, signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev, requires both sides to desroy, within three years, all nuclear-tipped missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles. it will be the first nuclear arms control pact requiring the destruction of weapons
sen. rudy boschwitz, r-minn., said the democratic amendment was ``perhaps unconstitutional and very frankly, it may change my position with respect to the treaty'' on the floor. but boschwitz supported the pact in today's vote
pressler predicted the amendment ``will lead to the defeat of this treaty because the votes aren't there.''
but sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., the panel's chairman, said ``the amendment's importance has been exaggerated'' and predicted its eventual approval by the full senate
sen. paul sarbanes, d-md., called the pact ``a very important step forward'' for the united states
sen. alan cranston, d-calif., agreed. ``in effect, this is a small step away from the nuclear brink,'' he told his colleagues
today's vote came a day after the amendment was added, a move that left some committee republicans angry and threatening to oppose the treaty when it comes to the floor
this has been made partisan, unnecessarily in my view,'' sen. daniel evans, r-wash, said tuesday. ``no one has worked harder for this treaty than me, but i'm now going to seriously take a look at whether i can vote for it.''
evans and other republicans were unhappy about the democratic-written provision, which was added to the measure with the help of helms
the provision says no future president can change the u.s. interpretation of the treaty without the approval of congress, either through a new pact or through a separate law
the measure arises from a longstanding fight between reagan and congress over reagan's assertion that the executive branch can unilaterally change how the u.s. government interprets a treaty. congressional democrats disagree with that statement, which reagan has used to justify some tests of his star wars missile defense system
the tests would violate the original interpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
democrats want assurances that reagan or another president won't assert the same right to re-interpret treaties on the intermediate-range nuclear forces pact
sen. richard lugar, r-ind., said reagan already has agreed not to change the u.s. view of the inf treaty and said the proposal ``is a deliberate attempt to embarrass the president.''
but sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., told lugar, ``those of us on this side did not begin this process,'' a reference to reagan's assertion involving executive branch rights on treaty interpretation
helms said he offered his amendment, which he said made minor changes in the democratic-written proposal, to make sure the democratic measure was constitutional
but lugar was suspicious. ``i frankly don't know at all what this is about. i'm sure something important is going on,'' he said, but ``i don't have any idea.''
earlier in the day, the senate met in a rare secret session to talk about intelligence estimates about the size of the soviets' force of ss-20 missiles, which will be destroyed under the treaty
the soviets have admitted to having 650 of the weapons, but helms and other conservative critics argue that u.s. intelligence estimates show that the soviets may possess up to 1,000. administration officials dispute that contention
the secret session was the senate's first since october 1986. it was held in the old senate chamber, down the capitol hall from the current senate meeting place. the current chamber was unusable because it is laced with electronic cables that could be tapped
helms said later that his colleagues, ``heard some things they hadn't heard before.'' court's decision.</note>
federal funding aimed at discouraging sexual activity by teen-agers is valid despite the ``constitutionally troublesome'' ways some religious groups spent the money, the reagan administration told the supreme court today
saying that congress passed the 1981 law ``in response to grave social, economic and health costs'' linked to teen-age pregnancies, solicitor general charles fried said, ``in our view, the statute is plainly constitutional on its face.''
but fried, the justice department's highest-ranking courtroom lawyer, conceded that some of the millions of dollars spent under the law each year may have gone to promote religion
i do not dispute that there may have been some departures'' from past high court rulings on church-state relations, fried said, adding that some of those departures are ``constitutionally troublesome.''
janet benshoof, an american civil liberties union lawyer representing those who successfully challenged the law in a lower court, was asked by justice antonin scalia whether congress was empowered to authorize self-restraint among adolescents
benshoof replied, ``yes, but you can't do it by telling young girls to pretend that jesus is their date.''
at issue is whether the 1981 law impermissibly promotes religion because religious organizations obtain money under it
the court's decision is expected by july
urged on by conservative republicans, congress allowed religious groups to obtain money for programs designed to prevent adolescent pregnancy by promoting self-discipline and to mitigate problems caused by premarital sex and teen-age pregnancy
aclu lawyers, representing those who challenged the law, said it ``authorizes the use of federal funds to subsidize religious indoctrination as a means of opposing premarital sex, abortion and birth control for teen-agers.''
a federal judge here agreed, and struck down the law last year
the law, officially called the adolescent family life act but dubbed the ``chastity act'' by its opponents, has three general program categories _ care, prevention and research
care services'' include pregnancy testing, maternity counseling, adoption and referral help
prevention services'' are those aimed at discouraging adolescent sexual relations, and include programs offering counseling and family planning
the law requires programs applying for federal funding to describe how, in providing services, they will ``involve religious and charitable organizations, voluntary associations and other groups in the private sector.''
although finding that the law has a secular or non-religious purpose, u.s. district judge charles richey said it has ``the primary effect of advancing religion and fosters an excessive entanglement between government and religion.''
he noted that the law ``explicitly permits religious organizations to be grantees, and envisions a direct role for those organizations in the education and counseling components of afla grants.''
the case is bowen vs. kendrick, 87-253, 87-431, 87-462, and 87-775. leaving late april and ceremony in may, sted she leaving in march and ceremony in april.</note>
after the deaths of milton and matilda, two musk oxen given to china by the united states in 1972, a georgia widow began a one-person campaign to replace them
next month, helen miller travels to beijing for a ceremony marking the success of her efforts and the arrival of two new animals
mrs. miller said she learned that just as pandas ling-ling and hsing-hsing _ gifts from china _ had become popular at the national zoo in washington, millions of chinese children visited the beijing zoo to see the oxen
so in 1980, after learning that the oxen had died, she began a letter-writing campaign to the white house, the national zoo and officials of the u.s. fish and wildlife service
she felt it was a matter of ``national honor'' to replace the animals that had been presented when then-president richard nixon made his historic trip to china as the two nations normalized relations
i don't just think about things,'' she said in a recent interview. ``if they are worth thinking about, they are worth acting on.''
musk oxen, found only in greenland and arctic regions of north america, have heavy fur coats and horns that dip down along their heads and then up. hunted for years, they now are protected
mrs. miller eventually learned that the university of alaska had a herd of the oxen and went there. university officials agreed to donate koyuk and tanana, a pair flown to china on march 21
the chinese are very excited about it,'' said mrs. miller, who departs in late april. ``there's going to be a big presentation ceremony. it took a long time, but it was interesting every step of the way.''
the ceremony, in early may, will be attended by u.s. officials, the governor of alaska and the head of the university of alaska's school of arctic biology, she said
mrs. miller's husband, gibbs, died in 1960, leaving her with four children. after attending vocational school, she got a job as a construction estimator
i like to do things that no one else will do,'' said mrs. miller
she has been a contestant on four tv game shows, winning a brazilian vacation, two cars, a 65-foot mobile home and two furs. three of her children also have appeared on game shows
now that the oxen are in china, mrs. miller has a new project, but for now it's a secret
you put your heart in it and go to work,'' she said.``if you believe in something strongly enough, then put feet on your prayers.'' details on clash. pick up 7th pvs, `in the...' edits thereafter to trim.</note>
hundreds of arab protesters fought israeli troops today in defiance of a massive clampdown in the occupied territories. hospital officials said two palestinians were killed and 24 wounded
the army confirmed one death and said three people were wounded on land day, an annual demonstration against israeli confiscation of arab land
the west bank and gaza strip were closed, and thousands of extra police and soldiers were deployed. six arabs were killed in the first land day protests 12 years ago
police swept through the offices of a key arab news service and ordered it closed for six months
a supreme court panel denied a foreign press request to allow media access to the occupied territories, but it ordered the army to explain within 30 days why journalists should not be allowed free access
only the territories' 65,000 jewish settlers were permitted to travel freely
in beit sahour near bethlehem in the west bank, troops clashed with about 200 protesters who pelted them with rocks, waved outlawed palestinian flags and set tires ablaze
an associated press reporter in the village saw roadblocks of boulders, rusted barrels, twisted metal and garbage blocking dozens of winding streets. four tires smouldered nearby and hundreds of baseball sized rocks littered the streets
in the west bank village of deir abu mashal, 20 miles northwest of jerusalem, soldiers killed a woman and wounded her husband and two sons
the army and hospital officials gave conflicting accounts
doctors at ramallah hospital told the associated press troops entered the home of wajalah rabir, 50, while she and her family were eating breakfast and fatally shot her in the head
a visitor to the hospital quoted mrs. rabir's 17-year-old daughter, zeinab, as saying the soldiers came in and asked if there were any men in the house
the girl told the troops no men were home, but they entered anyway, the visitor said. the visitor, who spoke on condition of anonymity, quoted the girl as saying a soldier then shot one brother who started to run. other family members then lunged toward the troops, who opened fire
hospital officials said mrs. rabir's husband and two sons were in serious condition from gunshot wounds. the officials, who have been barred from speaking to journalists, insisted on anonymity
the army said the woman was shot after she attacked a soldier with a rake. ``all those hurt were hurt during a very aggressive attack on our soldiers,'' the commander said on israel radio. ``they attacked with pitchforks, axes, clubs and metal bars in a very aggressive way.''
officials at nablus' al ittihad hospital said another palestinian, khalid salah, 22, died of a gunshot wound to the back during a clash with troops in the nearby village of burqa. they said another arab was wounded in the shoulder in that clash
the army said it was investigating the death which, according to u.n. figures, brought to 121 the number of palestinians killed by soldiers since unrest broke out in the territories on dec. 8. one israeli soldier has been killed
hospital officials said 24 palestinians were wounded by gunfire, including a 12-year-old girl near hebron
in east jerusalem, police officers swept into the arab-owned palestine press service and ordered it closed for six months
ibrahim kareen, publisher of the service, said police told him the agency was being closed because it was funded by the palestine liberation organization. he denied plo funding and vowed to continue providing information
all we need is a telephone,'' kareen said
an extra 4,000 police were stationed in israel's arab sectors
telephone lines to gaza remained severed, troops warned on loudspeakers that curfew violators would be shot, and gaza and the west bank were closed to most outside traffic
reporters were barred from entering the territories without a previously arranged army escort, and army spokeswoman ofra preuss said violators would be prosecuted
the maximum penalty for entering a closed military area is five years in prison
a general strike was observed in israel's arab towns, east jerusalem and the west bank. dozens of mounted police and foot patrols moved through east jerusalem's main salah edin street. graf pvs, ``my friends</note>
senate republican leader bob dole told president reagan today ``i'm reporting back for duty,'' one day after giving up his bid for the gop presidential nomination
dole met privately with reagan at the white house and didn't comment as he left. but white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters of the comment made to reagan by dole, who had campaigned as the man who helped steer reagan programs through the senate
one day earlier, dole, who for one winter week looked like a good bet for the nomination, ended his quest for the white house, as much the victim of his own campaign's shortcomings as of george bush's success
my friends know that i am a fighter; i don't like to lose,'' the senate republican leader said in bowing to the inevitable tuesday. ``i have been beaten before, and no doubt will be again. but i have never been defeated and never will be.''
in an ad-libbed addition to his prepared speech, dole promised to do ``all i can for our nominee, george bush.''
bush, with an insurmountable delegate lead, called dole while campaigning in wisconsin to thank him for a ``very generous statement.'' he added, ``it's been a hard-fought campaign and i respect the tenacity of bob dole.''
only pat robertson remains in the gop race as a stubborn challenger to bush. robertson conceded ``it seems obvious'' that bush would be the nominee but said he won't withdraw as a candidate
dole formally withdrew surrounded by family and friends in the senate caucus room, scene of watergate and iran-contra hearings. a supportive audience of senate and house colleagues jammed the room
also present were two former senior aides to the campaign, david keene and don devine, who because of the public manner of their firings were reminders of the dole campaign's internal divisions and ineptitude
dole's withdrawal must have been painful for a candidate who, in the glow of his lead-off victory in iowa, could see the nomination almost within his grasp
he benefited in that farm state from his rural, humble roots in neighboring kansas, and the contrast with the patrician bush. his victory in the nation's first delegate contest left bush a stunned third-place finisher behind dole and robertson
for the next week, critics called bush a failed campaigner and dole appeared on a winner's roll. even his own pollster told dole that he would likely win new hampshire, riding a surge in popularity built on his iowa success
but the dole campaign, thinking it could coast across the finish line, did not answer tough, last-minute bush television ads that suggested dole would raise taxes
fiercely and historically opposed to taxes, new hampshire voters dealt dole a loss from which he could not recover. dole later described his failure to answer the bush ad as his big mistake
dole's campaign was beset by internal divisions and vacillation. critics said it was a reflection of dole himself, calling him a consummate legislator but lacking in an executive's ability to delegate authority or organize
after new hampshire, dole's campaign went into a tailspin. it seemed to unravel in embarrassingly full view
campaign manager bill brock, in a struggle for control, fired keene and devine as reporters watched. he ordered the two off the campaign plane in florida
dole's strategy for winning the white house had been based primarily on winning the first two contests, and when he fell short in new hampshire his candidacy collapsed
he found himself far behind bush in the southern primaries on super tuesday three weeks later. unable to focus his energies on his best opportunities, he lost everywhere. in one night, bush moved halfway to a delegate majority
dole couldn't turn the race around in illinois and was effectively out of the running
in a metaphor of his sputtering campaign, a live 30-minute television broadcast in illinois _ planned in 11th-hour desperation _ was ruined by an electronic glitch
dole was always dogged by a reputation for meanness born of his hatchet-man role as the 1976 vice presidential nominee. he was unable to shake it this time around
bitter on the night of his new hampshire loss, dole snapped at bush during a joint, live network television interview for ``lying'' about his record
he was frustrated by a feeling he still had to run against ronald reagan, the man who defeated both dole and bush in the 1980 gop race. bush, reagan's loyal vice president, inherited much of the president's support
i'm sort of running against the ghost of ronald reagan,'' dole once said
dole campaigned gamely last week in wisconsin, his campaign jet and entourage gone. but bush had a massive lead in the polls
by week's end, dole appeared to be weary of waging a campaign that was only going through the motions
one thing you learn how to do pretty well in our business is to count,'' he said in withdrawing. ``you come to trust your instincts to tell you when it's over, and in my heart i know the time is now.''
the city council unanimously approved a law requiring pit bulls to wear muzzles in public, the first of its kind in the nation
the measure, approved monday, still must be ok'd by provincial authorities
there has been a recent increase in publicity over attacks by pit bulls, which are becoming very popular in the netherlands. nationwide, there are about 6,000 of the dogs
a pit bull terrier killed a horse in the southern city of eindhoven this month, and several people have been injured in recent pit bull attacks
although written with the pit bull terrier in mind, the gouda law would order muzzling for ``a breed designated as dangerous (by the city fathers) or any of its descendants obtained by cross-breeding.''
pit bull owners convicted under the new bylaw would face a $2,600 fine
world rice stocks are expected to fall by more than 30 percent this year to about 35 million tons, the u.n. food and agriculture organization reported wednesday
a report by the fao's intergovernmental group on rice said the change in the world rice market from one of surplus to limited supplies and rising prices was due largely to adverse climactic conditions
it also said some countries had adopted measures to reduce output
the fao group warned that another year of falling output could cause serious food security problems
the reduction in rice stocks was described as ``particularly acute'' in major producing countries in the developing world, such as china, india, bangladesh, burma, indonesia, malaysia, pakistan, thailand and sri lanka
in the united states, stocks were forecast to fall by more than 50 percent to 800,000 tons by the end of 1988
a nigerian plane coming to collect a cargo of cows overshot the runway after landing at a danish airfield, police said wednesday
one person was injured and the dc-8 was badly damaged when it slid about 100 yards off the runway in the town of billund on tuesday, said acting police commissioner bjarne jensen said
the plane, carrying eight crew members, was to transport cattle to egypt, he said. the cause of the accident was not known
the third installment of a four-part easter series, ``strangers no longer,'' concerns with the protestant-catholic convergence toward unity, dealing with official dialogues
from across christianity's denominational spectrum, reactions to a proposal for unity have poured into the headquarters of the world council of churches in geneva, switzerland
the response has been tremendous,'' said the rev. gunther gassman, a lutheran and director of the council's faith and order commission, an inclusive protestant-roman catholic-eastern orthodox unit that is compiling the appraisals
it's a unique thing in the history of the ecumenical movement,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``never has there been so much interest and discussion of a church document throughout the world.''
roman catholic, protestant and eastern orthodox denominations, 170 of them from around the globe, have sent official responses to an agreement jointly produced by their thinkers on a reintegrated faith
bem,'' it's called, standing for the central aspects of baptism, eucharist (celebrating the lord's supper) and ministry
sometimes called the ``lima text,'' it was produced by a commission of 120 theologians, bible scholars, historians, clergy and lay leaders at a meeting in lima, peru, in 1982
we have become increasingly aware of our unity in the body of christ,'' they said. ``sadly divided churches have been enabled to arrive at substantial theological agreements. we believe many significant advances are now possible.''
to that end, bem circulated among the churches for five years, translated into 35 languages. after pondering, the denominations have now voiced their assessment, the broadest ever attained in an ecumenical accord
it's a towering achievement,'' said the rev. john hotchkin, ecumenical officer for u.s. catholic bishops. ``it could serve to put a new floor under the ecumenical movement. it's a very important landmark.''
the vatican also appraised the document, generally commending the results, but asked for further elaborations, especially on the ministry
the responses are being distributed to the churches in six volumes, with the last two still to be compiled. a summary will be considered by the joint commission at a meeting in august 1989, and any clarifications and adaptations will be taken care of before the final document is presented to churches by 1991
then it's up to them,'' gassman said. ``our strong hope is that they act on it in the next 10 years, initiating some form of eucharistic sharing. many of them are ready to do so now.''
bem offers concordant beliefs about key functions of the church, drawing on common biblical roots and christianity's centuries prior to the 1054 schism that separated rome and eastern orthodoxy and the 16th-century protestant break from rome
the document challenges present-day churches to affirm this common, early core of faith. baptism of infants as well as adults is recognized, with precedents for each in practices of the early church
regarding the eucharist, the approach goes behind the medieval catholic doctrine of ``transubstantiation,'' upholding instead a broader concept of christ's ``real presence'' in celebration of the lord's supper
on the ministry, bem recommends a threefold tier of bishops, presbyters and deacons. most major churches have all three, but usually refer to presbyters as pastors, priests or ministers. some protestant bodies avoid the term bishop but have parallel overseeing offices under other titles
the responses have been as varied as the denominations. the vatican's 40-page response wasn't as long as the salvation army's 70 pages, the longest. the shortest, a half page from the presbyterian church of new zealand, simply said fine, let's go with it
we've made an enormous lot of progress in the churches' acceptance of each other,'' said the rev. john deschner, a united methodist from southern methodist university's perkins school of theology in dallas, who chairs the world council commission. ``a trust has developed among protestant, catholic and orthodox churches that is beyond what we'd ever dared hope
bem culminates the rising pleas for increased acts of mutual recognition of members and ministry, a kind of unity of mutual hospitality, welcoming each other in each other's denominational context, acknowledging each other before god.''
paving the way for bem has been a swelling profusion of dialogues and surprising accords among the denominations
on national and international levels, the bilateral talks have gone on 20 years between teams of catholics with lutherans, with methodists, with anglicans, with baptists, with disciples, with eastern orthodoxy, with presbyterians, with pentecostals, with evangelicals
at the same time, protestant bodies have met with one another, scrutinizing their respective views, seeking closer understanding and concurrence
it has become a vast, interconfessional conversation, a constant to-and-fro hum of inquiry, explanation, discovery and, often surprisingly, consensus
the talks probe the tangle of mutual misconceptions, mistaken impressions and caricatured images accumulated through centuries of alienation from one another
they seek to clear up where each really stands. on many points, it turns out to be together
for instance, lutherans and anglicans in separate dialogues with catholics determined they basically agreed on a key issue of the 16th-century protestant reformation that had divided them
protestants emphasized ``justification by faith'' alone, that salvation comes only through faith in christ's forgiving grace, and asserted that rome claimed the church dispensed grace for earned merit
but it turns out that arguments in the heat of old battle were misconstrued on both sides. they now agree _ as the u.s. lutheran-catholic team put it _ that ``our entire hope of justification and salvation rests on christ jesus'' and his forgiving grace
similarly convergent views have been found about the papacy itself, with anglicans and lutherans agreeing on the benefit of a unifying center, a presiding bishop of a pastoral rather than juridical kind, responsible to regular ecumenical councils
the deluge of dialogue reports have dealt with virtually all basic issues of churchmanship _ spirituality, scripture, apostolic succession, conversion, worship, grace, authority, the holy spirit, family, mixed marriages, salvation and papal primacy, usually with degrees of agreement
so much is happening, there is so much development that it's hard to keep up,'' said catholic brother jeffrey gros, who heads the faith and order office of the u.s. national council of churches
in a book summarizing a score of such understandings, ``growth in agreements,'' lutheran scholar harding meyer and reformed scholar lukas vischer say the dialogues ``constantly point beyond themselves,'' so the main aim no longer is ``just reaching of consensus but translation ... into practice in the living fellowship of the churches.''
many issues remain unsettled between rome and protestantism on such issues as ordination of women, which catholicism and orthodoxy forbid. but anglicans and catholics, in new talks, are discussing it
different shades of understanding, terminology and doctrinal nuances also linger, as do conflicts on social issues such as abortion and divorce, along with bureaucratic inertia
the ecumenical movement is a glacier,'' said lutheran bishop herbert w. chilstrom, head of the newly unified evangelical lutheran church in america. ``it moves slowly, but it does move.''
the court presiding over the nazi war crimes trial of retired u.s. autoworker john demjanjuk will announce its verdict on april 18, the government said wednesday
demjanjuk, 67, is accused of being ``ivan the terrible,'' the guard who operated gas chambers that killed 850,000 jews at the treblinka death camp in nazi-occupied poland
if convicted, demjanjuk could be sentenced to death. the ukrainian-born defendant claims he is a victim of mistaken identity
demjanjuk was extradited to israel in february 1986 from the cleveland suburb of seven hills
his trial ended feb. 10 after a year of testimony. the three-judge panel reopened hearings for two days in march to introduce new evidence at the request of defense attorney yoram sheftel
sheftel presented the court with statements from 12 camp survivors who did not identify demjanjuk as ``ivan.''
at the beginning of the hearings, five prosecution witnesses identified demjanjuk as the treblinka camp guard from photographs
the prosecution's key piece of evidence is an alleged ss card stating that demjanjuk was trained as a concentration camp guard. demjanjuk says the card is a forgery
edgar faure, the brilliant statesman who died wednesday at the age of 79, was hailed by friends and foes alike for his political savvy, intelligence and wit
faure occupied every important post in the french government except the presidency during a career that spanned four decades
president francois mitterrand, a fellow socialist, called faure ``a remarkable man who marked the history of our republic.''
jean-marie le pen, presidential candidate from the extreme-right national front, praised faure's ``intelligence and tolerance,'' despite ``our differing conceptions of political action.''
the bespectacled, balding father figure, known to the french simply as ``edgar,'' was best remembered as one of the nation's most progressive education ministers
under gen. charles de gaulle, during the 1968 student uprising, he masterminded vast reforms that allowed french universities more autonomy
faure was a member of the french academy and wrote books on subjects ranging from french oil policy to modern china
a renaissance man, faure even wrote musical scores. under the pseudonym edgar sanday, he published detective novels
faure was born on aug. 18, 1908, in the southwestern city of beziers, where his father, an army doctor, was stationed. he graduated from high school at the age of 15, earned his doctorate in law at 19 and was a practicing lawyer at 21
he was fluent in russian, and years later, would stun a soviet trade delegation negotiating without a translator for four hours straight, stumbling only once _ over the word ``corkscrew.''
yet he had an old-fashioned sense of honor and once challenged a prominent magazine reporter to a duel for having questioned in print his motives for reducing taxes on race horses. notoriously near-sighted, he was already waving the pistol when a colleague managed to talk him out of it
faure's successful law career was interrupted by world war ii. in 1942, faure and his wife lucie meyer, the elegant publisher of a political review, fled france for algiers
after the war, he was financial adviser to socialist governments led by his close friend pierre mendes-france
in 1947, he was elected to public office for the first time, serving as a deputy for the jura department in eastern france
from that time on, he served in the cabinets of numerous prime ministers, holding more ministerial appointments than any other public official
faure's first wife, lucie meyer, died in 1977. he is survived by his second wife, marie-jeanne vuez, and two daughters. burial will be saturday in paris following services at his church and at the national assembly
cocke county officials knew they had to come up with $345,000 quickly to keep public schools open after spring break. so they decided to sell the county-owned hospital
the deal negotiated between the county and baptist health system, which was renting the hospital, benefits everyone, but primarily prevents the nightmare of closing schools, county executive charles lewis moore said tuesday
we can't have that,'' he said. ``that's absolutely not satisfactory to anyone. one concern was that some seniors who have scholarships and financial assistance would lose it, plus it would affect employees and parents.''
the $1 million sale was approved 20-0 by the cocke county legislative body on monday night
the county lawmakers then provided the school system with $200,000, the minimum on which the schools could operate the rest of the term, and agreed to invest the remainder in an industrial park
the sale includes a 74-bed hospital, a 56-bed nursing home and a building housing three doctors' offices. baptist health system, based in knoxville, had leased the hospital since 1982, and last year extended that lease through 1999
at any point during those 17 years, baptist had the option of buying the hospital for $1.58 million, or $580,000 more than the actual sale price
but county officials say they can get roughly $3.6 million out of the deal in interest on the remaining $800,000, plus money saved because the deal exempts the county from funding care of indigents at the hospital for the next 12 years. that had been costing about $35,000 a year
county officials praised baptist health for coming to the county's rescue
we frankly had not intended to buy right now,'' said robert chandler, president of baptist health system. ``but they were having some financial problems, especially with funding the school system. so we felt we could help by buying now. helping the schools was our main motivation.''
