the evansville (ind.) courier on preventing teen suicides:
we are shocked and saddened by the three suicides involving present and former reitz high school students. yet our grief now must give way to concern
there seems no direct connection among the three, other than what experts call a copycat syndrome. one person commits suicide; another troubled individual learns of it, even sees it as an escape from despair, and the chain reaction begins
it's critical now that those closest to students _ parents, school personnel, classmates _ see that the chain is broken. ..
talk to your children, talk to your classmates, and if you're troubled yourself, seek someone who will listen _ no problem is so insurmountable
so often when we learn of suicide, we hear the word helplessness. no, we can't help those who have already taken their lives, but for others who may be troubled, we are not helpless, especially now that our consciousness has been raised so tragically
we must be alert; we must care; we must talk
if the two sides trying to force changes in the 1990 census both get their way, the results would nearly balance one another, a population expert said wednesday
the census bureau is under pressure to exclude illegal aliens from its national head count. traditionally, it counts everyone living in the country
groups which have filed suit to ignore the aliens contend large concentrations of them could result in in some states gaining seats in the house of representatives at the expense of other states
meanwhile, other groups want the final census totals to be increased to account for people who may be overlooked in the census _ most often blacks and hispanics living in urban areas
at stake are the 435 seats in the house, which are distributed among the states on the basis of population
if both sides get their way, the only change would be a flip-flop of one seat from california to georgia,'' said william o'hare, director of policy studies for the independent population reference bureau
o'hare told a breakfast briefing for northeast and midwest members of congress that he estimates their region will lose 14 house seats following the 1990 census. that would continue a trend evident over the last several decades, he noted
using estimates of the number of illegal aliens and undercounted minorities, he said that deleting the one group and adding in the other would make little difference in the long run
the only change, he said, would be that california would gain five new seats instead of six, while georgia would add two rather than just one
that's easy to understand, since there are so many undocumented aliens in california,'' he commented
o'hare's study of potential changes in house seats _ based on 1990 projections with no adjustments _ calls for california to be the big gainer, adding six house seats, followed by florida with a gain of four and texas adding three
expected to pick up one seat each are virginia, north carolina, georgia, and arizona
on the other hand new york would lose three seats. states losing two apiece would be pennsylvania, ohio, illinois and michigan. expected to lose one house seat are massachusetts, wisconsin, iowa, kansas, west virginia and montana
two mixed-breed dogs attacked a seeing eye dog, causing trauma that may make the $10,000 animal useless as a guide, its owner said
ollie, an australian shepherd owned by linda watson, 34, will be off his feet for about two weeks with bite wounds to the left front leg and neck. his life was saved tuesday by two passersby who kicked and beat the attacking dogs with a wrench and broom until they gave up
ms. watson and a co-worker were walking during their lunch break when ollie was attacked
when they were beaten off, the attacking dogs retreated into the home of their owner, joseph frances beasley, so animal-control officers couldn't impound them, said jimmy dykes, supervisor of escambia's animal shelter
but dykes said officers cited beasley for failure to have the dogs vaccinated and licensed
ms. watson said that while ollie will recover physically, the attack may make him aggressive. ``if that's the case, i've lost a dog worth $10,000,'' she said
two laboratory workers died of a rare brain infection called creutzfeldt-jakob disease, and both might have resulted from on-the-job exposure to contaminated tissue, doctors report
the cases were reported in separate letters to the editor in thursday's new england journal of medicine
in one letter, douglas c. miller of new york university medical center described the case of a 62-year-old woman who had worked in a medical lab for 22 years. her duties included preparing slices of human brains
after she died of creutzfeldt-jakob disease, doctors discovered she had worked with tissue from two people who had also died of the disease 11 and 16 years earlier
miller said the woman's illness ``most likely'' resulted from occupational exposure
in the other letter, lucian sitwell and colleagues from ottawa civic hospital in canada outlined a similar case in a 75-year-old physician who dissected tissue, mostly from animals, in a medical school
sitwell said the man may have been exposed to tissue from sheep that had scrapie. some experts theorize that scrapie and creutzfeldt-jakob disease are caused by the same, so far unidentified infectious agent
creutzfeldt-jacob diseases causes slow, progressive loss of mental faculties. it has been spread through transplants of brain tissue and corneas as well as growth hormone derived from human pituitary glands. pvs bgng ``meanwhile bush...; delete final graf</note>
vice president george bush would have ``no reluctance'' to criticize jesse jackson if he is the democratic nominee, a spokesman said today
bush, rejoicing in his clear path to the republican presidential nomination, is starting to focus on the general election campaign, including strategy against his eventual democratic opponent
if jackson is the nominee, we will feel very willing to attack him on the issues. there will be no reticence, there will be no reluctance,'' bush spokesman pete teeley said aboard air force ii
jackson's democratic rivals have left jackson alone until recently, working under the conventional assumption that jackson could not win the nomination. but as jackson racks up win after win, sen. albert gore jr. has expressed a willingness to criticize jackson on the issues and his lack of experience in government
bush, assured of the gop nomination, will continue to campaign hard to guard against complacency, teeley said
it feels great,'' bush declared tuesday, giving a thumbs-up sign to reporters after learning of the withdrawal of sen. bob dole, the same day bush sailed to an overwhelming win in the connecticut primary
meanwhile, bush organizers are scurrying to find new ways to keep attention focused on the candidate now that he is without a major gop rival
for one thing, bush plans to continue to make high-profile campaign appearances in states with key primaries _ including new york, pennsylvania, ohio and california
the immediate task ahead is unity,'' bush told a gop dinner tuesday night after his connecticut victory was announced. ``we republicans have no reason for complacency.''
he said that republicans now must present their party as ``a big party with big open doors.''
the challenges we face will never be met unless we meet them together, hand-in-hand, as brothers and sisters, as blacks and whites, as northerners, southerners, east and west, the wealthy and the wanting,'' he said
he complimented dole for a ``very gracious statement'' in dropping out of the race. ``i know exactly how he must feel. i was there, eight years ago,'' bush said, referring to his unsuccessful 1980 presidential bid
not all bush supporters were as jubilant about recent developments as were the vice president and his top strategists
wisconsin gov. tommy thompson, said that dole's exit could hurt bush's chances in the fall campaign now that ``it's obvious he's going to win the nomination.''
i can't see the fact that the vice president doesn't have any more opposition is that good for him. it's good to have a primary,'' said thompson, a strong bush backer
thompson, who has been accompanying bush in his three-day campaign swing in advance of the april 5 wisconsin primary, said many wisconsin independents and some republicans are now likely to vote in the democratic primary
those individuals who come out of a hotly contested primary can use it as a springboard to solidify the party,'' thompson said
the republican governor, who earlier in the week had suggested he would vote for democrat jesse jackson were he a democrat, indicated jackson would be hard for bush to beat in november
he (jackson) is a viable candidate. he's very exciting. i like the guy,'' thompson said
gop officials in wisconsin urged party members who had supported dole against crossing over and voting in the democratic primary next week
and top bush aides conceded that lack of a contest could steal the spotlight away from their candidate
we're going to have to display some creativity'' in keeping bush's candidacy before the public, said bush aide peter teeley
although bush is running virtually alone for the gop nomination, it will be at least a couple of weeks before he can gain enough delegates for a majority at the gop convention
assuming he wins every delegate that can be won from now on, he would cross that threshold on may 3, when ohio, indiana and the district of columbia hold their primaries. but if he picks up dole's delegates _ now counted as uncommitted _ he could go over the top as early as april 15, when minnesota holds its gop state convention
bush's sole remaining challenger is former television evangelist pat robertson, who has but 17 delegates
bush had said he would keep on campaigning hard, right up until the time dole announced he was retiring from the race. dole's exit makes the april 5 gop primary moot
it changes some of the dynamics. it removes some of the tension,'' bush said of dole's withdrawal
i don't like running against other republicans,'' he added
bush said he had called dole to ``congratulate him on a hard-fought race...he has been a worthy warrier and a tough competitor.''
bush said that, while he intends to continue to ``campaign'' in key states, ``the schedule will be somewhat lighter. and i'll have more time to flesh out the issue positions.''
the landlord of a building where 150 narcotics officers conducted a raid will reimburse police for the cost of the bust and to move innocent tenants to safer apartments, authorities said
the agreement was part of a judgment in san mateo county superior court announced tuesday
district attorney jim fox said it is the first in the region in which law enforcement officials successfully sued apartment building owners under a state nuisance abatement law intended to combat drug dealers
the action ``sends a message to property owners that they have an affirmative duty'' to stop drug dealing in their buildings, fox said
there were more than 75 drug-related arrests at the building from june 1985 to the december bust, when 22 people were taken into custody
the landlord, 2001 manhattan apartments inc., of sausalito, agreed to pay $25,000 in civil penalties, $7,500 to the drug task force and $2,500 to the east palo alto police for the cost of enforcing drug laws at the building
the owners also have paid $13,000 in relocation expenses for eight families
president reagan named a former deputy california attorney general, phillip d. brady, as deputy counsel to the president wednesday
brady, 36, will succeed jay stephens in the position. brady has been deputy assistant to vice president george bush since 1985. before that he was in the justice department
he was deputy attorney general of california in 1978 and 1979
the president also announced the appointment of william j. landers, 36, now with the justice department, as associate counsel to the president. landers was deputy city attorney of los angeles in 1978 and 1979
the white house also announced two judicial nominations the president plans to make. it said he will nominate simeon timothy lake iii, 43, of houston, tex., as a u.s. district judge for the southern district of texas and karl s. forester, 47, of harlan, ky., as a u.s. district judge for the eastern district of kentucky
two flight attendants for royal swazi airways were charged wednesday with illegal possession of 40,000 tablets of the sedative mandrax
the defendants, princess makhosazana dlamini and norsa nerina mkhwanazi, were not required to enter a plea but were ordered to return to court tuesday
bond was set at the equivalent of about $1,175 for each woman and ordered them to surrender their passports until the case is settled
prosecutor peter mwangi said ms. dlamini and ms. mkhwanazi were arrested sunday after they arrived at jomo kenyatta international airport aboard a royal swazi airways flight on which they had worked
a man has been ordered to work 200 hours at an animal shelter after he admitted trying to kill a stray dog with arrows
joseph t. irvine of las vegas says he will appeal his conviction tuesday of injuring, torturing or abandoning an animal
justice of the peace bill jansen ruled irving was not legally justified when he armed himself with a hunting bow and shot the dog twice
the judge could have imposed a six-month jail term and a $1,000 fine, but said community service at the animal shelter might teach irvine respect for animals
the dog, which has since been adopted and named lucky, sat in a chair in the courtroom tuesday
irvine claimed the animal followed him into his home after he tried to befriend it. he said he shot the dog once in the head with an arrow, then decided it was not enough and loaded the bow, then ``let him have it again.''
nasa on wednesday asked the nation's schoolchildren to select a name for the space shuttle that will replace challenger, destroyed in an explosion in 1986
the agency, in cooperation with the council of chief state school officers, invited teachers to enter their students in a national competition to name the orbiter, now being built and scheduled for its maiden flight in 1992
the orbiter-naming program responds to a basic human impulse to name things,'' the announcement said. ``nasa's first orbiters were named after sea vessels used in research and exploration. the tradition of naming an orbiter after an exploratory or research sea vessel will be continued.''
the three remaining shuttles in the fleet are discovery, atlantis and columbia
nasa said the name challenger had been retired, in honor of the seven astronauts killed in the explosion
the announcement said the name chosen should not only identify an american spacecraft but also should capture the spirit of america's mission in space
announcements of opportunity will be distributed soon to elementary and secondary teachers and principals. entry packets will be available in may
to enter, elementary and secondary school students will form teams and research a name,'' nasa said. ``each team will prepare a related classroom project to support and justify the name selected.''
there will be two entry divisions, covering kindergarten through the sixth grade and seventh through 12th grades
students in public and private schools in the united states and u.s. territories, department of defense overseas dependents' schools and bureau of indian affairs schools are eligible
each state, territory and agency will announce one winner in each division in march 1989. nasa will announce the final winner for each division and the name selected for the new shuttle in may 1989. agreement sent</note>
house leaders reached final agreement today on a package of $48 million in ``humanitarian'' aid to nicaragua's contra rebels and to children injured in that country's long civil war
the proposal had been worked out in negotiations over the last two days between house speaker jim wright, d-texas, minority leader robert michel, r-ill., and other leaders, who gave it their final approval today
agreement sent the measure to a house floor vote later today, and it was expected to receive a strong bipartisan majority. that would send the bill to the senate on thursday, where easy passage also was expected, and authorize the first u.s. aid to the rebels in a month
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the package was being examined by the administration but said it was ``encouraging'' and ``moves in the right direction.''
it sends a message to the contras that they are not abandoned, that we do care about them and want to keep them healthy and a viable force,'' said rep. mickey edwards, r-okla., who participated in negotiations to draft the compromise
and it lets the sandinistas know that it's important to the united states congress that the talks that take place down there take place with good faith, and that they move toward democratization,'' edwards added
as part of the deal, wright was to send a letter to president reagan pledging ``fair and orderly'' consideration for any future request the administration might make for new military aid if the central american peace process breaks down, said rep. david bonior, d-mich., leader of a democratic task force on the contra issue
but wright would retain control over the precise timing of a vote on such an aid package and the rules under which it would come before the house, bonior said
a cease-fire verification commission, made up of nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo and organization of american states secretary general joao baena soares, would have ``substantial'' say in whether new military aid is warranted, bonior said
the package would provide aid to keep the contras together while they spend the next 60 days in cease-fire zones during negotiations for a longer-term truce
it would send about $2.7 million monthly in food, clothing, medicine and shelter to the rebels over the next six months. an additional $1.5 million in communications gear, subject to approval by the cease-fire commission, would push the total six-month rebel aid package to $17.7 million
that rate of aid is the same as the rebels were getting prior to feb. 29, when the last u.s. assistance ran out
an identical amount would go into a new program to care for children injured in the seven-year civil war, bonior said
the package also would provide $10 million to finance the verification commission, set up as part of last week's cease-fire agreement to ensure adherence to terms of the cease-fire worked out in sapoa, nicaragua, between the contras and the leftist managua government
the bill would provide additional money for transportation of the aid, but that amount was not included in the $50 million figure
the money would be administered by the state department's agency for international development, bonior said. aid would get $2.5 million in the bill to cover administrative costs
one of the most contentious issues in the negotiations was whether reagan should be guaranteed the right to a quick, guaranteed vote in congress if the sandinistas renege on promises of amnesty and restoration of civil liberties, and hostilities break out anew
republicans, wary of promises made by the leftist government, had insisted such a guarantee was needed as insurance that the sandinistas would live up to their end of the bargain
in a compromise, wright drafted a letter to reagan assuring the president of a chance to submit a proposal for new military aid if the peace process becomes derailed, and to have the proposal treated fairly
that means that the measure would be considered by the appropriate house committee and could come to the floor for a vote, but under conditions determined by wright, said bonior
reagan would be urged to get the advice of the verification commission before making any such request, but would not be forced to do so
any new aid for the contras would have to conform to the requirements of the cease-fire reached last week. that agreement said the contras would receive only humanitarian aid and that the aid would be routed through ``neutral organizations.'' the cia has delivered past u.s. aid supplies to the rebels
in remarks tuesday in managua, nicaraguan president daniel ortega urged congress not to approve any aid that would conflict with the agreement, which he defined as allowing provision of civilian clothes, medicine and food, but not uniforms or boots
president reagan put in a plug for the superconducting super collider wednesday, saying it is more than an ``arcane interest'' to a few research specialists
reagan has asked congress for $365 million to begin construction of the super collider, which would be the world's largest particle accelerator
the scientific community is divided on the project, some regarding it as a key to the technological future, and others saying it would drain needed money from more worthwile research
i know that some people may question the practical applications of the superconducting super collider,'' the president told a group of high school science students and others in the white house rose garden
the strange world of subatomic particles, they may think, will never be more than an arcane interest to a few highly specialized scientists,'' he said
but the truth is the practical applications of this new technology are already changing the way we live. every time someone turns on his desk computer, makes a phone call or plays a video game, he is plugging into that mysterious world of quantum physics. the superconducting super collider is the doorway to that new world of quantum change.''
the students in the audience were part of a program established in 1985 to give top science students from each state a chance to work for two weeks in the summer at national laboratories in the washington area
reagan approved construction of the super collider in january, 1987. a site is to be selected next january in either arizona, colorado, illinois, michigan, new york, north carolina, tennessee or texas
the projected cost to build the 53-miles-around tunnel that comprises the super collider is more than $4 billion
six nobel laureates, four of whom were present for wednesday's ceremony, wrote reagan that the project ``represents america's commitment to the pursuit of excellence in basic scientific research.''
the letter was signed by were james watson cronin, val logsdon fitch, sheldon lee glashow, burton richter, samuel c.c. ting and steven weinberg. all but fitch and glashow attended
ex-president richard nixon will appear april 10 on the nbc-tv show ``meet the press'' for an hour-long interview _ his first extended television appearance in eight years, the network said wednesday
there are no set conditions for the interview,'' said nbc news vice president tim russert, who had tried to get nixon on the weekly program for three years
following the appearance on ``meet the press,'' nixon will appear in a three-part interview with bryant gumbel on nbc's ``today'' show. nixon's last long television interview was in 1980 on the abc-tv program ``20-20.''
the ``meet the press'' taping will be april 9 in washington, said nbc spokesman bill mcandrew. the program will be broadcast unedited, he said
meet the press'' moderator chris wallace will be joined by anchorman tom brokaw and commentator john chancellor in quizzing nixon, who resigned under threat of impeachment in august 1974
nixon will appear live on the april 11 ``today'' show, with the following two days featuring taped highlights of his interview with gumbel
cbs is dropping its low-rated tuesday lineup of comedies and putting ``cagney &amp; lacey'' back in its monday night time period
cbs is facing a third-place finish in the prime-time ratings this season for the first time ever and was trying to add more half-hour comedies to its drama-heavy schedule
the critically acclaimed ``frank's place'' was spared the ax tuesday night and will be returned to the schedule shortly, cbs said. it had been moved from monday to tuesday in the schedule shakeup earlier this month. ``cagney &amp; lacey'' will replace ``wiseguy'' on monday, but ``wiseguy'' also will return soon, cbs said
trial and error,'' ``coming of age'' and ``my sister sam'' have had their last tuesday broadcasts, and cbs announced no plans to bring them back. those comedies, plus ``frank's place'' were the four lowest-rated network shows in last week's nielsens
cbs will replace the tuesday lineup with theatrical movies in the meantime, and the detective series ``houston knights'' will return april 26
democratic presidential hopeful jesse jackson and key members of his party's establishment held a summit meeting wednesday, showing, he said, that ``old wineskins are expanding and making room for new wine.''
jackson huddled for a breakfast meeting with more than two dozen well-known figures in the party. afterward, they said no one had brought up reported party concerns that his nomination could damage democratic chances of winning the white house next november
we only see that in the press,'' said california assembly speaker willie brown, jackson's national campaign chairman. ``maybe people don't want to say that in front of us.''
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jackson are locked in a tight race for the lead in national convention delegates, after a big jackson win in the michigan caucuses last weekend and a dukakis victory in the connecticut primary tuesday
in addition to private concerns about jackson, another democratic contender, sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee, has begun strong criticism of jackson's experience and his stands on issues
i categorically reject his notion that there's a moral equivalence between israel and the plo,'' gore said tuesday in new york. ``and i am dismayed by his embrace of (plo leader yasser) arafat and (cuban president fidel) castro.''
jackson brushed aside those criticisms, and gore sought a meeting with jackson late wednesday in washington before jackson was to fly to wisconsin to campaign for the primary there next tuesday
after the breakfast meeting, former defense secretary clark clifford, one of the solid figures of the party establishment, had nothing but praise for jackson
what he is also doing is bringing a new maturity to the american political scene,'' said clifford. ``his candidacy could not have occurred 50 years ago, 25 years ago, or perhaps even 10 years ago. it is ... an important breakthrough in our constant seeking to bring more fairness to our political process.''
jackson said the breakfast brought ``together democrats who have traditional investment in the interests of the country and the party and those who are new to the process.''
in this instance, we bring together old wineskins and new wine, but the old wineskins are expanding and making room for new wine,'' he added, using an image he used frequently in his 1984 campaign
former democratic party chairman john white, who put together the breakfast, is joining the campaign as an informal adviser
this meeting is a new maturing of the political process in america,'' white said. ``it represents a growing-up of america. it represents a bonding of the democratic party and a bond that recognizes no class.''
participants in the breakfast said one concern about jackson was posed to him in a question about his relationship with black muslim leader louis farrakhan
white said jackson ``quoted jesus about casting the first stone and forgiveness and so anybody who hasn't made mistakes ... let's not be casting stones at each other about the past.''
farrakhan campaigned with jackson early in the 1984 campaign, but the tie was cut after the black muslim leader called judaism a ``gutter religion'' and called adolf hitler ``a great man.''
mcdonnell douglas corp. became the pentagon's top research contractor in fiscal 1987, winning awards totaling $1.7 billion, the defense department said wednesday
among educational and non-profit entities, the massachusetts institute of technology continued to hold down the top ranking, winning research contracts during the year worth $407.6 million
the johns hopkins university was close behind with awards totaling $354.9 million
overall, the pentagon increased its spending on research by more than 10 percent during fiscal 1987, with awards reaching a grand total of $21.8 billion. that compared with $19.8 billion in fiscal 1986
much of last year's increase appeared related to work on president reagan's star wars anti-missile system. the amount of money invested in research on ``missile and space systems'' climbed from $6.9 billion in fiscal 1986 to $7.9 billion in fiscal 1987
moreover, the martin marietta corp. _ a key star wars contractor _ vaulted from fifth place in the fiscal 1986 rankings to second place last year with contract awards rising from $695.3 million to $1.6 billion
the latest figures are contained in a report prepared annually by the pentagon to rank the top 500 companies or non-profit groups performing ``research, development, test and evaluation'' work. the rankings are based on a review of all contracts totaling $25,000 or more awarded during the fiscal year that ended last sept. 30
mcdonnell douglas, whose overall ranking as the nation's largest defense contractor was announced just a month ago, displaced the lockheed missiles &amp; space co. in assuming the top spot for research. mcdonnell douglas' research contracts climbed from $928 million in fiscal 1986 to $1.7 billion in fiscal 1987
because of martin marietta's abrupt rise, lockheed fell to 3rd place in the research rankings, winning contracts in fiscal 1987 worth $1.54 billion compared with $1.48 billion the year before
the remainder of the top 10 included the boeing co. in 4th place with awards totaling $1.2 billion, followed by the grumman aerospace corp., $901.5 million; general electric co., $784.4 million; raytheon co., $593.8 million; trw inc., $556.6 million; rockwell international corp., $494 million; and ibm, $470.9 million
the $407.6 million in research contracts won by mit was enough to give it the 11th place ranking overall. in fiscal 1986, mit had won contracts worth $363.9 million and was ranked 14th overall
among other educational and non-profit entities, johns hopkins was 2nd in fiscal 1987 with $354.9 million and a 15th ranking overall, followed by the mitre corp., $347.5 million, 16th overall; the aerospace corp., $338.9 million, 18th overall; and charles stark draper lab inc., $164.7 million, 26th overall
all told, the top 500 concerns accounted for 97 percent of the total research contracts awarded, or $21.2 billion. the top 500 included 380 businesses, 100 educational and non-profit organizations, three u.s. government agencies and 17 foreign contractors
the research awards to foreign concerns totaled $114.3 million, up only slightly from the $106.9 million reported in fiscal 1986. the leading foreign contractor remained the same, the canadian commercial corp., with awards totaling $25.9 million
a dispute between government agencies over the questions to be asked on the 1990 census has been settled, the census bureau reported wednesday
friday is the deadline for the bureau to tell congress the questions it intends to ask americans in the national head count
the issue has been clouded by a disagreement with the white house office of management and budget. that agency wanted to reduce paperwork by deleting some questions and reducing the number of people who get the more complex long form
the two agencies have agreed that all 106 million households in the nation will be sent the short form, while the more detailed long form will go to 17.7 million. census had wanted to sent it to nearly 20 million households, omb to limit it to 10 million
short form questions on plumbing facilities and condominiums will be switched to the long form, as omb suggested. but other questions will be retained, including the cost of uilities
some things that were asked in the 1980 census will be dropped in 1990. these include employment five years earlier, marital history, weeks spent looking for work, number of bathrooms, air conditioning and heating equipment, presence of an elevator and type of fuel used for cooking and heating water
