a girl awaiting a triple transplant operation got one special wish _ to meet entertainers siegfried and roy _ but was denied a second one when they refused to make her younger brother disappear
cassandra james, 9, of las vegas is awaiting a trip to pittsburgh children's hospital for a heart, liver and kidney transplant
the make a wish foundation learned she wanted to meet the illusionists, and arranged the visit tuesday night after their show
roy told cassandra to ``hang in there and be tough.''
her problems began with a strep throat infection that traveled to her kidney when she was 2. doctors later discovered her liver was too swollen to permit a kidney transplant, and suspected her heart was also diseased
orders to u.s. factories for manufactured goods fell for the second month in a row in february, but analysts said the 0.8 percent decline was not a cause for alarm
the commerce department said wednesday that orders for durable and non-durable goods dropped to a seasonally adjusted $210.86 billion last month following a 0.6 percent decline in january
the february setback was the biggest since a 1.4 percent drop last august and marked the first time that factory orders have fallen for two consecutive months since the summer of 1986
economists said the declines showed that businesses did cut back on orders in the early part of the year in an effort to trim high levels of unsold goods that had built up in the final three months of 1987
while this process will dampen growth, economists said it appeared that the cutbacks had been moderate and would set the stage for faster growth in the months ahead
the economy is expanding at a moderate pace. we are not looking for either a boom or a bust,'' said bruce steinberg, an economist with merrill lynch in new york. ``although we had declines in orders in the past two months, those declines came off a very high level of demand in the fourth quarter.''
even with the two months of declines, total factory orders were 8.3 percent higher than a year earlier, reflecting the strong growth in manufacturing demand in 1987. analysts also noted that the backlog of unfilled orders continued to grow in february, rising by 0.8 percent to $412.3 billion, indicating production will have to remain high to fill those orders
economists expect manufacturing to be one of the major sources of strength for the economy this year as american companies continue to benefit from a weaker dollar, which has made their products competitive again on world markets
this export boom is expected to spur u.s. companies to boost their investment spending plans for new plant and equipment, further adding to overall economic growth
however, the february report said the key category of non-defense capital goods fell 3.9 percent, although the sector was still 23 percent higher than a year ago. this category is considered a good gauge of business spending plans on capital equipment
jerry jasinowski, chief economist for the national association of manufacturers, said the weakness in stock prices and fears about higher inflation rates may be causing some companies to lower their investment spending somewhat
the february decline in factory orders included a drop of 1.1 percent in orders for durable goods. these items, expected to last three or more years, fell to a seasonally adjusted $118.5 billion last month. an advance report last week had put the decline in those orders at a sharper 1.8 percent
orders for non-durable goods fell 0.4 percent in february to $97.9 billion
orders for military equipment fell 8.2 percent to $8.4 billion last month, but military demand was still 14 percent higher than a year ago. without the drop in defense orders, total orders would have fallen by a slightly smaller 0.5 percent in february
orders for transportation equipment were one of the few areas of strength last month, climbing 3.5 percent to $30 billion. the aircraft component showed a 6.8 percent increase
orders for primary metals, such as steel, edged up 1.4 percent and were 26 percent higher than a year earlier
orders for electrical machinery fell 7.4 percent, while orders for non-electrical machinery were off 5.4 percent
shipments of manufactured goods edged up 0.1 percent in february to $207.4 billion
treasury secretary james a. baker iii told congress on wednesday that he strongly disagrees with proposals to forgive some of the third world's debt, now over $1 trillion
i believe this path leads both debtors and creditors off the cliff,'' he said. ``this approach would irreparably politicize the debt problem.''
forgiveness would distract both debtors and creditors from the need to make reforms, encourage repudiation of debt and shift the risk on bank loans to taxpayers, including u.s. taxpayers, he added
i simply cannot endorse such schemes,'' he told the senate appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations
he argued for a u.s. contribution to increase the capital of the world bank, the largest single source of aid loans to third world countries. he said pulling out of the world bank or the inter-american development bank, as some critics have suggested, would reduce u.s. influence and make it more likely that they would act contrary to u.s. interests
but he said the reagan administration would not ask congress for money to bring the united states up to date in the year beginning sept. 30 on its arrears in payments to the world bank. he said west germany, kuwait and saudi arabia had reduced their contributions because of the u.s. shortfalls and he was sorry about that
he promised that the reagan administration, before it leaves office, will ask that the money be furnished in the 12 months following oct. 1, 1989
rep. david r. obey, d-wis., told secretary of state george p. shultz earlier this month that the arrears should be paid before a new contribution is sought. obey, chairman of the house appropriations foreign operations subcommittee, predicted there will be trouble in congress for the administration's request
baker said the administration will not ask for new contributions to the inter-american development bank until the borrowing countries, which now control lending, give the u.s. government greater power over new loans
during baker's testimony, sen. don nickles, r-okla., complained of the bank's internal spending. he said it:
_recently moved into one of the most expensive new buildings in washington at a cost of $225 million
_spent an average of more than $100,000 each on separation pay for departing employees
_had an average of 35 claims a year on its health insurance for each employee
we agree that's the kind of thing that has to be cleaned up,'' baker said, but did not confirm nickles' figures
baker clashed with sen. daniel k. inouye, d-hawaii, chairman of the subcommittee, over plans to help other countries refinance as much as $16 billion owed to the united states for weapons and other military aid. inouye said regulations proposed by the treassury could add as much as two percentage points to borrower's costs
about $5 billion worth of israel's debts would be affected, and the high cost of refinancing might discourage other countries from using the plan, inouye said
u.s. servicemen joined west german firefighters wednesday in piling sandbags to protect the city of wiesbaden from the floodwaters of the swollen rhine river
thousands of volunteers have pitched in the past three days to protect people's lives and property from flooding
six people are believed to have died in flood-related accidents
floodwaters slowly receded in most of west germany on wednesday, but the situation along the danube river in central bavaria state was still critical after the worst flooding in 70 years. about 3,500 bavarians had fled their homes
in wiesbaden, u.s. air force security police and west german firefighters worked to shore up dikes on the rhine river with sandbags
we had 70 security police working out there all night with west german firemen,'' u.s. air force spokesman hans ostertag said
no major flooding problems were reported wednesday in wiesbaden, near frankfurt, as the rhine receded from dangerous levels
residents of ahofling, a bavarian hamlet 12 miles east of regensburg, stayed up tuesday night trying to keep the danube from inundating their homes
most of the 415 residents of ahofling were up all night filling sandbags to bolster a dike,'' said herbert zeitler, a state spokesman
the waters are receding slowly but there is still danger of breaks in the dike,'' said zeitler
zeitler said property damage ``will run in the millions'' of dollars
the bavarian interior ministry warned the situation could again worsen if warmer weather accompanied by heavy rains speeds up the spring thaw of snow in mountainous areas
the ground is saturated and it will take several months before it will again be able to absorb any large amounts of water,'' the ministry said in a statement
in bonn, chancellor helmut kohl issued a statement expressing condolences to the familes of those who died in the floods and gratitude to people who pitched in to help avert further catastrophes
armenians threatened to continue a general strike paralyzing the main city of a disputed southern region until the government agreed to make the region part of aremenia, newspapers reported wednesday
for the first time, an official soviet newspaper, komsomolskaya pravda, used the word ``strike'' to describe what was previously was referred to as truancy or absenteeism in stepanakert, the central city of azerbaijan's nagorno-karabakh region
the soviet press generally uses the word ``strike'' only to describe labor unrest in the west. but komsomolskaya pravda, the organ of the youth organization komsomol, took advantage of soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's drive for openness to break from tradition
the daily also provided the first official confirmation that the strike was part of a series of labor protests in stepanakert and that the walkout started march 24, not saturday as other newspapers have indicated
all but essential services such as bakeries and dairies, some public transportation and medical clinics were reported to be shut down in stepanakert, a city of more than 33,000 people. the government has lost millions of rubles in revenue because of the strike, newspapers said
we're only two or three steps from catastrophe,'' vasily atadzhanyan, the director of a shoe factory, told komsomolskaya pravda. ``we will pay huge fines for not fulfilling our obligations to our customers. we say directly: `not coming to work is sabotage.'''
only about 120 of 1,500 workers showed up for work monday at the shoe factory, the newspaper said
people are sitting home ... without noise and without demonstrations,'' said a man answering the telephone at the official newspaper in stepanakert, sovietsky karabakh. ``people say they are going to stay away until they get a decision from the government in their favor.''
the communist party newspaper pravda said many stepanakert residents were upset that soviet newspapers were not accurately reporting the dispute
we want everyone to know the truth. the absences from work will continue until our matter is settled,'' pravda quoted one resident as saying
early press coverage claimed that armenians, who are mostly christian, and azerbaijanis, who are mostly shiite moslem, live together in harmony. it blamed the unrest, in which at least 32 people have died, on a few ``extremists.''
authorities have been meeting with residents to urge them to return to their jobs and vowed not to bow to pressure to annex predominantly armenian nagorno-karabakh to armenia
instead, authorities have unveiled a plan to spend up to 400 million rubles, or $640 million, to improve social and economic conditions in the aremenian-dominated region
the labor newspaper trud said people in stepanakert were grateful for the government's efforts but that some still believed it was necessary to stay away from work to press their demand
the newspaper sovietskaya rossiya said about 100 specialists and workers appeared for work at an electrical-technical factory tuesday morning
ninety percent of the workers at a plant manufacturing construction materials appeared at work monday morning, only to walk out en masse, komsomolskaya pravda said
armenians began mass street rallies and strikes in stepanakert on feb. 13. the turmoil spread to the capital of the armenian republic, yerevan. on feb. 28, ethnic rioting broke out in sumgait, a industrial city in azerbaijan, and officials said 26 armenians and six azerbaijanis were killed
a hindu ascetic has been standing for three months in the western state of gujarat to collect funds for a shelter for holy cows
ramanuj vaishnavdas, 24, has been on his feet under a tree in front of a temple in palanpur town day and night to collect 5,551 rupees (about $427). he wants to build a shelter for the cows, which are considered holy and an image of the mother by the hindus
the sadhu, or ascetic, takes a break only for 15 minutes every morning for his ritual bath, the united news of india news agency reported wednesday
he sleeps and eats _ only one meal a day _ while standing
cow shelters and orphanages are common in india, where cows roam freely on the streets and often are a traffic hazard. cow slaughter is illegal in many of india's 25 states
a federal law aimed at encouraging chastity among teen-agers provides money to religious groups that, in one instance, advised ``young girls to pretend that jesus is their date,'' the supreme court was told wednesday
we're not saying that chastity cannot be a secular value, but it has been misused'' by religious groups funded under the 1981 law, argued janet benshoof, an american civil liberties union lawyer
as a result, she contended, the law unconstitutionally promotes religion
but the reagan administration's top-ranked courtroom lawyer defended the law
solicitor general charles fried conceded that ``there may have been some departures'' from past supreme court rulings on church-state relations by some private organizations carrying out the law's purpose. but he said such ``constitutionally troublesome'' spending of federal money has been corrected, and that the law can be carried out in a constitutionally acceptable way
the law, known as the adolescent family life act, was passed by congress ``in response to grave social, economic and health costs'' of early-adolescent pregnancy, fried said
he noted that religiously affiliated groups for years have participated in government programs dealing with juvenile delinquency, foster care, adoption and drug prevention
the disputed law, sponsored by former sen. jeremiah denton, r-ala., and ushered through congress by fellow conservatives, provided millions of dollars for three general program categories _ care, prevention and research
care services'' include pregnancy testing, maternity counseling, adoption and referral help
prevention services'' are those aimed at discouraging adolescent sexual relations, and include programs offering counseling and family planning
the law requires applicants for funding to describe how, in providing services, they will ``involve religious and charitable organizations, voluntary associations and other groups in the private sector.''
the law also allows religiously affiliated organizations to receive money for such programs
a federal judge here struck down the law last year, ruling that its primary effect is to promote religion and that it fosters an excessive entanglement between government and religion
the administration then asked the supreme court to salvage the law. the justices are expected to announce their decision by july
benshoof acknowledged that federal money may be used to cope with the problem of teen-age pregnancies. more than 1 million unmarried girls become pregnant each year, and about half obtain abortions
but the aclu lawyer added that the 1981 envisions a constitutionally suspect ``union between government and religion.''
not once in seven years has (the department of health and human services) questioned the religiousity of any institution receiving aid'' under the law, benshoof contended
when justice antonin scalia asked whether congress could spend money to encourage self-restraint by teen-agers, benshoof said groups receiving the money ``can't do it by telling young girls to pretend that jesus is their date.''
the aclu says a virginia organization that received $150,000 under the law offered such advice
plans by salvadoran guerrillas to escalate their war against the u.s.-backed government reinforce their ``well-deserved reputation for ruthless and indiscriminate violence,'' the state department said wednesday
the rebel plan was disclosed by the insurgents' high command at a news conference with foreign journalists in guerrilla-held territory. among other steps, the rebels said they intend to target u.s. military advisers for assassination
state department spokesman charles redman said the united states obviously ``will not be intimidated by threats against its personnel. the u.s. commitment to assist the democratic government of el salvador, backed by a strong bipartisan consensus, remains firm.''
the rebel leaders said they plan to increase attacks in san salvador, the capital, targeting the country's upper class, to use surface-to-air missiles against military helicopers and to step up attacks against military installations
redman said the proposed rebel offensive ``once again confirms their disregard for the well-being of the salvadoran people and their commitment to achieve power and install a totalitarian dictatorship at any price.''
two greenpeace volunteers scaled nelson's column on wednesday to protest acid rain pollution
the two men, who made their ascent in five hours using equipment, were arrested and charged with breaching the peace when they descended the 170-foot landmark in trafalgar square later in the day, greenpeace officials said
joe thompson, 26, and john stevenson, 30, started their ascent on the column at 4 a.m. and reached the statue of admiral horatio nelson, a 19th-century british naval hero, about five hours later
during their descent, they unfurled a banner reading ``stop acid rain'' on the column
thompson and stevenson, both from sheffield in northern england, used climbing ropes and harnesses. the environmental group wanted to highlight what it considers government complacency over acid rain damage
it urged prime minister margaret thatcher's government to allocate part of the estimated $8.2 billion in electricity price increases in the next four years to fighting acid raid, caused mainly by sulfur and nitrogen emissions from coal-fueled power plants and factories
sears, roebuck and co. has agreed to halt sales of lawn darts, following a federal complaint about the potentially dangerous sports items, the consumer product safety commission said wednesday
sears agreed in a consent decree to stop selling lawn darts within a week, the commission said
the decree settles charges that the nationwide retailer offered lawn darts for sale without required warning labels and in areas near toy sales
lawn darts are an outdoor game in which large, pointed darts are tossed at targets on the ground. they can pose a serious hazard, with three deaths reported in the last 18 years and an estimated 670 annual injuries, the safety agency said
federal regulations require warning labels on the darts and prohibit their sales in or near toy sales areas. they are permitted to be sold as sporting goods
sears' prompt response to the commission's concerns should serve as an example for manufacturers and other retailers of lawn darts,'' said commission chairman terrence m. scanlon
the agency asked that consumers report injuries or improper sales of lawn darts by calling it at 1-800-638-2772
wheat farmers should be provided with some kind of incentive to sell grain on the open market rather than have to forfeit it to the government when price support loans come due, the national association of wheat growers said wednesday
frank johannsen, association president, said wheat farmers deserve the same kind of consideration given corn producers who are being allowed to keep their grain under federal price support for an additional year
that was a reference to agriculture secretary richard e. lyng's announcement tuesday that price support loans for some old-crop corn and sorghum will be extended a year longer than their normal maturity dates
johannsen, a bayard, neb., wheat farmers said in a statement released here that the association is ``seeking a way to encourage growers to settle their maturing loans'' by paying them off with generic certificates. the certificates are issued by usda as payment-in-kind under crop programs and can be exchanged for surplus commodities owned by the department's commondity credit corp
if the price support loans are not repaid, a farmer must forfeit the grain to the ccc, which cancels the debt
once the ccc takes over the grain, it must be moved into government storage. much of the ccc wheat is currently being sold back into the market in weekly auctions
since current estimates are that it costs the government at least 20 cents a bushel to move, store, catalog and exchange forfeited wheat through weekly auctions, our proposal won't cost anything extra and it will reduce some of the government's logistical problems,'' johannsen said. ``it has the added benefit of keeping wheat moving in the pipeline of our much-improved market.''
besides, he said, grain farmers ``have a right to expect even-handed treatment'' from the department. ``forcing farmers to forfeit their loans only broadens the government's role in markets.''
hundreds of arabs defied a massive security crackdown and battled israeli troops in the west bank on wednesday to mark a palestinian anniversary. soldiers killed four arabs and wounded 39 others, officials said
the army's toughest restrictions in more than 20 years of occupation failed to contain the violence. the measures included mass arrests, the deployment of thousands of extra police, restrictions on media coverage and a ban on palestinians traveling in occupied areas
we can't say that land day was quiet. it was not,'' said west bank commander maj. gen. avraham mitzna
the day commemorates a confrontation on march 30, 1976, when israeli arabs protested the forced sale of 1,600 acres of their land for jewish settlement. six arabs were killed
wednesday's fatalities brought the arab death toll to 123 since the unrest began dec. 8, according to u.n. figures. one israeli soldier has also been killed
the army closed the arab-owned palestine press service for six months, further illustrating the seriousness israel attaches to reducing media coverage
the agency, the only arab information service, has been a vital source of breaking news for foreign journalists since israel ordered the territories closed monday
the army barred reporters from entering the west bank and gaza strip except in news pools with an army escort. army spokeswoman ofra preuss said reporters violating the ban would be prosecuted with the maximum penalty being five years in prison
u.s. television networks and some journalists entered the territories with military escorts. others slipped through alone _ taking back roads, accompanying jewish settlers or posing as tourists
in arab towns throughout israel, about 30,000 israeli arabs waved palestinian flags and chanted anti-occupation slogans as helicopters circled overhead. about 4,000 extra police were deployed
in street battles in a half-dozen areas around the biblical city of bethlehem, troops clashed with arab protesters who hurled rocks, bottles, metal bars and raised the outlawed palestinian flag
officials at beit jalla hospital said 12 arabs were wounded
in the village of beit sahur, where tradition says shepherds spotted the star signaling jesus' birth, about 200 arab protesters clashed with troops who responded with tear gas and live ammunition, arab witnesses said
witnesses said one palestinian was shot and wounded in the demonstration
mitzna said the high casualty toll was the result of army orders to crush plo-ordered protests on land day
the high number of casualities was caused by the active, immediate and forceful measures of our units everywhere there was an attempt to violate order,'' mitzna said
mitzna said four arabs were killed by army gunfire and 45 to 47 injured, most from shooting and some from tear gas and beatings. hospital officials said 39 of the injured were shot
in deir abu mashal, a west bank village 20 miles northwest of jerusalem, troops killed a 50-year-old woman and wounded three other family members. the army and hospital officials gave conflicting versions of the clash
doctors at ramallah hospital said the troops entered the home of wajalah rabir while she and her family were having breakfast and fatally shot her in the head
the soldiers came in and asked if there were any men in the house,'' mrs. rabir's 17-year-old daughter, zeinab, said in quotes relayed by a visitor at hospital
the daughter said she told the troops no men were home, but they entered anyway. a soldier shot one brother who started to run and other family members then lunged toward the troops. the soldiers opened fire, she said
mitzna said the clash began when soldiers entered the village to search for arabs who allegedly fired four shots at an army roadblock
inside the village there was violent resistance to arrests and as a result ... a woman was killed who participated in a brutal attack on soldiers,'' mitzna said
the commander of the unit said mrs. rabir was shot when she used a rake to strike an unconscious soldier
in the village of burqa, troops opened fire on arab protesters, killing khalid salah, 22, officials at al ittihad hospital in nearby nablus said
the other two fatalities were identified as abdel kareem mohammed halakha, 25, of the village of shuyukh near hebron and hosni omar shaheen, 24, of yamoun north of nablus, arab reports said
the three-day crackdown in the occupied lands began late monday and early tuesday. the 850,000 palestinians on the west bank were ordered confined to their villages while the 650,000 arabs on the gaza strip were prohibited from leaving their homes
in washington, the state department defended israel's authority to maintain order in the territories but said it should be exercised in a humane way
spokesman charles e. redman supported assertions by assistant secretary of state richard schifter that israel ``not only has the right but the obligation'' to restore order in the violence-beset territories it has held since the 1967 six-day war
land day, an annual day of anti-israel protest, marks a bloody clash between israeli troops and arab citizens over land confiscation
it also has become a day for palestinians in the occupied lands to show their opposition to israeli rule
the day commemorates a confrontation on march 30, 1976, when israeli arabs called a general strike to protest the forced sale of 1,600 acres of their land for jewish settlement
the protest, at first peaceful, turned violent when arab crowds attacked army vehicles with rocks, knives, crowbars and firebombs. troops fired shots to disperse protesters
six arabs were killed and 31 wounded. hundreds more were arrested
officials blamed the israeli communist party, rakah, for inciting the protest. but many saw the occasion as a sign that the israeli arab community, which now numbers 700,000, would never be an integral part of the country
since 1976, land day has been a source of tension and violence. angry protests have broken out in israel and the occupied territories, although no fatalities occurred until this year
authorities, fearing major disturbances this year, closed the west bank and gaza to journalists. west bank residents were confined to their towns and villages for three days while residents of the gaza strip were ordered to stay in their homes
the republican party, with front-running george bush as its likely presidential nominee now that his chief rival bob dole is out of the race, turned to platform matters and focused on foreign policy as it opened hearings wednesday
at the end of the carter years, the united states was weaker and soviet relations were strained,'' jeane j. kirkpatrick, a former u.s. ambassador to the united nations, told a gop panel at the start of the first of three 1988 national platform hearings
at the end of ronald reagan's presidency, the united states is stronger and relations with the soviets are stronger,'' said mrs. kirkpatrick
wednesday's session on foreign policy matters will be followed by hearings in kansas city, mo., on may 31, and los angeles on june 30, in advance of the gop national convention in new orleans aug. 15-18, where a platform will be produced
the may session will focus on education, child care and neighborhood development matters, while the june hearing will concentrate on economic growth
vice president bush is leading the gop presidential delegate race. dole, a senator from kansas who had been his main challenger in the early primaries and caucuses, withdrew from the contest on tuesday, leaving pat robertson still running but far behind bush
mrs. kirkpatrick, who provided a foreign policy overview at the platform hearing, said the most important accomplishment of the reagan administration has been to ``demonstrate through domestic and foreign policy the power of freedom.''
she said progress has been made during reagan's tenure in rebuilding american military forces and bringing terrorists to justice. she added that progress also has been achieved in u.s.-soviet relations
former reagan administration officials, think-tank representatives and members of congress testified before the republican platform committee panel on what they saw as the successes of the reagan years and on their views of the carter era and of the democratic presidential candidates
more than 60 legislators and former officials arranged to testify on issues including those involving central america, international terrorism, u.s.-soviet relations, defense resources, veterans, and reagan's proposed strategic defense initiative, also known as star wars
l. francis bouchey, a member of the council for inter-american security, accused leading democratic candidates michael dukakis and jesse jackson of attempting to return to what he called the ``failed years of the carter administration.''
bouchey accused the democrats of ``neo-isolationism and on-again, off-again support of the nicaraguan resistance fighters.''
rep. bill green, r-n.y., urged the party to ``be in step with the majority of americans, including american women.''
women may well determine who is the next president. they probably will decide some senate and congressional races this november,'' green said in a statement released before his testimony
it would not be smart for a political party to ignore or anger such voters. yet there is a danger of the republican party's doing just that,'' he said
the panel included gop national committee chairman frank j. fahrenkopf jr.; maureen reagan, co-chairman of the republican national committee; sen. robert w. kasten jr., r-wis.; rep. jerry lewis, r-calif.; chuck hardwick, speaker of the new jersey state assembly; and delaware gov. michael n. castle. `and'</note>
an adviser to jesse jackson said wednesday he detected the beginnings of an anonymous ``stop jackson'' movement in the democratic party, and a southern party chairman acknowledged there is ``an awful lot of apprehension out there'' about the possibility of jackson's nomination
democratic establishment leaders gathered here with jackson, and after that meeting, jackson supporter rep. mickey leland of texas said he understood an effort to stop jackson was afoot
leland said he did not know who was behind the attempt, and said he knew of no party leaders joining such a movement. but he said it did not appear to be confined to southern white democrats
there is some movement afoot,'' leland said. ``we can't put our hands on it. we don't know who the leader is. but we do understand ... different players of the democratic party have been approached.''
he named democratic national chairman paul kirk and house speaker jim wright as among those approached. contacted later, kirk and a spokesman for wright said no one had talked to them about keeping the nomination away from jackson
i haven't talked to anyone, and no one's approached me,'' said kirk, who earlier this week rejected talk of a movement to block jackson
although jackson fell substantially behind michael dukakis in connecticut's primary tuesday, his 2-to-1 victory in michigan on saturday has forced democratic leaders to confront the possibility that jackson could end the primary season as top vote getter and perhaps delegate leader
in recognition of that, a group representing the top ranks of washington's old-line democratic establishment _ including presidential adviser clark clifford, former party chairman john white and one-time mondale aide richard moe _ met with jackson over breakfast at a downtown hotel
they came away praising jackson and insisting they wouldn't be party to any effort to block him
i don't think there will be at this particular time, especially from the south, a stop jesse jackson movement,'' said charles whitehead, state democratic party chairman from florida, after the session
whitehead acknowledged widespread concern among democrats about the prospect of jackson winning the nomination, however. in the wake of michigan, some democrats have privately voiced the fear that the liberal black jackson could prove an unelectable nominee in the fall and damage other democratic candidates
i would be less than honest with you if i didn't tell you there is absolutely an awful lot of apprehension out there among an awful lot of democrats about the nomination of jesse jackson,'' whitehead said. ``sure there is
they're afraid of nominating someone that they consider unelectable,'' he said
but whitehead, whose state primary was won by dukakis, the massachusetts governor, said there was ``that same apprehension about nominating an eastern liberal.''
you've got a fear there if you nominate an eastern liberal, you've nominated another (walter) mondale,'' who lost 49 states as the 1984 nominee, he said
most democratic party insiders have said this week that any public effort to block jackson would be damaging and alienate blacks and other voters the party will need in the fall, no matter who the nominee is. ``you can't win with him and can't win without him,'' one political source said, speaking on condition of anonymity
another source close to democratic party politics said concerns among party leaders had eased with the connecticut vote following ``two days of gnashing of teeth.''
he said a feeling was growing that jackson was strengthening the party with new voters, and that they should not be discouraged by suggestions jackson would be denied the nomination. but, he contended, the remaining calender of big-state primaries decreases the likelihood jackson would end up with the most delegates
fueling talk of a stop-jackson effort was a campaign begun this week by alabama democratic chairman john baker. he suggested in a letter to party leaders around the south that they form a group of unpledged convention delegates who will commit themselves to ``the most electable'' presidential candidate
baker denied his effort was aimed at jackson, but he came under fire in his own state. a black state senator, michael figures of mobile, a jackson supporter, accused baker of racist remarks
it's not my intention to sound racist,'' baker said. ``but i need to be candid, and i need to talk practical politics. we've got to think who can beat george bush and the rest of the republicans.''
israel's surrogate militia raided a south lebanon town in tanks wednesday with support from helicopter gunships, killing seven people, wounding 15 and knocking down scores of houses, police reported
the assault on the shiite moslem town of kfar roumman at 9:45 a.m. coincided with a general strike and joint lebanese-palestinian demonstration in lebanon's moslem sectors in solidarity with the 4-month-old arab rebellion in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip
police and u.n. observers said militiamen of the south lebanon army in 12 soviet-designed t-54 tanks advanced to kfar roumman, half a mile west of the ``security zone'' israel maintains in south lebanon, and fought guerrillas of the hezbollah, or party of god. the tanks were supplied by israel, which captured them from arab armies
police said sla militiamen killed five civilians and two hezbollah fighters in a house-to-house search of kfar roumman, a town of 2,000 people, and pulled back to the security zone four hours later
israeli helicopter gunships strafed kfar roumman with machine guns, police reported
they said the militiamen advanced behind a barrage of 155mm howitzer fire from israeli positions in the zone
according to the police report, kfar roumman was hit with more than 140 rounds from tank cannon and mortars before the assault and 13 people were wounded. they said two other people were wounded by shells that fell on nabatiyeh, a market town nearby
a police spokesman said the militia apparently was pursuing hezbollah fighters who attacked two of its outposts before dawn
islamic resistance (hezbollah) fighters were seen withdrawing from kfar roumman. the village has been devastated by shelling,'' said the spokesman, whose name was withheld in keeping with regulations
u.n. peacekeeping observers in the south said israeli troops and sla militiamen had expected attacks on land day, which marks a clash on march 30, 1976, between israeli troops and arab citizens over land confiscation in the occupied territories
banks, schools, shops, restaurants and other businesses were closed in beirut, the northern port of tripoli, the bekaa valley of east lebanon and the southern ports of sidon and tyre. the strike was called by the national committee in support of the palestinian uprising
several demonstrations were held in jordan, most of whose citizens are palestinian. more than 500 students chanting ``revolution until victory!'' rallied at the jordan university campus in amman
about 10,000 palestinian and lebanese leftists marched in moslem west beirut, escorted by police and carrying banners. similar demonstrations were reported in sidon and tyre
banners reading ``the youngsters of lebanon praise the uprising in palestine'' and ``down with shultz's (peace) plan'' were among those raised in beirut
leaders of palestinian groups, some of them at odds, and representatives of several leftist militia factions united in the throng that marched across beirut's main corniche mazraa thoroughfare
it was the strongest lebanese expression of solidarity with the palestinians since the invading israeli army drove the palestine liberation organization out of the country in 1982
vice president george bush, moving quickly to put distance between himself and the controversy surrounding attorney general edwin meese iii, said wednesday the justice department ``has to be above reproach.''
bush said he was troubled by the resignation of top justice department officials, but ``i'm not going to pass judgment'' on whether meese should resign
the republican presidential candidate, in a statement devoid of any support for the embattled attorney general, said meese must make up his own mind on quitting
bush said meese would not hold the top law enforcement post in a bush administration
campaigning for the first day without a major gop rival, bush was peppered by reporters with questions on the meese controversy
two top justice department officials quit on tuesday amid reports of meese's mounting legal difficulties
clearly eager to keep the matter from becoming a campaign issue, bush told reporters, ``morale in (the) justice (department) is very important.''
it seems to me that the justice department has to be above reproach.propriety,'' he said
speaking for himself, bush said, ``i want to hold an ethical standard so high that there's no perception of wrongdoing.''
asked whether meese would be attorney general in a bush administration, the vice president said, ``no, nor would any other member of the (reagan) cabinet, because i want to have a new cabinet.''
when a reporter suggested that bush's position on whether meese should resign remained unclear, bush responded: ``that's what i intend.''
he also said he didn't think the affair would rub off on his campaign, but suggested, ``i'm sure my opponents will try to use it.''
i'm not going to prejudge mr. meese. i'd like to find out a little more about what is happening here,'' bush said
meanwhile, bush told a lunchtime rally that it didn't matter to him which candidate the democrats finally nominate
i will take on whoever the democrats put up,'' he said
as to whether republicans would prefer running against democrat jesse jackson rather than michael dukakis, bush said, ``i don't plan to get in there and fine-tune what's happening on the democratic side.''
bush wrapped up three days of campaigning in wisconsin. during his visit, he picked up the endorsement of former rivals rep. jack kemp and sen. bob dole quit the race, giving him a virtual lock on the gop nomination
bush aides said the vice president would skip a visit back to wisconsin that had been tentatively planned for monday so he can focus his attention on consolidating his support and planning future campaign appearances
spokesman pete teeley said dole, who withdrew from the gop race on tuesday, was expected to make campaign appearances on bush's behalf _ but specifics had not been worked out
a french jet fighter crashed and exploded wednesday near a nuclear power plant, but officials said the facility could have withstood the force of the impact if the plane had hit it
the pilot of the mirage jet fighter was killed when his plane went down at 9:20 a.m. about a mile from the isar plant at the bavarian village of ohu
federal and state officials said the concrete domes covering west german nuclear plants are strong enough to withstand a direct hit from a plummeting airliner, so there was no risk of a nuclear accident
there was no danger at the power plant,'' said edith volz, a spokeswoman for the state-run bavarian utilities in munich. ``the complex is protected by heavy concrete walls and the reactors are safe from plane crashes.''
the mirage burst into flames and exploded on impact, spreading debris over a wide area, police said
the fighter took off from the strasbourg-entzheim air base outside of strasbourg, france, and was on a ``totally routine, low-altitude mission,'' according to a french air force spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with defense ministry regulations
the french defense ministry identified the pilot as lt. thierry millet, 26, and said he was not flying unusually low or close to a nuclear facility
france has military forces based in west germany, and its military aircraft frequently fly training missions over west german territory
anti-nuclear activists used the incident to renew criticism of atomic power plants and of low-level military flights that are common over bavaria
opposition social democrats in bavaria said they would bring the matter up for debate in the state's parliament
this is proof that the authorities have underestimated the dangers posed'' by military training flights, said dietmar franzke, a social democratic state delegate
the plant at ohu is an 870-megawatt isar i reactor, which began producing electricity in 1977. isar ii, a 1,300-megawatt reactor that is also located in the area, is not yet on line, officials said
military aircraft are barred from flying over nuclear power plants, according to alfons metzger, a spokesman for the bavarian interior ministry
in bonn, defense ministry officials said there were no signs indicating the french pilot had failed to adhere to those regulations. acquaint.</note>
exiled stage director yuri lyubimov expressed his desire to return to the soviet union in an unusual newspaper interview that could signal official willingness to allow him to come back
lyubimov was interviewed by the government newspaper izvestia in madrid, where he viewed four perfomances by moscow's taganka theater of maxim gorky's ``mother.''
lyubimov, 70, founded the taganka theater and over 20 years turned it into moscow's most popular modern theater with his avant-garde productions
the director struggled constantly with censors. in july 1983 he was allowed to travel to london to stage fyodor dostoyevsky's ``crime and punishment'' amid speculation authorities did not want him to return
in march 1984 he was thrown out of the communist party, and four months later his soviet citizenship was revoked
lyubimov has staged productions around the world since then. he took israeli citizenship this year and has moved to jerusalem with his wife, katalin, and son, peter. he is almost never mentioned in the official press
in its article on tuesday, izvestia stressed that soviet writers and artists have more freedom under mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms, in a possible effort to show the differences between lyubimov and authorities have narrowed enough to allow him to return
lyubimov reiterated his previous statement that he would like to return to work in the soviet union if he were guaranteed artistic freedom, but that he was making no political demands
we are talking only about the creative side of my life,'' he was quoted as saying
after more than four years abroad, ``in order to once again gain strength, survive, one needs to stand on his native land, on which he was raised, where his fathers and grandfathers lived,'' lyubimov said
even while he has been exiled, he told the newspaper, he has concentrated on staging productions that acquaint the world with russian culture
he praised the more open literature that is being published under gorbachev's policy of glasnost, and said, ``it is necessary to come, to see, and to work in the theater.''
on year ago, lyubimov and a group of other exiled scientists and artists wrote an open letter expressing their doubts about gorbachev's reforms, calling the soviet union a ``gravely sick country.''
the letter was printed by the weekly moscow news, and the writers were criticized bitterly in the official media, which accused them of wishing evil on their native land
izvestia reported that taganka's current director, nikolai gubenko, who also was present at the interview, said the theater wants lyubimov to return and see what it is doing. ``after that, he himself can decide his fate,' gubenko was quoted as saying
lyubimov was quoted as saying his meetings in madrid with taganka actors he once directed were ``good and difficult at the same time.''
sen. bob dole said wednesday that his failed presidential campaign had made serious tactical mistakes but added that they weren't the main reason for his downfall
in an interview a day after he quit the presidential race, the kansas republican expressed some of his frustrations over his unsuccessful battle with vice president george bush for the gop nomination
the bottom line is that you can't beat ronald reagan,'' dole said. ``i was running against ronald reagan jr. in the south.''
that was a reference to bush's success in campaigning as reagan's vice president and logical heir. ``it's just this promotion idea that you just ought to go up the ladder,'' dole said
he also said republican party ``winner-take-all'' rules in the primaries and caucuses contributed to his exit from the campaign
if delegates were divided proportionally, he said, ``i'd still be in the race.''
asked the one thing he would do differently in his campaign, dole replied: ``keep the press off the plane.''
he complained that reporters on the campaign plane ``sit back there and they scheme up these little things and the next thing they're in time or newsweek.''
dole said he thought he had received some unfair news coverage during the campaign. for example, he singled out the numerous stories written about one of his kansas associates, dave owen, who resigned as national finance chairman of the dole campaign in january after reports raised questions involving his financial dealings
but apart from all that, dole said that his campaign organization had blundered, particularly in new hampshire and south carolina, and that those mistakes weakened his candidacy early in the nominating process
for example, he did not respond to last-minute new hampshire television ads by bush raising questions whether dole cowld increase taxes. in addition, his campaign spent heavily early in the nominating process, which caused problems in later contests
south carolina we probably should have bypassed instead of getting in there,'' said dole
bush's win in south carolina, he maintained, delivered a boost to the vice president and helped him sweep the super tuesday primaries that followed in the south, including north carolina, missouri and oklahoma _ states the dole campaign had hoped to win
now had we won new hampshire, we still would have had a tough race,'' dole said
illinois was the next battleground after super tuesday, and dole said, ``i knew that we weren't going to win illinois and i knew then it was probably over.''
he said many of his friends and advisers urged him to remain in the presidential race even when it appeared he had almost no chance to win the nomination
you can't do it unless you've got the money,'' said dole
the campaign, he said, would end with a ``little debt'' but he said he didn't know the exact amount
overall, dole said, he was pleased with the fund-raising ability of his campaign and said he had ``good organizations in a number of states.''
but he expressed reservations about the management of the campaign, saying, ``i think as far as organization, i'm not certain whether we had enough direction.''
dole did not criticize william brock, his campaign chairman who directed the operation, but said the national political director, norman watts, ``i don't believe was strong enough.''
james and suzy are having a tiff. and to the delight of gossip-loving new yorkers, they're having it out in public _ in the columns they write for new york newsday and the new york post
it began last week, when james _ that's james revson, newsday's new society columnist _ wrote that he felt ``cheated and used'' by suzy, who wrote in the post about a party she did not attend
what specifically bothered revson (one of the revsons, of revlon cosmetics fame) was that suzy mentioned 32 people who supposedly were at the party, but only 12 of whom actually showed up
suzy was on vacation (``on the sunswept isle of mustique'') when both her column and revson's appeared. but by wednesday she was back. and suzy _ that's just plain suzy to you, aileen mehle to her friends _ was furious
in a column that combined the tact of joan rivers with the politesse of sean penn, suzy called revson ``a liar,'' ``a rat,'' a ``know-nothing,'' ``a nut,'' ``a jerk'' and ``a snake.'' among other things
to be sure, suzy admitted she had written about the party, thrown by metropolitan museum chairman (and new york times publisher) arthur ``punch'' sulzberger, in advance. she said it was the only way she could get out of town for her vacation (which was ``heaven.'')
and yes, she said, it's true that some of the people she said were at the party never did show up
and yes, ``i should have yanked the whole thing or at least the names the (press) release said would attend.''
but is she apologizing? not a chance
i bow in accuracy and meticulousness and decency to no one,'' she wrote. ``that is the reason i have survived as a star all these long years _ that and because in my field i am the best and the brightest there is.''
and dear readers, fans and publicity-seekers, i would like to go on record as telling the world that any place rat revson is, i will not be. do not invite me anywhere if you invite him. just call it a boycott _ or even a suzycott.''
the target of the suzycott says he is unimpressed. ``i'm not joining it,'' he said. ``i refuse to join it even if she asks me.''
revson said he thought suzy's column ``showed a certain lack of restraint on her part. ... i didn't know that a lady knew those words, or how to spell them.''
on a serious note,'' he added, ``columnists are journalists, columnists are reporters, and there are ethics. and nobody is allowed to break those.''
is he worried about the effect of the suzy controversy on his fledgling column?
i'm delighted,'' said revson, obviously holding to the theory that any publicity is good publicity. ``the next time i see her, i may buy her a drink.''
a city fire investigator wednesday said that three cubans who died battling a blaze at their consulate might have been saved if firefighters hadn't been kept outside the building for 15 minutes
investigator jacques plouffe criticized the cuban consulate for not informing the fire department of tuesday's fire
we might have saved three lives,'' he said
havana radio, monitored in miami, identified the dead as pablo gonzalez martinez, 35, an official at the trade office; norma goderich, 33, wife of a vice-consul; and jose perez salbaluco, 35, a consulate guard
they died fighting the blaze which apparently started on top floor of the four-story mansion
the blaze took 100 firefighters more than three hours to bring under control. its cause was under investigation
authorities first learned of the blaze when security guards at a nearby luxury apartment building reported smoke coming from the consulate roof
firefighters then rushed to the consulate but were held back for about 15 minutes before they were allowed to enter the building, located on the slopes of mount royal
by the time they got in, the fire was out of control
we had a little trouble getting in because there was nobody to answer the door,'' said the district fire chief, guy lafortune, who arrived about 7:30 p.m. ``they weren't expecting us because nobody (at the consulate) had called an alarm and everybody in the building was upstairs fighting the fire.''
under the 1963 vienna convention, authorities of the host country, such as police and firefighters, cannot enter consular premises without permission
consul-general lourdes urrutia only let the firefighters in after she received permission from cuban officials in ottawa
lafortune said the firefighters were allowed to fight the blaze on condition that they did not enter certain areas of the building
men were stationed at certain doors to keep us away. there was no fire in those areas,'' said lafortune
lafortune said his men had a hard time fighting the flames because every window on the fourth floor was either barred or heavily shuttered and nailed closed
he said he saw about a dozen guns of various kinds on the walls inside
firefighters said it was easier to get into the cuban consulate than into the nearby soviet consulate when it caught fire in january 1987. soviet officials tried to put out that fire with buckets of snow and a garden hose before firefighters were let in
in 1972, when the cuban trade commission in the north end was firebombed and one cuban was killed, cubans held firefighters and police off with submachine guns
and in 1954, the soviet embassy in ottawa burned to the ground after officials refused to allow firefighters to fight the fire
investigator plouffe said it took him and his partner armand villette about 25 minutes to gain entry to the building wednesday to retrieve some tools
a rabies outbreak in nearby chester county has prompted health officials to warn residents to avoid wild animals and take extra measures to protect pets and farm animals
the problem is big, and it is growing,'' harold russell, chief veterinarian for the county health department said tuesday. ``what we are seeing is the tip of a very massive iceberg.'' eastern parts of chester county are some 20 miles west of philadelphia
he warned the rabies virus, which last week forced officials to kill a horse, is likely to spread into philadelphia, especially among raccoons in the city's sprawling fairmount park
a total of 23 rabies cases have been confirmed in chester county this year, compared to 36 in all of 1987, said ruthie ketterer, secretary for the state health department's acute infectious disease division
lancaster county, the next county west of chester, has reported 37 cases. the total for the state for 1988 is 101, ketterer said
dr. robert sharrar, director of philadelphia's office of health promotion and disease control, said wednesday the city was monitoring the rabies situation in chester county and surrounding counties and states
the last known case of human rabies in philadelphia was in 1938, and the last case in a dog was 1948, he said. health officials declared the city rabies free in 1975, but would revoke that designation at the first rabies case and recommend rabies treatment for anyone bitten by dogs or cats thereafter, he said
rabies is a viral disease that attacks the brain and is almost always fatal. a vaccine for humans and dogs was developed by louis pasteur in the 1880s and scientists are working to develop an oral vaccine which would work when eaten by wild animals
government agents confiscated nearly 685 pounds of cocaine aboard an ecuadorean boat traveling through the panama canal, a pro-government newspaper reported wednesday
the report in critica said agents of the national department of investigations detained the ship isla baltra after receiving information from ecuadorean police about the cargo
the boat was headed for barcelona, spain
critica said the ship was stopped as it completed its transit of the canal, boarded by navy squads and special anti-narcotics agents, then taken to the port of balboa where it was searched
the illegal drug was found in 278 packages in a container of prefabricrated building material aboard the ship, the report said. it did not say if any arrests were made or give the estimated value of the drug
the united states has called for the ouster of panama's strongman, gen. manuel noriega, since he was indicted on drug-trafficking charges in february in florida. he says he is innocent
prices farmers got for raw products this month averaged the same as they did in february but still were 7.4 percent above march 1987, the agriculture department said wednesday
the department's agricultural statistics board reported higher prices for lettuce, cattle, eggs and broiler chickens, while farmers received lower prices for hogs, milk, wheat and sweet corn
the price of lettuce increased sharply from february to march but was well below record levels during the november through january 1988 period,'' the report said. ``calf prices dropped slightly from february to march but were at the second highest level since june of 1979.''
prices of cattle sold for beef were the highest since may 1979, the report said. hog and wheat prices decline from february, while corn prices rose slightly
department economists say net cash income of farmers may be in the range of $50 billion to $55 billion this year, down from the record level of $57 billion in 1987. that is the difference between cash receipts and cash expenses during the calendar year
consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987
according to the preliminary march figures, based mostly on mid-month averages, the index for crop prices was up 0.9 percent from february and averaged 10 percent more than a year ago
commercial vegetable prices rose 11 percent from last month but were down 7.1 percent from march 1987
higher prices for lettuce and tomatoes were major contributors to the increase in the (vegetable) index,'' the report said. ``the increase was moderated by lower prices for sweet corn, asparagus, celery and onions.''
lettuce prices were reported at $21.30 per 100 pounds, compared with $11.10 in february and $35.60 in january
the index for livestock and livestock products was down 0.7 percent from february but was 4.2 percent above march 1987. prices were higher for cattle, eggs and broilers but were lower for hogs and milk
march farm commodity prices averaged 130 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures, the same as in february. a year ago the march index was 121 percent
no new figures for farm production costs were included in the report. those have been confined to quarterly averages because of budget cutbacks
in january, however, farm expenses were unchanged from last fall but averaged 4.4 percent above a year earlier. the next quarterly figures will be reported in april
the report said:
_cattle averaged $68.40 per 100 pounds of live weight nationally, up from $67.40 in february and the $59.30 reported for march 1987. those are averages for all types of cattle sold as beef
_hogs averaged $41.90 per 100 pounds, compared with $45.80 in march and $47.40 a year earlier
_corn, at $1.84 a bushel, was up from $1.83 in february and the average of $1.47 per bushel a year earlier
_wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures, averaged $2.64 per bushel, compared with $2.79 in february and $2.57 a year earlier
_rice averaged $8.46 per 100 pounds, compared with $8.97 in february and $3.62 a year earlier
_soybeans were $5.93 per bushel, compared with $5.97 in february and $4.73 a year earlier
_upland cotton was reported at 56.9 cents per pound, compared with 56.8 in february and 47.5 cents in march 1987
_eggs were 50.8 cents per dozen, compared with 46.9 cents in february and 54.4 cents a year earlier
_milk was $12 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.30 in february and $12.50 a year earlier
_broilers were 27.5 cents per pound, live weight, compared with 25.7 cents in february and 29.1 cents a year ago
seven hundred of the u.s. troops sent to honduras on march 17-18 left palmerola air base for the united states and a u.s. spokesman said the rest will be home by thursday
the guys that turn out the lights will be leaving tomorrow (thursday),'' said maj. gary hovatter, u.s. military public affairs officer at palmerola
hovatter said planes left at a rate of about one an hour wednesday carrying the 700 soldiers and equipment back to fort ord, calif
president reagan sent 3,200 american soldiers to honduras after president jose azcona hoyo asked for help. azcona said that sandinista troops from neighboring nicaragua had invaded honduras in pursuit of contra rebels
the sandinistas reportedly retreated after the honduran air force twice bombed the border region, but the u.s. troops stayed on to finish emergency training exercises with honduran troops at five bases throughout honduras
the soldiers from the 82nd airborne division at fort bragg, n.c., and the 7th light infantry division at fort ord began to return home monday
hovatter said the last of the soldiers, about 80 from the 82nd airborne, would leave thursday after ``policing up the place.''
the united states maintains a permanent operation of about 1,100 to 1,500 soldiers in its joint task force bravo operation at palmerola, the largest and most important u.s. military headquarters in central america north of panama
the base is about 40 miles northwest of tegucigalpa, the honduran capital
hovatter said by telephone wednesday that ``some of the planes are carrying more equipment than people.''
the americans brought about 2.3 million pounds of equipment with them, including two tanks, 12 105mm howitzers, machine guns, ammunition and helicopters
it's gone very smoothly,'' hovatter said of the redeployment. ``we've had minimal delays and no incidents or accidents.''
sen. paul simon, entering territory staked out by fellow democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson, stood in front of a chrysler corp. plant wednesday and declared he is more qualified to take workers' concerns to the white house
when asked whether he has hesitated criticizing jackson for fear of offending black voters, simon said: ``you have to be careful. you don't want to be perceived as anti-black.'' but he added, ``i don't have problems running against anyone.''
i'm not here knocking others,'' simon said, ``but i think experience is one of the things you should look at.''
jackson had led an emotional rally earlier this year at the auto plant, where 5,500 workers are scheduled to be laid off by the end of september. jackson's support for the workers and his call to end ``economic violence'' won him the endorsement of the united auto workers union local 72
simon, at a news conference next to the plant, said he has a similar message plus the congressional experience to translate it into action
i have been fighting for (workers') policies on the washington scene, not just with speeches,'' simon said. ``i offer not only passion, but programs.''
simon, who won the march 15 illinois primary, is campaigning for support in wisconsin's primary april 5. ``i'm going to do well in wisconsin,'' he said, ``and we're going on to atlanta,'' site of the democratic national convention july 18-21
about 20 simon supporters were on hand for the news conference, along with some auto workers
i think he is speaking for the workers as well as jackson,'' said bill seep, an employee of the plant
another employee, phil haney, said he expected the workers to stay unified behind jackson, though he added some might choose simon when they cast their ballots. ``you can't fault anyone who votes for simon,'' he said
simon said he would try to rebuild the country's manufacturing base by removing tax breaks for companies that move jobs overseas and by giving corporations incentives to boost production in the united states
he added that he came to kenosha ``because of this plant and what it represents. what we have had is an administration that has elevated and sanctified greed.''
he accused chrysler of deciding to halt production without giving enough consideration to the impact on the workers and the community. `navel.' picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng: arnaud de.</note>
some unification church members are upset because their church founder, the rev. sun myung moon, believes one of his followers from zimbabwe is the reincarnation of his son, according to a report published wednesday
the affair began last fall at the unification theological seminary in upstate new york, where a senior named charles was believed to be hearing and relaying messages from moon's deceased son, ``lord'' heung jin nim, the washington post said, quoting former and present church members
heung jin nim was killed in an automobile accident in 1984 at age 17
according to the post account:
dick richard, a former seminary student who recently left the church, said that in ``mid-november, i was told there was a black brother from africa who had been prepared by jesus ... and that heung jin nim had assumed his body.''
it obviously scared a lot of people there .. but they went along with the whole thing because it came from reverend moon, the messiah.''
the reincarnation incident has caused what some followers of moon are calling the biggest theological upheaval in the 34-year history of the unification church, in part because the zimbabwean reportedly has been slapping church members and elders
officials at the washington times, which is owned by church members, have tried to distance themselves from the affair
from the bottom of my navel, i don't want to know about this,'' said ron godwin, the times' senior vice president for business. ``i know that such a person exists and that he's been preaching in the church, but i will walk a mile not to get involved.''
arnaud de borchgrave, chief editor of the times, at first dismissed the young zimbabwean as a plant from communist north korea
the north koreans have had a very strong presence in zimbabwe since day one,'' de borchgrave said in an interview from paris
it just sounds so ridiculous,'' de borchgrave said. ``the nameless zimbabwean _ that strikes me as suspicious right there. ... i've asked people, `who the hell is this zimbabwean?' and nobody can tell you.''
john rees, co-owner with de borchgrave of a private intelligence newsletter, ``early warning,'' said de borchgrave's ``attitude was primarily one of concern that it would make the paper look ludicrous.''
the zimbabwean, who has taken the name of heung jin nim, has been traveling to church parishes around the world, preaching
this guy talks non-stop,'' said john raineri, a photographer for the world and i, sister publication to the times. ``i've seen him speak for three days straight he doesn't rest the whole time.''
one of the most disturbing aspects of the affair, church members say, is violence attributed to the zimbabwean
the president of the times, bo hi pak, was admitted to georgetown univeristy hospital for tests last dec. 9-17, saying he had recently fallen down a flight of stairs. no injuries were found, but later pak underwent surgery in south korea to repair a damaged blood vessel in his skull, according to times executives
pak is moon's closest deputy, and stories that he had been injured spread quickly through the church. kate tsubata, a church member, was skeptical until she heard a church elder describe a meeting in which moon was asked about the reincarnated son's reported violence
the elder said that ``even colonel pak had been beaten,'' tsubata said. ``he just let it drop. ... it was quite significant.''
tsubata spoke of a friend who was slapped repeatedly by the zimbabwean. ``he described them as stinging slaps to the face, causing him to see stars,'' she said. ``but afterwards, he felt good.''
gordon anderson, secretary-general of the moon-financed professors world peace academy, reported similar behavior during a church ceremony in the world missions center in manhattan. the zimbabwean walked among the 100 church members present, listening to their confessions and instructing them to repent, usually through prayers or fasting
he did slap, but he didn't strike hard enough to hurt anyone. he cuffed me on the ear a little bit,'' anderson said. pell comment. picks up 17th graf pvs, bgng: republican senators</note>
the senate foreign relations committee recommended overwhelmingly wednesday that the senate ratify a historic treaty to eliminate all u.s. and soviet medium-range nuclear weapons
this is a small step away from the nuclear brink,'' said sen. alan cranston, d-calif., said following the committee's 17-2 vote
it means the elevator of nuclear escalation will finally stop and hopefully descend,'' said committee chairman claiborne pell, d-r.i
cranston said his head count shows no more than five senators will vote against the intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty when the full senate takes up the treaty, probably late next month. ratification requires a two-thirds senate majority, 67 votes if all 100 senators are present and voting
the only dissenting votes inside the committee were cast by sens. jesse helms, r-n.c., and larry pressler, r-s.d. helms has worked vigorously to derail the treaty
the resounding committee vote papered over a bitter partisan dispute over an amendment added to the treaty on tuesday with the aim of assuring that the meaning of the pact cannot be reinterpreted by a future president without the consent of congress
many moderate republicans said the amendment represented a partisan jab at president reagan and his administration's reinterpretation of the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty to permit the deployment of a star wars missile defense system
several gop lawmakers said the controversy may cause them to reassess their support of the treaty and cranston said he may be willing to search for a compromise when the senate debates the issue
the treaty, signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, requires both sides to destroy, within three years, all nuclear-armed missiles with a range of 300 miles to 3,400 miles
these include all soviet ss-20 and other medium- and shorter-range missiles aimed at targets in western europe and all of the smaller force of u.s. pershing 2 and ground-launched cruise missiles stationed in europe and aimed at the soviet union
the treaty is the first accord in the history of arms control to require the actual destruction of the missiles that carry nuclear warheads. and it is the first to require on-site inspection to verify compliance with its terms
the foreign relations committee voted after 21 days of hearings in which scores of expert witnesses testified. the senate intelligence and armed services committees also conducted an intense examination of the agreement and recommended it be adopted, the latter voting its approval, 18-2
the armed services committee did express some lingering concerns, and in final testimony on wednesday, ambassador maynard glitman, the chief u.s. inf negotiator, responded to them
glitman said ``futuristic'' weapons such as lasers and particle beam generators are in fact banned by the treaty if they are carried on ``weapons delivery vehicles'' within the prohibited range
the soviets, the ambassador said, ``understand that all future (weapons) systems falling within the criteria will be banned.''
and if an unarmed medium-range missile were to strike and destroy a target through impact alone, it would be considered a weapon if it had been designed for that purpose, he said
later, sen. sam nunn, d-ga., the armed services chairman, said glitman's statement had not resolved the issue and that he would seek a more definitive clarification during senate debate
nunn said he might seek passage of an amendment to the treaty requiring the administration to obtain a specific statement from the soviets acknowledging that they had agreed not to produce, deploy or flight test futuristic medium-range weapons
pell told a news conference this issue is one of several hurdles facing the treaty on the senate floor. he said he is hopeful all obstacles can be overcome and the treaty ratified before reagan's summit meeting with gorbachev in late may
if it is not, he said, reagan will be embarrassed and in a weakened position to pursue the far more significant strategic arms reduction treaty aimed at cutting u.s. and soviet intercontinental missile forces by up to 50 percent
republican senators complained at length about the committee's 12-7 decision on tuesday to add the provision aimed at ensuring that administration testimony and official description of the treaty is ``authoritative'' and binding
the provision says no future president can change the u.s. interpretation of the treaty without congressional approval, either by senate ratification of a new treaty or by the house and senate passing a separate law
it very frankly may change my position in response to the treaty,'' said sen. rudy boschwitz, r-minn., contending the measure was aimed at the strategic defense initiative and the administration's reinterpretation of the abm treaty
cranston said the measure was worded to apply only to the inf treaty, not to any other pact or to future accords
but boschwitz insisted it was politically motivated. ``i think we are making a great mistake. it weakens the value of the treaty very substantially. i would hope that on the floor of the senate we would be able to remove this provision.''
pressler called the amendment, ``mischievous and partisan.''
it will lead to the defeat of this treaty entirely because (with it), the votes aren't there,'' he said
the new executives of united press international said wednesday that they intend to turn the deficit-plagued news service into a profit-making organization within two years by eliminating about 150 jobs, focusing on business news and embarking on joint electronic ventures
there'll be no liquidation of upi,'' declared chairman earl w. brian
president paul steinle said upi ``will remain a full-service, 24-hour-a-day, seven-day-a-week, worldwide supplier of news and information.''
the two executives, who gained operating control of upi from mexican publisher mario vazquez rana on feb. 19, said they were determined to reverse upi's persistently heavy losses, which average $2 million a month and totaled $20 million last year
brian told a news conference in this washington suburb that his ``turnaround business plan'' calls for stabilizing the company within three to six months and making a $100,000 profit in the july-september quarter of 1989
to achieve the turnaround, brian said he expects to raise $15 million in permanent equity financing, mostly from outside investors. in the meantime, he said, $5 million in bridge loans will be made available by wnw group inc., aided by infotechnology inc
brian is chairman of wnw group, the media investment company that operates upi, and of infotech, a new york-based information technology and venture capital firm
the upi executives said they are committed to ensuring that the 81-year-old wire service survives and flourishes into the 21st century
vazquez rana rescued upi from chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings in june 1986 by purchasing the company for $41 million. he reportedly put an additional $50 million into upi before he relinquished control of his stock for 10 years to brian's wnw group in february for an undisclosed cash payment
the new executives said upi will save $10 million in the first year in administrative cost controls, $5 million in staff reductions and $5 million in deficit financing
there have been published reports that 400 or more editorial personnel alone would be laid off at upi,'' steinle said in a statement. ``in fact, there will be fewer than 150 net staff reductions, and less than 100 of those will be editorial. ... at this time, we do not anticipate further cutbacks.''
the executives said this means that the current 1,280 upi employees worldwide will be reduced 14 percent to about 1,130 employees through layoffs, early retirements and attrition. the biggest percentage of layoffs will occur in administrative positions, brian said
steinle said wire service guild officers were briefed on the plan wednesday morning. ``their response was polite,'' he said. ``they were interested, i think they were pleased.''
sean mccormally, chairman of the guild's negotiating committee, said the union agrees that upi needs stability. ``we believe the logical next step toward stability is for management to reach a fair and equitable contract with its employees,'' he said. ``that added stability should prove attractive to potential investors.''
upi officials said contract negotiations already had begun. guild members at upi have been working without a contract since april 30, when the old one expired. upi management declared an impasse in contract talks and instituted a new set of ``work rules'' in november
mccormally said the union is happy that steinle had promised no further layoffs beyond the 150 announced wednesday. ``but we are insisting our members have the protections guaranteed by a contract and by effective union representation,'' he said
the company executives stressed that the 180 upi bureaus worldwide will continue virtually unchanged
asked how upi would improve news coverage with fewer employees, steinle said the staff will be ``not as large but more focused,'' concentrating on stories most in demand by subscribers while providing full coverage of the major stories of the day
brian said no existing upi services, such as photos or sports, will be dropped, although he said money will be saved by transferring a spanish-language translation desk from upi headquarters in washington to latin america, possibly mexico city
the executives said upi will concentrate on areas with major client support, such as state and regional reporting, and will emphasize technical reporting that local news media are unable to provide
this includes an increased emphasis on business and financial news and analysis and its effect on the consumer, plus more and better reporting in areas such as health, science, law and medicine,'' steinle said
brian said upi's ``patchwork quilt'' communications system will be streamlined and its ``shoebox accounting system'' will be modernized. he predicted additional savings by pooling upi's resources with those of other companies offering the potential for joint ventures in the information industry
for example, he said that within the next few months, upi will be ready to take part in a new, low-cost electronic news and information service called dbc supernews and to provide new regional business and stocks reports around the country
brian said supernews will allow anyone with a personal computer at more than 28 million cable television sites to receive news on any subject via satellite from financial news network, a 24-hour cable tv network that is a subsidiary of infotech
the news would be gathered by comtex scientific corp. from upi and other major news sources in a venture also involving data broadcasting corp., an fnn subsidiary
brian said upi is looking at dozens of other possible ventures, including data base and electronic feeds to corporate and government users and serving as distributor for other information products
upi's national managing editor, bill ferguson, said one example of how productivity will be increased is the use of a computer system that can edit a story automatically in three separate styles for newspapers, radio and television
we will still be the second major news service in the united states, not quite as large as we were before, but certainly more focused, with more business systems behind it, with more chances of surviving over a longer period of time and hopefully with more success,'' steinle said
said brian: ``we have an established and successful track record in turnaround management. we know how to operate companies within their means and we have links to other companies with significant future joint-venture potential for upi in the information industry.''
steinle said upi will constantly assess market reaction to its services. ``as a market-driven company, we will supply what the market wants and is willing to pay for,'' he said
the treasury department announced wednesday it was selling $2.56 billion in 20-year bonds to the government of mexico as part of an innovative effort to help solve that country's debt problems
mexico will pay $492 million in cash for the zero-coupon bonds, so-called because they are sold at a deep discount from the face amount and pay no interest until they mature
the sale of the u.s. securities was the final step in an innovative procedure unveiled last december. mexico sought to induce foreign banks to forgive a portion of their loans by offering, in exchange, smaller quantities of mexican government bonds that would be backed by collateral consisting of u.s. treasury securities
banks were asked to bid for the bonds, offering to cancel their loans at a discount
backers of the plan had hoped to reduce mexico's debt burden by up to $10 billion, but when the bids were opened on march 2, the amount of debt reduction amounted to a disappointing $1.1 billion
the mexican finance ministry rejected nearly half of the bids it received as insufficient. the bids accepted would retire $3.66 billion in debt at an average discount of 67.66 cents on the dollar, offering $2.56 billion worth of mexican bonds in exchange
the $2.56 billion in zero-coupon bonds sold by u.s. treasury on wednesday will be used as collateral to back up the mexican bonds
a machine that sends a shockwave into the body to break up kidney stones is effective and less risky than invasive surgery, a panel of experts concluded wednesday following a conference at the national institutes of health
the panel, organized to reach a consensus on how best to treat and prevent kidney stones, recommended use of the extracorporeal shockwave lithotriptor to treat kidney stones smaller than 2 centimeters in diameter. it said that a combination of therapies, which may include surgery, may be needed for larger stones
the lithotriptor, introduced in the united states in 1984, uses a fluid shockwave, generated by an electrical pulse, to break up stones in the kidney or in the duct that drains the kidney. once the stones are broken up, they can be more easily passed out of the body. the procedure routinely does not require surgery
more than a half million people have been treated with the lithotriptor worldwide, the panel said, and it has been proven to be effective
but the experts cautioned that because lithotriptsy is new, ``the long-term effects of the therapy are unknown.''
dr. fredric l. coe, a professor of medicine at the university of chicago and chairman of the panel, said there have been reports of elevated blood pressure among some lithotriptsy patients, and there have been cases where the therapy causes kidney injury. he said these problems need to be further studied
for kidney stones larger than 2 centimeters, the panel recommended the use of a combined therapy that would include a surgical procedure called nephrolithotomy. using this technique, surgeons make a small incision near the kidney and then insert a flexible tube that can be manuevered to the site of the kidney stone. by manipulating instruments through the tube, the surgeon can break up the kidney stone and remove it
coe said the panel recommended a therapy system in which stones larger than 2 centimeters would be removed by nephrolithotomy. small stones or fragments could then be treated with lithotripsy. later, if needed, a second removal surgery could be performed. he said this combination was preferrable to repeated sessions of lithotripsy
open surgery, where a wide incision is made and the kidney exposed, is required now only in rare cases involving special types of stones or other physical factors, coe said
kidney stones account for seven to 10 of every 1,000 hospital admissions in the united states. there are seven to 21 cases of kidney stone annually for every 10,000 persons. though the stones may cause great pain, they are rarely life-threatening
coe said about 70 percent of all kidney stone cases can be treated using lithotripsy
for prevention of stones, the panel recommended the use of medication for certain types of stones, a modification of diet where indicated, and increased fluid intake. increased urination, caused by a higher fluid intake, the panel said, can lower the concentration in the urine of chemicals that tend to form stones
kidney stones are formed when chemicals in the urine crystalize. about 80 percent of the stones are formed of calcium oxalate crystals. others are of calcium phosphate salts, uric acid, cystine or a combination of magnesium, ammonium and phosphate
fashion students at florida state university are putting their design talents to work for children stuck with cumbersome or awkward medical devices
parents of handicapped children buy ready-made clothes, then slash them and cut them to make them fit,'' emma kittles, a professor of clothing, textiles and merchandising said wednesday. ``it's almost impossible to buy clothing to fit the devices their children have to wear.''
kittles has challenged a class to design clothing that is functional, comfortable and has style. their results will be compiled in a step-by-step teaching manual on designing clothing for disabled children
thinking of children 2 to 13, the students must design clothes that would be easy to put on and would camouflage any medical devices
for children in wheelchairs, the students must design outfits that eliminate excess folds and bulk and that are made of fabrics that don't chafe
another challenge for the students is designing clothes that make it easier for children to dress themselves with the help of front or side fasteners, such as velcro, large snaps and zippers with large tabs
children are at the stage that they are learning things to make them independent; one of those things is dressing themselves,'' said kittles. ``but even if the child cannot dress himself, the therapist and parents want clothing that is easy to manipulate on these children.''
because each child's needs are different, the students will interview the parents before measuring, buying fabrics and designing outfits. the child also shares personal preferences, such as favorite colors
the roman catholic patriarch of jerusalem, in a vatican radio interview wednesday, appealed to christians and ``responsible politicians'' to work for peace in the holy land
monsignor michel sabbah, a palestinian, said unrest in the israeli-occupied territories seemed worse as ``we celebrate holy week by reflecting on the suffering of christ and of the people of jerusalem and of all those in prison, dead, injured and suffering from hunger.''
he said the church could only pray and ``appeal to the whole world, to all the responsible politicians ... to put an end to this human tragedy that we have been living for so many years.''
sabbah, the first arab patriarch for latin rite catholics in the holy land, did not criticize either israelis or palestinians for the violence, and said both groups were suffering
he told the station in the telephone interview that he did not think the violence would disrupt easter ceremonies in the region. but he said is appealing to all christians to pray that political leaders can bring peace to the holy land
the head of the environmental protection agency has overruled a hearing examiner and banned use of the insecticide diazinon on golf course and sod farms in an effort to protect birds, epa said wednesday
agency administrator lee m. thomas said the major manufacturer, ciba-geigy corp. of greensboro, n.c., had ``failed to show by a preponderance of the evidence that even a single acre of turf will be destroyed if diazinon is canceled, much less that golf course or sod farm operations will be significantly affected by turf replacement costs.''
epa spokesman al heier said it was the first time epa had acted against a pesticide solely to protect birds, though the harm to birds was one reason ddt was banned in 1972
chief administrative law judge gerald harwood in january upheld ciba-geigy's contention that the benefits of use under additional restrictions outweighed the risk to birds
but thomas's decision, signed tuesday and released wednesday, said the company's benefits case was ``singularly weak.''
ciba-geigy's contention that the risk (to birds under new restrictions) would be low is undermined by the critical flaws in its field studies,'' thomas wrote
even disregarding those flaws, some risk to birds would remain, thomas said, and ``these risks are not justified by the benefit of avoiding a negligible cost increase to golf courses and sod farms.''
other insect control measures should add less than 0.5 percent to operating costs of golf courses and sod farms, thomas said
he said that ``unblemished golf courses and lawns are not as significant as the benefits to public health programs and food crops'' normally at issue in pesticide decisions
evidence of the benefits of maintaining price competition among products, avoiding turf damage and the comparative safety of diazinon ``is either nonexistent, speculative or in conflict with more persuasive evidence,'' thomas wrote
many bird species find golf courses and sod farms good feeding grounds, especially in urban areas where these large expanses of green are easy to spot from the air. they ingest the chemical both from the insects they eat and from directly eating small pellets of the chemical
the agency has said it knows of 60 instances in 18 states of bird kills where diazinon was the known or suspected cause. anywhere from one to 800 birds were killed in these cases, and epa believes the deaths are significantly underestimated
diazinon has other uses on farms, in nurseries and in gardens that are not affected by thomas' ruling. about 8 million pounds a year are sold, of which 512,000 pounds is used on golf courses and 60,000 pounds on sod farms, the agency said. diazinon is contained in 494 licensed pesticide products
ciba-geigy spokesman skip ragland said the company still believed its product could be used safely, but had not had time to study thomas' decision. the company could begin a court appeal, but ``we don't know yet how far we're going to take this,'' ragland said
maureen hinkle, a lobbyist for the national audubon society, praised thomas' decision and noted that other pesticides frequently kill birds
we hope it will be a precedent for other pesticide decisions affecting birds,'' she said
sikh radicals killed 15 more people in punjab, bringing the death toll to 50 in three days of attacks linked to their violent separatist campaign, police reported wednesday
attacks blamed on sikh militants have taken at least 580 lives already this year in punjab, india's main agricultural region and the only state where sikhs are the majority. the death toll for all of 1987 was about 1,000
this week's violence has included the first successful use of rocket-propelled grenades against police. izhar alam, the punjab police chief, said he believes arms are being smuggled in from pakistan
seven people killed tuesday night were members of two sikh families in the amritsar district adjacent to pakistan, alam said
many attacks involve random fire. on monday night, gunmen killed 10 people at a sikh wedding party, including the bride and groom. a survivor said the raiders shouted that family members were police informers
although members of the sect have a majority in punjab, sikhs make up only 2 percent of india's 800 million people, more than 80 percent of whom are hindus
targets of the sikh gunmen include moderate sikhs who oppose a separate state, as well as hindus. at least 328 of this year's victims have been sikhs
an increasing worry for punjabi authorities is the more powerful weaponry being introduced, including grenade launchers and ak-47 assault rifles
no casualties were reported in the first attack with rocket-propelled grenades, made on a police barracks last week. on tuesday night, however, 10 men were wounded by grenades fired at a truck carrying paramilitary personnel of the border security force in the gurdaspur district north of amritsar
police found an underground arms cache in the amritsar district sunday that included 14 soviet-made rpg-7 launchers along with he-80 anti-tank grenades, said s.s. virk, a senior officer of the paramilitary central reserve police
alam's claim that arms have come from pakistan conforms with indian allegations that pakistan arms the militants, a charge the government in islamabad denies
the rightist arena party has withdrawn from vote counting in the march 20 election, claiming others are trying to deprive it of victory, officials said wednesday
election officials announced soon after the election that arena, an abbreviation of republican nationalist alliance, had defeated the christian democratic party of president jose napoleon duarte
it appeared at the time that arena would get at least 31 of the 60 national assembly seats under the system of proportional representation, with about 22 being assigned to christian democrats
arena left the count tuesday night by taking its representative off the three-member central elections council, which does the tallying. it was protesting a council decision to consider challenges to the elections of three arena candidates
francisco merino, the party's council representative, said the other members wanted to make a ``game of the vote tallies in order to change the results of the elections.''
the other members are the council president, mario samayoa of the christian democrats, and arturo mendez azahar of the conservative national conciliation party. two votes are enough to approve any decision
roberto d'aubuisson, the former army major who founded arena, told reporters recently that if his party did not receive 31 seats it would be a case of ``fraud and we will withdraw from this democratic process.''
alfredo cristiani, president of arena, said in a television interview wednesday: ``the people are being defrauded. this could explode at any moment, something difficult to stop (could) occur.''
in a recent interview, samayoa denied the accusation of fraud in the vote-counting, which he said ``only exists in the mind of those who have manipulated the information about the results in their favor.''
he said officials completed the official tallies and assignment of seats last saturday for 11 of the 14 provinces, but some recounts would be needed in the other three because of challenges
the arena upset presented duarte, a staunch u.s. ally, with dim prospects for his last year in office. presidential elections are set for march 1989
arena benefited from popular discontent about duarte's failure to meet his 1984 campaign pledges of improving the economy and ending the 8-year-old civil war with leftist guerrillas
both unemployement and the annual inflation rate are estimated at 40 percent
the death of chairman james howard of the house public works and transportation committee paves the way for a relatively obscure californian to take over the panel, and for possible shifts among subcommittee leaders
rep. glenn anderson of los angeles is acting chairman of the public works panel and its ranking democrat. anderson's top aide, jeremiah bresnahan, asked wednesday if the lawmaker would want to become the panel's permanent chairman, said, ``i can't imagine he wouldn't want to be.''
other legislators and committee aides, asking to not be identified, said it appeared certain that anderson would become committee chairman, probably next month, and that he was not likely to be challenged for the job
anderson, 75, is a former california lieutenant governor who was elected to the house in 1968. he is a strong union supporter who has been an advocate for many projects the committee oversees, but he has been one of the least visible members of the panel's leadership
the real question is whether anderson will choose to retain his chairmanship of the surface transportation subcommittee when he takes control of the entire committee. that subcommittee, which oversees enormous highway, water and mass transit programs, is generally considered the most desirable on the committee
under house rules, anderson could retain both posts
robert maitlin, an aide to rep. robert roe, d-n.j., who ranks behind anderson in seniority, said it is ``very doubtful'' roe would give up his chairmanship of the science, space and technology committee to take over the surface transportation subcommittee
rep. norman mineta, d-calif., said he might be interested in heading the surface transportation subcommittee if anderson vacated the job. mineta now chairs the committee's aviation subcommittee
house democratic rules call for a nominee to head a committee to be selected by the democratic steering and policy committee, a panel of 31 democratic representatives dominated by the party's leadership. that selection must then be approved by a vote of the 257 democrats in the house, and then by the entire house
the 60-year-old howard, d-n.j., died last friday, a day after being stricken with a heart attack while playing golf in suburban maryland. pesticide</head>
environmental protection agency scientists can foresee no risk to humans or other organisms from a proposed field test in maryland of a new genetically engineered pesticide, the agency said wednesday
the pesticide, if eventually approved, would be used against the european corn borer
crop genetics inc. of hanover, md., applied to both epa and the agriculture department's animal and plant health inspection service to test the new substance on its farm near ingleside, md., and at the agriculture department's research station at beltsville, md
the report by microbiologists and plant pathologists from the hazard evaluation divison of epa's pesticides office said the properties of the engineered organism and results of lab tests on mice ``indicate that there are no human health risks.''
the report said it is difficult to transfer the organism from one plant to another except on the blades of cutting tools, and the engineered organism eventually should die out in competition with the natural strain
for this small-scale field test, providing all the containment, monitoring and contingency procedures are adhered to, we can foresee no risk to non-target insects and no effect on endangered species,'' and the organism may be used, the group said
the report will be considered at a public meeting april 18 of a subcommittee of epa's pesticide scientific advisory panel. the panel's report is expected in time for a decision on the permits in may. support</head>
a senior pentagon official said wednesday the soviet union has been sending money to philippine insurgents, but he said the rebels' growth is slowing and they are not now targeting americans in the country
richard l. armitage, assistant secretary for international security affairs, also praised the capture tuesday of several top communist rebel leaders in the philippines, saying, ``this has to have a devastating effect on the morale'' of the new people's army
armitage told a congressional subcommittee hearing that he found ``dramatic differences'' during a recent visit to manila, compared to one 18 months earlier
he said president corazon aquino's government now has people who genuinely care about the health of the nation. the debate in manila, he said, is no longer over whether the president will survive coup attempts but how successful she will be during the rest of her term, which ends in 1992
asked by rep. robert mrazek, d-n.y., whether there has been any soviet support for the rebels, armitage said, ``in terms of equipment, none. in terms of money, sure.''
in the first public claim by an administration official that there is soviet support for philippine rebels, armitage said soviet money goes to the communist party of the philippines and is then funneled to the new people's army. he gave no other details
armitage said that the up to 16,000 armed and another 10,000 unarmed rebels also receive money from groups in europe, australia, new zealand and the united states, and they are known to have held discussions with north korean and vietnamese representatives
no outside group is known to have sent arms to the rebels since a shipment of about 150 weapons by the palestine liberation organization in the early 1980s, he said
the defense official said growth of the insurgency has been about 2 percent annually, compared to 20 percent during the last year of president ferdinand e. marcos' regime, which was replaced by mrs. aquino's government in a february 1986 revolt
he noted that no american servicemen have been killed in the philippines since two american airmen and a retired u.s. soldier were gunned down last october
communist rebels claimed responsibility for the killings and said more u.s. soldiers would be killed. but armitage said he believes it was the work of a local rebel group that backfired and not the result of a communist central committee policy
assistant secretary of state gaston j. sigur appeared before the appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations to defend administration proposals for $257 million in aid for fiscal 1989. this is $90 million less than congress appropriated for the philippines last year
sigur noted there are also congressional proposals for the united states to lead an international effort to raise $5 billion for the philippines over the next five years
he also pointed to the possibility of additional aid in connection with the agreement allowing u.s. use of clark air base, subic navy base and other military facilities in the philippines. a review of the bases agreement begins in manila next week, with money a key issue
the iran-u.s. claims tribunal has sharply curtailed hearings because of iranian claims that iraqi missile attacks are keeping its lawyers and witnesses from appearing in the hague, sources said
the 6-year-old tribunal is charged with arbitrating billions of dollars of u.s. and iranian financial claims arising from the 1979 islamic revolution which overthrew the late shah mohammad reza pahlavi
three of four scheduled hearings have been canceled since march 7 at iranian request
one western source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said wednesday that the cancellations mean only one claim is expected to be heard by the nine-judge tribunal between march 7 through may 25
no hearings are set during the moslem holy month of ramadan from april 18-may 20
current cases have taken at least six years to reach the hearing docket, which is set months in advance
both iraq and iran have been engaging in missile attacks on population centers in their 7{-year-old war
in a major case involving the delaware firm combustion engineering co., the iranian agent to the tribunal, mohammed k. eshragh, wrote the tribunal that ``representatives and attorneys in the above-mentioned case cannot travel to the hague due to the present circumstances prevailing in iran.''
he requested cancellation of the hearing, a tribunal source said wednesday. the request was granted march 22
that case, scheduled for an april 11-13 hearing, involved a claim against the iranian government and two of its agencies for engineering and inspection services provided to steel mills in iran
eshragh has refused official comment on the situation in tehran, but tribunal sources _ speaking on condition of anonymity _ said he recently claimed iraqi missile attacks had forced evacuation of 1 million residents from the capital, a city of approximately 6 million
the sources said eshragh claimed iranian attorneys were unreachable and airline service from tehran was disrupted
eshragh was not available for comment at the bureau of iranian legal services in the hague
officials at the tribunal have tried to verify independently eshragh's claim that iranian parties to the cases were unavailable
the independent sources that we have seen ... would support the statement made by the iranian agent,'' said a tribunal source
other hearings canceled included one scheduled april 15 on a claim by the silver springs, md., firm of tadjer-cohen associates inc. against an iranian government bank. the claim involved an undetermined amount of unpaid invoices for supervision of an iranian construction project. the hearing was called off march 24
a march 9-10 hearing in a case brought by fairfield, conn.-based general electric corp. was called off march 8. that claim, brought against the iranian government and several of its agencies, sought millions of dollars in compensation for aircraft engine parts shipped to iran
still on schedule is a hearing april 14 involving a claim by the california firm near east technological services usa, inc. against the iranian air force for unpaid spare parts shipments
the tribunal source said that hearing has apparently not been canceled because it will be handled by iranian lawyers already in the hague
the tribunal has so far awarded about $1 billion to american claimants and about $60 million to iranians, plus an undetermined amount of interest to claimants on both sides
the arbitration panel was established by the 1981 algiers accords, which brought freedom to american hostages held at the u.s. embassy in tehran for 444 days in 1979-81
it is the only known forum for official contacts between u.s. and iranian officials.  ss to elite guard sted secret police. picks up 11th graf pvs, about 1,000 ...</note>
a bomb exploded near the south african embassy here wednesday, a few hours after police arrested more than 80 people protesting the assassination of an african national congress official
in the southern port city of marseille, at least six gunshots were fired tuesday night at a building in front of the south african consulate. the gunmen fled in a car and no arrests were made
no injuries were reported from the bomb which exploded about 3 a.m. wednesday at a paris office building a few blocks from the embassy. police said no claim of responsiblity had been received
late tuesday night, police arrested 41 demonstrators who broke into and smashed the south african tourism office, and 46 others who painted anti-apartheid slogans on the home of the south african ambassador in paris
police identified the protesters only as young leftists who supported the anc. all but four were released overnight
they were protesting the slaying of dulcie september, 53, the anc representative to france, switzerland and luxembourg, who was found dead tuesday outside the door of the anc's paris office. she had been shot in the face
police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said at the time that the killing looked like ``the work of a professional.''
the anc, the main guerrilla group fighting the apartheid government of south africa, blamed pretoria for september's death. the south african government denied responsibility and said the attack was related to strife within the anc, which was banned by south africa in 1960
a french foreign ministry spokesman said tuesday that no claim of responsiblity had been received
in marseille, the gunshots were fired at 11:15 p.m. tuesday at the windows of a building in front of the consulate. the building was painted with the slogan, ``botha, assassin, ss,'' a reference to south african president p.w. botha and to adolf hitler's elite guard, the most powerful instrument of nazi power
about 1,000 people marched peacefully in a separate protest in paris tuesday evening
president francois mitterrand said tuesday he would ask south africa about the attack and reaffirmed his ``condemnation of the regime of racial segregation.''
a colleague of ms. september's claimed that she had requested protection from the interior ministry after receiving death threats and being followed. the interior ministry denied that ms. september had requested protection
if she had asked, we would have given it to her,'' a ministry spokeswoman said
ms. september came to paris after spending five years in a south african prison for her outspoken criticism of apartheid
ms. september's sister, stephanie arendse, said that after she was released from prison ``she became quiet and didn't talk about her politics so much.''
in an interview published wednesday in the south african daily, the cape times, mrs. arendse said the family was uncertain whether ms. september's body would be returned to south africa for burial
ms. september, the oldest of three daughters and a teacher by training, was tried in 1963 along with 10 others for treason and sabotage and sentenced in 1964 to five years in prison, at the age of 29
on her release in 1969 she was placed under house arrest and confined to wynburg, in northern cape province
mrs. arendse said her sister left south africa on an exit visa in 1973 and settled in london, where she attended a nursing school
she was an administrative secretary at the anc's lusaka, zambia, headquarters and served in other capacities before 1984, when she became representative for france, luxembourg and switzerland
an anc spokesman on tuesday called ms. september one of the organization's ``most vigorous activists.''
jean and leonard peck, having breakfast wednesday with democratic presidential candidate albert gore, said they didn't mind having that media crowd in their kitchen _ they'd seen it all before
exactly 12 years earlier, a georgia peanut farmer, jimmy carter, had visited the wisconsin dairy farm family on his way to the white house
i guess we have a popular farm,'' leonard peck, 67, said after gore, his press entourage and secret service agents left. ``it's a lot of work, but it's a thrill,'' said his wife. ``i think it worked better this time because we had been through it before.''
gore, a senator from tennessee, spent tuesday night at the peck farm. he put on work clothes and helped prepare cows for milking and put straw in animal stalls before joining the family for a breakfast of pancakes, sausage and a family specialty made with cornflakes, ice cream, strawberries and cream
gore's farm background came through. ``you could tell that he knew his way around the farm and he could handle a fork and acted at home with the cows,'' leonard peck said
an aide to presidential hopeful albert gore says jesse jackson may be using easter as a ``political pulpit'' if he solicits campaign funds during a sermon sunday
if we were to use easter sunday as a political pulpit, you guys in the newspapers would beat us to death,'' mike veit, gore's colorado campaign coordinator, told the denver post tuesday
if we went in and raised money in a sunday church service, you'd beat us up even worse,'' added veit, stressing his comments reflected his views and not those of gore
colorado's presidential caucuses will be held the day after easter, and campaign staffers for gore, a senator from tennessee, and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis have been reluctant to schedule big political events for the religious weekend
jackson is to deliver a sermon sunday at the first baptist church in denver's capitol hill, where the pastor says jackson's appearance will be part of a worship service, not a political rally. but the pastor says three collections will be taken _ one for the churches, one for missionary work, and one for jackson's campaign
democrats are soliciting corporate donations to help pay for their national convention in atlanta this summer, and they're offering some political plums in return
a four-color brochure sent out this week to 600 corporations in georgia and the southeast offers tickets to the convention, choice hotel rooms, transportation and exclusive parties to those willing to chip in
this convention provides a unique opportunity for corporations to get their message across to governors, members of congress, foreign ambassadors,'' says nancy parrish, a fund-raising consultant who helped design the convention sales package
a $15,000 contributor would get two convention tickets, access to a hospitality suite, rooms at area hotels and seats on vip buses running between hotels and the convention site
for $200,000, a contributor will receive floor seats or a skybox, a private reception room, more hotel rooms, exclusive parties and limousine service
a poll says massachusetts gov. michael dukakis leads jesse jackson among democrats likely to vote in new york's april 19 primary but jackson has an edge among those strongly committed to a candidate
according to a chicago sun-times-gallup poll released tuesday, dukakis was the only democrat to lead vice president george bush among new york voters. in general election matchups, dukakis led bush 49 percent to 41 percent, while bush led jackson 55 percent to 31 percent
of the new york democrats interviewed, 44 percent preferred dukakis, 28 percent favored jackson, 3 percent chose tennessee sen. albert gore and 2 percent backed sen. paul simon of illinois
but only 14 percent of democrats who said they were strongly committed to a candidate planned to vote for dukakis, while 21 percent favored jackson
the results were based on telephone interviews with 1,205 registered new york voters conducted between friday and sunday. the sample included 421 likely to vote in the democratic primary and 329 in the republican primary. the margin of error was 5 percent among democrats and 3 percent for general election matchups
a fast-moving storm brewing in the southwestern united states dumped up to a half a foot of snow on parts of utah on wednesday and threatened wyoming and colorado with heavy snow
utah's higher elevations got 6 inches of snow before skies cleared wednesday afternoon. salt lake city received 3 inches of snow in six hours; in utah's western desert, tooele got 5 inches
snow advisories were issued through thursday morning for southwest utah and the northern and central mountains of colorado, where up to 8 inches was expected. a winter storm watch also was posted for south-central and southeastern wyoming, where up to 10 inches of snow was forecast
farther south, showers and thunderstorms developed along a stationary front extending from texas' lower rio grande valley across louisiana into mississippi
the eastern united states continued to enjoy unseasonably warm weather, with highs in the 70s from the central and eastern gulf coast to the middle atlantic states
heavier rainfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m. est included 1.56 inches at alexandria, la., and 1.29 inches at baton rouge, la
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 24 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 87 at the southwest regional airport in fort myers, fla. the early morning low for the nation was 3 degrees above zero at international falls, minn
thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extending from the southern and central appalachians through the mid-mississippi valley and across much of the southern and central plains. rain was expected from kentucky and tennessee into kansas, oklahoma and northern texas. snow was forecast for the central rockies and the central high plains, eastern colorado and western nebraska. fair skies should prevail over the rest of the nation
high temperatures should be below 50 degrees from much of the rockies to the upper great lakes, including highs only in the 30s and upper 20s from northern arizona across much of colorado and wyoming to western south dakota. highs should reach in the 60s and 70s from the southern and central pacific coast through southern arizona and the southern high plains to the southern and mid-atlantic coast, and in the 50s in most of the rest of the nation
ferdinand marcos, the exiled former president of the philippines, says negotiations for a return to his homeland are under way and he will likely go back ``very soon,'' a published report said
if i have a political role to play, we will negotiate that later,'' marcos was quoted as saying in the latest edition of paris match, which goes on sale thursday
the philippine government has said it sent emissaries to talk to marcos in january and february. mrs. aquino has said that before marcos returns, he must give back billions of dollars he allegedly stole during his 20-year rule. marcos has denied stealing any money
negotiations have started between the government of mrs. (corazon) aquino and myself,'' marcos was quoted as saying in an interview in his exile home in honolulu. ``these negotiations are continuing at this moment and going very well. i hope that we can very quickly set the date of my return, as well as the conditions.''
asked when he would return, he responded, ``man proposes and god disposes ... i will be going home very soon,'' the magazine said
marcos fled the philippines during a civilian-military revolt in the wake of fraud-tainted feb. 7, 1986 presidential elections in which both he and mrs. aquino claimed victory. mrs. aquino revoked his passport
in the paris match interview, marcos was quoted as expressing his admiration ``for the way mrs. aquino is confronting all sorts of problems.'' but he also expressed fears that her government could soon disintegrate
the communists will then have a free field to immediately take power,'' he is quoted as telling the weekly photo magazine, in a reference to leftist rebels
for me the only way to make a contribution to national unity is to return to my country, with respect for all conditions we can agree to.''
marcos also is quoted as saying that he needs to return for health reasons, especially old war wounds acting up, and to settle lawsuits filed against him since he was deposed. graf pvs, bgng: fellow presidential</note>
michael dukakis cautiously began speaking of differences between himself and jesse jackson on the middle east and domestic policy wednesday, signaling a delicate new phase in their struggle for supremacy in the democratic presidential race. jackson and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. tangled more openly
jackson canceled a planned meeting with gore on wednesday, citing comments gore made about him the day before, which he called ``more personal than principled.'' gore, sounding irritated, responded: ``there is no reason why anyone should think jesse jackson ought to be treated differently from any other candidate in this race.''
gore had said jackson did not have the experience necessary for the presidency
fellow presidential hopeful paul simon said he, too, has better credentials for the white house than jackson, and spoke frankly about the dilemma that has plagued democrats since jackson moved to the front ranks of the presidential contenders. ''you have to be careful. you don't want to be perceived as anti-black,'' he said
jackson, an outsider if there ever was one, broke bread with the inner circle of the democratic party establishment in washington. he said it showed that ``old wineskins are expanding and making room for new wine.'' but a congressional supporter said he detected the beginnings of a ``stop-jackson'' movement taking hold elsewhere
the democrats who met with jackson said they wanted no part of that. but florida party chairman charles whitehead said, ``i would be less than honest with you if i didn't tell you there is absolutely an awful lot of apprehension out there among an awful lot of democrats about the nomination of jesse jackson.''
jackson scored a landslide victory over dukakis in the michigan caucuses last weekend that stunned some party leaders
some of them say privately they fear that if nominated, the black, liberal former civil rights leader would lead democrats to an election-day loss that might jeopardize democratic control of the congress. on the other hand, party leaders are afraid of offending the millions of black voters jackson brings to the polls, knowing that their support will be needed to produce a general election victory
dukakis regained his footing with a victory in connecticut's primary tuesday night by a margin of 2-1 over jackson, and holds a narrow lead in convention delegates, 647 to 634. gore trails with 364. it takes 2,082 delegates to win the nomination
the democratic maneuverings in advance of monday's colorado caucuses and tuesday's wisconsin primary contrasted sharply with the serenity on the republican side
bob dole reassumed the mantle of republican senate leader following his withdrawal from the presidential race. he went to the white house and told president reagan he was ``reporting back for duty.''
in an interview, he said he made serious tactical mistakes in his campaign, but he added that the real problem was ``you can't beat ronald reagan.''
i was running against ronald reagan jr. in the south,'' he said in a reference to vice president george bush who campaigned as reagan's right-hand man
bush campaigned in wisconsin, but he hardly needed to. former television evangelist pat robertson is his only remaining rival, and the only question left is when the vice president will garner the final delegates needed to clinch the nomination
but there was enough twisting and turning on the democratic side for both parties
dukakis, under pressure from party officials to develop a more compelling campaign message, spoke for the first time of differences between himself and jackson
from time to time differences will arise. ... we have differences over the middle east, we have differences about certain aspects of domestic policy, and how to build a strong economy, how to create good jobs and those will come out over time,'' he said on cbs' ``this morning.'' he didn't elaborate
dukakis wasn't the only one jabbing at jackson
sen. simon, who needs a strong finish in wisconsin, clearly had jackson in mind when he said, ``i offer not only passion, but programs. ... i am here. i have been fighting for (workers') policies on the washington scene, not just in speeches.''
gore, who took issue with jackson on middle east and other issues on tuesday, said wednesday that his remarks were ``really not that different from what i've been saying for several months.''
gore had said in new york the day before that jackson has a ``complete and total lack'' of experience needed to be president
the tennessee senator, who has done poorly since he won several states on super tuesday, campaigned in wisconsin, and said, ``i think we're going to surprise some people in this state.''
jackson himself expressed pleasure at his breakfast meeting with party leaders from around the country, including former chairman john white, one-time defense secretary clark clifford and other democratic insiders
white called it a ``bonding of the democratic party'' and said the subject of jackson dragging the party down to defeat was discussed ``not at all.''
but someone at the table asked jackson about the 1984 controversy that surrounded his relationship with black extremist louis farrakhan. white said jackson ``quoted jesus about casting the first stone and forgiveness and so anybody who hasn't made mistakes ... let's not be casting stones at each other about the past.''
jackson himself said he saw no evidence of a concerted movement to stop his nomination
but rep. mickey leland of texas, a supporter, said he did
there is some movement afoot,'' leland said. ``we can't put our hands on it. we don't know who the leader is. but we do understand ... different players of the democratic party have been approached.''
he named democratic national chairman paul kirk, and house speaker james wright as among those approached. contacted later, kirk and a spokesman for wright said they had not been approached about stopping jackson
several of the largest insurance companies are offering sharp discounts in premiums for drivers of cars with air bags, the safety devices that inflate and protect a driver in a serious accident
usaa, the country's sixth largest insurance company, announced wednesday a premium discount of up to 60 percent for personal injury and medical coverage for air bag-equipped cars
the company also said it would contribute $300 to the purchase or lease of a 1988 car equipped with an air bag
state farm mutual automobile insurance co. on tuesday announced a premium discount of from $3 to $24 for cars equipped with air bags or passive belts, which automatically wrap around a car occupant
robert f. mcdermott, chairman of usaa, told a news conference he expected air bags to be available as an option or standard equipment in several million cars within the next 18 months
with safety belt use levels of 50 percent, we estimate we will annually save 4,400 lives and prevent 73,000 moderate to critical injuries,'' he said. ``with air bags and a 50 percent belt use rate, the number of lives saved doubles to 8,800 and injury reduction more than doubles to 151,000.''
the auto industry in the past has complained that while insurance companies have campaigned to get air bags into cars they have not offered car owners financial incentives to order the safety devices. testing</head>
a preliminary injunction barring random drug testing of 9,400 civilian army employees was set aside by a federal appellate court tuesday while it considers the justice department's appeal of a lower court order
a three-judge panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals here granted a stay that was sought by the justice department of the preliminary injunction issued by u.s. district judge thomas f. hogan on march 1
hogan had ordered the army to stop random urine testing of civilian army employees, finding that the practice was an ``excessively intrusive'' search prohibited by the constitution
the preliminary injunction was issued in a case brought by public employee unions representing civilian army employees at ft. stewart, fla.; aberdeen proving ground, md.; and the sharp army depot in lathrop, calif
the injunction banned random testing of all 9,400 civilians in sensitive jobs who were subject to the anti-drug program, including pilots, guards and police officers on military bases
in issuing the injunction, hogan had expressed regret that it ``removes what might be a powerful weapon from the nation's arsenal in the campaign against illegal drug use, but the values represented by the constitution and fourth amendment are transcendent.''
citing a legal precedent that allows stays of judicial decisions when a party is likely to prevail on the merits of a dispute, circuit judges stephen williams, james buckley and d.h. ginsburg said ``a stay is warranted in this case.''
kenneth t. blaylock, president of the american federation of government employees, expressed disappointment that the appellate judges had set aside the injunction against random testing. he said the union was ``determined to continue its fight to protect employee rights under the constitution.''
justice department spokesman amy brown said the department was pleased with the court's decision to stay hogan's order. the army had no immediate comment
no date has been set for a hearing on the department's appeal in the case. ground at atlanta during the incident, picking up 9th graf pvs, `an unidentified...'.</note>
for the second time in her career, flight attendant nancy holt has given cardiopulmonary resuscitation to save a stricken passenger
this time, john d. farmer jr., 62, of jacksonville had run to catch his flight monday from atlanta to jacksonville and arrived at the plane just before it began taxiing from the gate at atlanta's hartsfield international airport
he asked if he could sit in the first-class section until he caught his breath, ms. holt said. noting his heavy breathing and gray color, ms. holt asked if he wanted oxygen
he said yes, took a few breaths and toppled over,'' she said. the plane was taxiing toward the runway at the time
that man weighed over 200 pounds,'' said john fors, an atlanta businessman who was aboard the plane. ``that 110-pound lady pulled him off the seat and began cpr.''
ms. holt, who has worked for delta air lines for 10 years, remembers wondering as she pulled farmer to the cabin floor how she would move him
i got the strength from somewhere,'' she said. ``i put him on the floor and he was dead; there was no pulse and no breath.''
in the meantime, ms. holt's supervisor called rescue personnel at the airport
an unidentified doctor aboard the plane assisted her in continuing cpr, ms. holt said. paramedics revived the man, however, ms. holt said
he was clinically dead,'' said mark johnson, an atlanta fire bureau paramedic. ``we helped save his life,'' but he stressed that ms. holt's quick action was primarily responsible
that person deserves equal praise or more.''
farmer told johnson he had been discharged from a hospital just five weeks ago with a heart problem and had exerted too much effort trying to catch the plane
about eight or nine years ago, ms. holt revived a passenger who had suffered a heart attack aboard a delta flight, she said
cpr proficiency is part of flight attendant's training, she said, and ``you never forget it.'' to bill</note>
the senate passed 62-28 on wednesday a bill designed to revitalize the devastated u.s. uranium industry and restructure the government's own failing program to sell enriched fuel to nuclear power plants
the bill, which faces an uncertain future in the house, also would establish a $1 billion fund to clean up or stablize large, mildly radioactive piles of uranium tailings at 26 sites in seven western states. the cost would be shared equally by uranium mill owners, nuclear utilities and the government
among its more controversial provisions, the legislation _ which took six years to clear the senate _ would:
_impose a schedule of escalating fees on nuclear utilities that load their reactors with more than 37.5 percent foreign uranium. beginning in 1995, however, utilities could buy up to half their uranium from foreign suppliers without penalty. opponents, including sens. bill bradley, d-n.j., and daniel evans, r-wash., argued that this would violate the spirit of the recent free trade pact signed with canada, a leading exporter of relatively inexpensive, high-grade ore. bradley and evans lost an attempt, 47-45, to delete the import restrictions from the bill
_settle the nuclear industry's debt to the u.s. treasury for past purchases of enriched uranium at $364 million. opponents argued that the figure should be as high as $8.8 billion
_convert the department of energy's uranium enrichment program, supposedly self-financing but a multibillion-dollar loser since the mid-1970s, into a corporation owned by the government. if and when the enterprise begins turning profits, the treasury could sell the stock in a bid to recover previous investments
sen. j. bennett johnston, d-la., who guided the measure through his energy committee, said it is ``the culmination of six years of legislative effort to fashion a sound, sensible and well-balanced program to address the challenges we face today in the uranium industry and the nuclear fuel cycle
we're not here to debate the canadian trade deal,'' johnston said. ``let's keep american jobs at home.''
he estimated the bill would restore 20,000 jobs in the uranium mining industry, which has dwindled in this decade to 2,000 workers at just three mines. and he estimated the uranium enrichment workforce, cut by half since 1980, could be restored to at least 12,000 jobs
the national taxpayers union, the environmental policy institute, the union of concerned scientists, the u.s. public interest research group and environmental action all opposed key provisions of the bill, particularly the feature which limits the government's recovery of uranium enrichment costs to $364 million
the groups argued that charging just $364 million is an unprecedented bailout for the nuclear industry since the white house has estimated that the industry should be billed $3 billion and the general accounting office said the government should charge $8.8 billion
the 1954 atomic energy act required the government to be fully compensated for its enrichment of nuclear fuel used by commercial utilities
enrichment is a critical process in nuclear power. it involves increasing the percentage of fissionable material in natural uranium from 0.7 percent to about 3 percent, the amount necessary for use in light-water reactors
when the government began enriching commercial fuel in 1969, the united states was the only free-world supplier of the service for nuclear utilities and business was booming. predictions of burgeoning demand led to the expansion of the three doe plants, and, even then, all capacity was committeed
but then came a drastic decline in the demand for nuclear power, with utilities canceling plans for more than 100 additional reactors since the late 1970s. meanwhile, two european consortiums and the soviet union began to supply foreign utilities with enriched uranium, and by the 1980s, the u.s. monopoly had dropped to 50 percent of the market. even some u.s. utilities found it cheaper to buy foreign uranium
adding to the government enrichment program's woes was the fact that the energy department contracted with the tennessee valley authority for billions of dollars worth of electricity to operate its production plants. but when demand fell off, that electricty wasn't used _ even though tva charged for it anyway. the senate legislation settles that long-term debt at $1.2 billion
benjamin netanyahu, who gained prominence as an articulate defender of israel's policies in his post as ambassador to the united nations, announced his resignation wednesday
netanyahu became israel's permanent representative to the united nations in september 1984 after serving two years as the deputy chief of mission at the israeli embassy in washington
he is known for his forceful views on terrorism and is the editor of a 1986 book called ``terrorism: how the west can win.''
netanyahu, 39, plans to compete for a seat in the parliament, running as a candidate of prime minister yitzhak shamir's right-wing likud bloc, israel radio said
i have accelerated my resignation because, as i think, we are facing fateful decisions,'' netanyahu said on israel television. ``i think we must ... create a policy based on the correct reading of the international map.''
as an ambassador, i could not voice my thoughts. i certainly plan to do so and to influence the policy,'' he said
he said that ``israel has to maintain a full military control over all the territory west of the jordan river'' and reject the u.s. peace proposal, which he called a ``dangerous plan.''
israel has faced nearly four months of unrest in the occupied west bank of the jordan river and the gaza strip, which it seized in 1967
netanyahu, the son of a cornell university professor, has lived in the united states most of his life. he attended high school in philadelphia and studied business administration at the massachusetts institute of technology
his education was interrupted when he returned to israel in 1967 for a five-year stint in the army, during which he reached the rank of captain
netanyahu's brother jonathan was killed during israel's 1976 rescue of hostages in entebbe, uganda.   
democratic presidential contender michael dukakis, seeking a way to open a lead over jesse jackson, began wednesday to show how he might deal with his charismatic rival _ by stressing his government experience
dukakis sought to sidestep any direct criticism of jackson, whose campaign has boosted the democratic party with many new voters who will be needed in the november election. but he indirectly raised the issue of qualifications
i think (voters) want to know which one of us has the strength and the experience and the values to lead this country, to build a strong future. ... that's what this race is all about, that's what the presidency is all about,'' dukakis said at a statehouse news conference
jackson's victories on super tuesday and in michigan have made him dukakis' principal challenger, and dukakis has been struggling to find an effective way to fight off jackson without alienating jackson's backers
dukakis was drawing fire from another democratic contender, sen. albert gore jr., who accused him wednesday of being overly reluctant to specifically spell out his differences with jackson
he was asked: why would you make a better president?'' gore said of dukakis. ``he said, `i'm not going to answer that question. i think that's ludicrous.''
however, dukakis has been using the experience theme to separate himself from jackson, who has never held elective office
i'm a doer. i just don't talk about these things. i've created jobs. i'm building housing for families of low and moderate income,'' dukakis told an interviewer on the cbs ``this morning'' show
but at his boston news conference, dukakis was at pains to say he considers himself on friendly terms with jackson
we get along. we enjoy each other's company. he knows about the things we're doing here. we know about the things he's doing,'' the governor said
pressed, however, dukakis mentioned two broad areas in which he and jackson differ
we don't agree on middle east policy. we don't agree on some aspects of economic policy here in the united states,'' dukakis said
he refused to go into detail, promising to do so in a speech in wisconsin later this week
dukakis said he spoke to jackson by telephone wednesday morning, just hours after taking a 2-to-1 victory over jackson in the connecticut primary. however, the massachusetts governor refused to say what the two men discussed
a house committee urged the federal aviation administration on wednesday to block a plan by eastern airlines for a cargo carrier to fly eastern passenger flights in the event of a strike
in a report, the house government operations committee said orion air inc. of raleigh, n.c., should not be allowed to fly eastern aircraft until orion corrects ``major deficiencies'' noted in an april 1987 faa report
the committee is of the view that prudence and common sense dictate that orion not be graduated to the ranks of a passenger carrier pending a full and complete resolution of the major problems cited in that report,'' the panel said
orion officials have said they have corrected most of the problems cited by the faa
the committee also recommended that the government require eastern to notify passengers if their flights are to be operated by orion personnel
earlier this year, eastern signed an agreement under which orion would hire and train up to 400 pilots to fly eastern aircraft if the airline's pilots honor a possible walkout by the carrier's mechanics
the pilots' union has challenged that arrangement in court. on tuesday, u.s. district judge barrington d. parker issued a preliminary injunction blocking eastern from proceeding with its orion plan
construction crews scrambled wednesday to repair a cracked sewer main as million of gallons of raw sewage flooded nearby bodies of water, endangering fish and forcing industries to close
health advisories warning residents against fishing in local waterways remained in effect, as did three plant shutdowns ordered monday in hopes of curbing further environmental damage from toxic chemical discharges
a 20-foot section of the 11-mile sewer main _ the only link between muskegon and the county wastewater management system _ had to be replaced after construction crews discovered two small cracks in the section monday
but before the section could be replaced, the entire main had to be drained, releasing about 10 million gallons of untreated sewage into sanford's bayou
from 30 million to 40 million gallons of raw sewage was expected to be released into local waterways before completion of the repairs, expected thursday, said michael vandenheuvel, chief sanitarian for the muskegon county health department
ron woods, environmental engineer for the state department of natural resources, said preliminary tests showed there definitely would be a fish kill in sanford's bayou, but that none was expected in muskegon lake or muskegon river
we're optimistic that the lake will be able to assimilate the waste,'' said woods, who added that the sewage leak ``is among the worst i've ever seen.''
vandenheuvel said the released sewage posed only a slight health risk to humans
just as a precaution, we don't want people drinking that water or fishing in it,'' he said. he predicted the health warning would be lifted in about a week
vandenheuvel said a small leak had been detected in the pipe in january and that repairs had been scheduled next month. though the cracks required quick action, he said, drainage of the main would have been necessary in either case
there's just no way to shut that big pipeline down without draining it,'' he said
to drain the pipeline, construction crews tuesday cracked open the broken section of the main with a power shovel, resulting in a 30-foot geyser of raw sewage and industrial waste, which flowed into the bayou and eventually into muskegon lake
the wastewater vaporized, and the resulting steam cloud was carried over the jackson hill neighborhood by a moderate wind. the county health department reported several complaints of the stench, but said it posed no health risk to residents
officials urged residents to reduce the number of times they wash clothes, take showers or flush toilets while repairs were being done
five hundred employees were laid off temporarily at one of the three large muskegon plants ordered closed monday night to prevent the discharge of toxic chemical wastes
at the s.d. warren co. paper mill in muskegon, the treatment system's largest single source of wastewater, nearly half the company's 1,060 employees were told to report to work only after the main was repaired, company officials said
at sealed power corp.'s piston ring division, about 50 employees were laid off monday night, but were recalled wednesday. company officials said the plant would begin limited operations again wednesday night, hauling wastes by trucks directly to the wastewater management system
lomac inc., a chemical manufacturer in egelston township, has maintained full employment levels
the afl-cio on wednesday awarded its once-bitter rival, the international brotherhood of teamsters, sole oranizing rights to attempt unionizing the adolph coors co.'s lead brewery at golden, colo
the labor federation ordered one of its veteran affiliates, the machinists union, to halt efforts to organize the same 3,200 coors workers, saying the teamsters had a much better chance of succeeding
the decision was an outgrowth of the teamsters' decision last october to reaffiliate their 1.6 million members with the afl-cio. the union had been expelled 30 years earlier on charges of corruption
last september, before the teamsters reaffiliation, the labor federation had awarded sole organizing rights to the machinists union at coors. but the teamsters challenged that ruling as soon as they were readmitted
facing ongoing organizing efforts by the teamsters over the past two years, coors and the afl-cio last august ended one of the most prolonged and heated labor-management disputes in the country
in that agreement, the labor federation brought to an end its 10-year-old nationwide boycott of coors beer. in exchange the company agreed to forgo erecting legal roadblocks often used by management against an attempt by an afl-cio-affiliated union to organize its workforce
but that was before the teamsters were again an afl-cio affiliate. and teamsters officials admitted they had concerns now about how the coors-afl-cio pact will hold up in the face of the federation's decision wednesday
we're elated,'' said charles klare, director of the teamsters' 100,000-member brewery and soft drinks division. ``but there's a lot to be found out yet. we've got to meet with coors and determine if they accept the fact that the afl-cio picked us.''
the machinists union had argued before murray finley, a former president of the amalgamated clothing and textile workers union who was picked by afl-cio president lane kirkland to arbitrate the dispute, that the teamsters should give up the coors effort based on last september's decision
the teamsters countered they had an ongoing organizing campaign at coors a year before the machinists entered the picture and had gotten more than 30 percent of the workers at golden to sign teamster union cards
kirkland agreed with the teamsters, according to witnesses at the arbitration proceedings
it was a black-and-white case, based on the facts,'' said vicki saporta, the teamsters' director of organizing. ``we were there first and they didn't even have a single card signed. we're also the predominant union in the industry. we have contracts at all 12 anheuser-busch breweries covering some 9,000 workers.'' appointed, congressman asking for subcommittee hearing, quotes from later funeral service, remove outdated and redundant material. pickup 11th graf pvs, `there's a tremendous...' subs 19th graf, bgng `chavis' father' to delete first reference to britt.</note>
a special prosecutor was appointed wednesday to investigate the death of julian pierce, an indian activist running for a judgeship who was eulogized as robeson county's ``best hope for change.''
the appointment by the state attorney general's office was made at the request of county district attorney joe freeman britt, who had been pierce's opposition in the race for the superior court judgeship
pierce, who was found dead saturday, has been mourned by supporters who at first said they suspected he was killed because someone did not want a lumbee indian to be elected judge. more than 2,300 people attended a funeral and a memorial service for the activist wednesday
sheriff hubert stone said pierce's slaying was apparently the result of a broken romance, not a political vendetta, but that he was still investigating comments made by sandy gordon chavis. chavis had has been charged with murder in the incident; another man involved in the shooting committed suicide tuesday, officials said
senior deputy attorney general jim coman, a member of the attorney general's special prosecution unit, was appointed special prosecutor in the case, said john simmons, a spokesman for attorney general lacy thornburg
coman said he hoped to begin meeting with investigators next week
earlier, rep. harles rose, d-n.c., whose district include robeson county, said he has asked for a congressional criminal justice subcommittee, headed by rep. john conyers, d-mich., to hold a hearing in the county
the only role a subcommittee would have would be to look at how the federal government is interfacing down here,'' rose said. ``i want to know, is this county getting the kind of federal help it needs?''
about 1,500 people attended a memorial service at pembroke state university and 800 mourners later jammed a small church in maxton for pierce's funeral
he was loved. he was respected,'' said the rev. johnnie chavis during services at the sycamore hill independent holiness church. ``that says a lot more than we can say about a lot of people.'' the minister said he was a distant relative of the man who was arrested
pierce's family filled up half of the seats in the 400-seat church. several hundred others sat on wooden chairs outside
at the pembroke memorial service, christine griffin, acting co-director of lumbee river legal services, said pierce's compassion was ``overwhelming and all-consuming.''
he was the best hope we had,'' mrs. griffin told the packed auditorium. ``if he were here, he would say to us not to use the same weapons that were used against him to bring about change.''
we will keep up the peaceful fight for change through the courts and through the ballot box,'' said the rev. joy johnson
he was our first real hero for meaningful change in robeson county,'' said johnson. pierce had been the legal services executive director until he resigned to run for judge
despite the arrest of sandy gordon chavis, indian leaders said racial tension would not go away
there's a tremendous amount of suspicion ... that perhaps all the answers have not been put forward,'' vernon bellecourt, a representative of the american indian movement, said wednesday
chavis said that john anderson goins, also 24 and a lumbee indian from pembroke, shot and killed pierce, stone said. goins committed suicide tuesday
stone said the killing appeared to stem from goins' personal problems with 16-year-old shannon bullard, the daughter of pierce's girlfriend, ruth locklear. the sheriff said goins may have felt pierce helped ms. locklear get trespass warrants against him
although he hasn't entered a formal plea, chavis has told a family friend he was not involved in the slaying, the news and observer of raleigh said. the newspaper said chavis told ruth godwin that goins asked him saturday to go for a ride
the two stopped near pierce's home, but chavis said he thought goins was getting out of the car to go to the bathroom, the newspaper reported
i heard three shots,'' chavis said, according to mrs. godwin. ``i was stunned.''
stone declined comment on whether chavis knew goins' intentions
goins left flowers, a teddy bear and some cards on the doorstep of his former girlfriend's home before he killed himself, officials said
chavis' father, ronald, helped bring the suit that prompted the general assembly to create a separate superior court district for robeson county
the law was intended to help a non-white candidate get elected in a county where blacks and indians make up 58 percent of the registered voters
under state law, britt, who is white, will become judge because he is now unopposed. gov. jim martin said he would meet thursday with indian leaders calling for a special legislative session to allow an opponent in the may 3 vote
the sheriff expressed regret at his comment tuesday that the slaying was ``just another murder.'' ``one person's life is just as important as another's,'' stone said
in lumberton, a bomb threat emptied the robeson county courthouse on wednesday, but employees were allowed to return in less than two hours. no bomb was found and officials said they did not know if the threat was connected to the pierce case
the supreme court, in a case of particular importance to rural areas, was urged wednesday to compel states to provide free bus transportation for poor school children
duane houdek, representing a family challenging busing fees in north dakota, said the state unlawfully discriminates against some people who have trouble affording the busing charges
the bismarck, n.d., lawyer was asked by justice byron r. white whether north dakota is constitutionally required to provide transportation for poor people
that's a fair characterization'' of his argument, houdek replied
but some justices indicated their decision, expected to be announced by july, could be based on narrower grounds. they said the question may be whether north dakota discriminates improperly because it treats some school districts differently than others
north dakota law provides free bus transportation to those living in districts that have reorganized to broaden their tax base and improve education. only those districts that have not reorganized are allowed to charge parents for busing costs
the law was intended to spur reorganization while assuring people in those districts they would not have to pay for transportation
attorney general nicholas spaeth of north dakota defended the system as ``permissible geographic discrimination'' that does not unfairly harm the poor
it's one way economic benefits are dispensed,'' he said. he argued that the law does not deprive anyone of a public school education
the law was challenged by paula kdrmas from rural dickinson, n.d. she said the statute denied equal educational rights to her daughter, sarita, because the family could not afford a $97 annual bus fee
ms. kdrmas has driven sarita the 16 miles to school rather than pay the fee
george t. dynes, a lawyer representing the local school district, said it would have been cheaper for the kdrmas family to pay the bus fee _ which he said would be about 1.7 cents per mile
bus service in dickinson is offered for a fee to elementary school students who live more than three miles from school and to high school students who live more than four miles away
the north dakota supreme court upheld the law, saying local school officials rationally may decide their limited resources are needed for services other than transportation
a statutory scheme under which a school district offers to provide student transportation at considerably less expense to the parent than self-transportation would entail does not constitute a deprivation which offends either federal or state equal protection rights,'' the state court said
the case is kdrmas vs. dickinson public schools, 86-7113. grafs after 18th graf bgng: he denied ... to update with arad, lughod comments. picks up 19th graf pvs bgng: redman, on ...</note>
the state department on wednesday defended israel's authority to maintain order on the west bank and gaza, but said it should be exercised in a humane way
spokesman charles e. redman supported assertions by assistant secretary of state richard schifter that israel ``not only has the right but the obligation'' to restore order in the violence-beset territories it has held since the 1967 six-day war
schifter said at a congressional hearing tuesday that israel also was obliged ``to use appropriate levels of force to accomplish that end.''
in nearly four months of protests and disorder, 121 palestinian arabs and an israeli soldier have died in clashes. schifter, who is in charge of the state department's human rights office, also testified the united states had protested israeli ``brutalization'' of palestinian prisoners and ``random beating of civilians.''
schifter sought to distinguish those actions from dealing with violence and violent protests
abdeen jabara, president of the american-arab anti-discrimination committee, called wednesday for schifter's dismissal because of his comments
schifter is apparently more concerned about israel's image than he is about human rights,'' jabara said
the state department has consistently opposed the use of live ammunition, bone-breaking beatings and tear gas in confined places against stone-throwing demonstrators,'' he said. ``schifter's testimony ... yesterday contradicted this established policy.''
but redman supported the official, saying: ``what ambassador schifter said is exactly the same thing that the secretary (of state george p. shultz) and myself and every american authority has always said
first, israeli authorities have a duty to preserve order. that kind of duty has to be carried out with a certain authority. there's no doubt about it. but it also has to be carried out in as humane a way as possible.''
redman said ``we have never hesitated, in the latter sense, to express our concerns or criticism of particularly activity or excessive use of force.''
about 75 pro-palestinian demonstrators protested peacefully outside the israeli embassy's gates for an hour wednesday afternoon
lofting flags of the palestine liberation organization, the demonstrators chanted: ``palestine, yes! israel, no! victory, victory, plo,'' and ``no more beatings, no more crime! israel out of palestine.''
this was the first protest at the embassy since the supreme court last week knocked down rules that had kept all demonstrations _ peaceful and otherwise _ at least 500 feet away from foreign embassies. authorities still are allowed to keep potentially violent protests away from embassies, but no violence or arrests occurred
the israeli embassy's press office refused to comment on the demonstration or the new rules concerning such protests
moshe arad, israel's ambassador, blamed the deaths in west bank protests wednesday on the palestine liberation organization, which he said is inciting ``warfare.''
we are faced with a situation in the west bank, in gaza, in which elements are interested, especially the plo, in inciting to violence, promoting violence and making sure no dialogue is possible,'' arad said on pbs's macneil@lehrer ``newshour.''
shultz, meanwhile, met with a group of israeli and arab reporters and defended his proposal to hold mideast negotiations beginning may 1
shultz will fly to rome on thursday and then to israel on sunday night to begin five days of shuttling to israeli and arab capitals
he denied in the session with reporters he would invite leaders of the countries to a united nations peace conference
arad, on pbs, said that although israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir had ``reservations'' about a middle east peace initiative proposed by shultz, israeli government is united in welcoming the secretary's return to the region next week
you will find the israeli government interested and keen to pursue this dialogue,'' arad said
ibrahim abu-lughod, a member of the palestine national council, urged shultz to open talks with the plo
during shultz's trip to the region in late february and early march the palestinians declined to meet with shultz but lughod, also interviewed on pbs, said that on shultz's return visit palestinians may meet the secretary. the palestine national council is the so-called legislative arm of the plo
redman, on another subject, expressed regret that israel had ordered the closing of the arab-owned palestine press service in jerusalem. he said the result would be to restrict reporters' freedoms
khalil jahshan, president of the council of presidents of national arab-american organizations, said, ``we find the administration's mild criticism of israel morally bankrupt.''
in letters to shultz and to president reagan, jahshan wrote, ``it is our conviction that the united states government is contributing to the worsening situation in the israeli-occupied territories by failing to make it absolutely clear that it will not tolerate the escalating oppression of palestinians.''
jahshan, who requested a meeting with reagan, called on the united states ``to ensure that impartial observers be permitted access to the territories to help ensure that innocent people are not massacred.''
the first stage of the $600,000 world cup grand prix chess competition opens in brussels on friday, beginning a new and lucrative battle among the world's top chess players
the top-ranked 25 players internationally will each compete in four of the six world cup tournaments during 1988-89. the overall champion will get $100,000, in addition to winnings from the individual tournaments
the card for the opening $104,000 tournament in brussels is headed by soviet anatoly karpov, the former world champion; dutchman jan timman and swiss veteran viktor korchnoi
world champion garri kasparov, a favorite to win the overall competition, will sit out the first tournament
the world cup is organized by the grandmasters association, established recently by some of the world's best players to counter the influence of the world chess federation
after the world championship, the world cup grand prix provides the biggest prizes for the international grandmasters
the world cup is aimed at increasing the popularity of chess and making it more accessible to the media, while providing more money for top players. organizers it will provide continuous competition, unlike the world championship, held every few years
the world chess federation said in a statement that the world cup competition was ``a great step in the promotion of chess.''
each of the six tournaments will involve either 16 or 18 of the selected players. the three best tournament finishes of each player will count for the final standings
other stages of the competition will be held in belfort, france; reykjavik, iceland; barcelona, spain; rotterdam, the netherlands; and skelleftea, sweden
the three-week brussels tournament is dominated by six soviets while players from hungary, the united states, switzerland, yugoslavia, cuba, britain, sweden, and the netherlands are also scheduled to take part
the world cup players were selected on the basis of their international ranking
the next world championship tournament is scheduled in 1990, while the next two-year world cup is set for 1990-1991
democrat richard a. gephardt, out of the presidential race but still campaigning on the trade front, called on lawmakers wednesday to save the heart of his plan to fight foreign barriers with import curbs
i think that we can come up with something that will be positive,'' the missouri congressman told a house-senate conference committee that is drafting a compromise version of rival 1,000-page trade bills approved by both houses last year
gephardt told reporters earlier that he would push for the conference committee to adopt his plan as it was approved by the house. the senate takes a differing approach to unfair foreign trade barriers
but gephardt seemed to acknowledge that his plan was bound to be modified by the conference committee in the long run, something that lawmakers have been conceding for weeks
he said any final version should focus on key countries employing unfair trade practices as part of a systematic trade strategy. wholesale negotiations should be shunned in favor of working on major trade trouble spots, gephardt said
mandatory retaliation is needed when negotiations fail, he noted, saying ``you have to have a stick in the closet.'' but he added that flexibility is necessary in dealing with trading partners and thus the president should have the power to waive retaliation when necessary
the conference committee stopped short wednesday of action on any of the major issues remaining before it puts the finishing touches on a compromise
i'm not going to kill myself to have that guy downtown say he's going to veto everything,'' said rep. dan rostenkowski, d-ill., chairman of a house-senate conference committee on trade legislation
it was the latest democratic comment on a drumroll of warnings from the reagan administration that the bill could be inviting a veto. the vice chairman, sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said tuesday that he was tired of hearing veto threats
rostenkowski said he still hoped to wrap up work by the close of business on thursday, when lawmakers leave on their spring break. but it remained unclear that he could meet that deadline
we're what you call clearing away brush,'' said rep. william frenzel, r-minn. ``we're to the small sapplings now and we haven't gotten to the part of the forest where the big redwoods are.''
besides the gephardt amendment, lawmakers have not resolved what the bill should do to overhaul existing law under which u.s. industries endangered by surges in foreign competition can obtain import restrictions from the government
whether to ban toshiba products because of that company's sale of submarine silencing equipment to the soviets remains undecided, as do provisions involving third world debt and requiring foreign owners of u.s. property to disclose their identities and the extent of their holdings
bentsen is campaigning to hang onto a senate provision to repeal the windfall profits tax on oil companies, a move that is opposed by rostenkowski
new protests that the bill already has been diluted came from lawmakers representing industrial areas where japanese imports have cut into jobs
i doubt that i can vote for it,'' rep. ed jenkins, d-ga., told the conference committee. ``because i don't want to be a part of some great trade bill that has no teeth and doesn't do anything at all for the industry of this country.''
the house has given up an awful lot and the administration has gotten a lot of what it wants and the senate has also,'' rep. don pease, d-ohio, said. ``the final product ought to be a legislative product and not just a product of the administration and ratified by us.''
rostenkowski and bentsen repeated their goal of producing legislation that president reagan would be willing to sign
or one that would embarrass him if he vetoes it,'' rostenkowski said
in a speech in richmond, va. on monday, reagan threatened to veto the legislation if it contained mandatory import curbs, forced disclosure of foreign ownership or a measure requiring employers to give notice of plant closings or large-scale layoffs
the plant-closings provision was adopted by a house-senate panel tuesday night. rostenkowski was asked wednesday if he regarded it as a permanent feature of the legislation
i see it as a big problem for getting the president's signature,'' he replied. update with contra reax. picks up 12th graf pvs bgng: the legislation ...</note>
the house overwhelmingly approved on wednesday a $48 million package of humanitarian aid for the contra rebels in nicaragua and for children injured in nearly seven years of civil war
the aid bill, passed on a 345-70 vote, was portrayed as a gesture of u.s. support for a temporary truce reached last week between the rebels and the sandinista government, and for continuing talks aimed at achieving a long-term end to hostilities
the hope is that this will lead to political instead of military processes now taking over'' in nicaragua, said house majority leader thomas foley, d-wash
this war is over, whether some like it or not,'' said rep. leon panetta, d-calif
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said after the house vote, ``we are pleased and look forward to the vote tomorrow in the senate.''
despite producing the first strong bipartisan vote on u.s. policy toward nicaragua in more than five years, lawmakers showed more weariness than joy as they plodded through two hours of debate
it is not the magic key to facilitate a cease-fire in place or fruitful negotiations and all the rest,'' said minority leader robert michel, r-ill., who said it has become clear congress is no longer inclined to grant the military aid he would prefer. ``but for the moment it's the only thing we have to give.''
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, noting the years of previous acrimony on the issue, called the broad support for the bill ``very impressive'' and said it should ``provide encouragement to both sides in central america.''
some democrats called the vote another victory for wright on the central american issue, which he has dominated on the u.s. side since a five-nation peace accord was signed in guatemala last aug. 7
the speaker has invested tremendous risk, and has been almost totally successful in saying, `i'm going to stick my neck out for peace down there,''' said rep. mike lowry, d-wash
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., promised speedy consideration on the other side of the capitol, and it appeared likely that the matter could come to a vote on thursday
officials of the nicaraguan resistance, a miami-based umbrella group of the contra rebels, said they were elated with the package
this is what we have been waiting for, for a long time _ a broad bipartisan aid package for the resistance,'' said alfredo cesar, a director of the resistance. he said it sends ``a strong political message to central america in general and to the world that the united states is not abandoning the resistance fighters in the mountains.''
the legislation would renew aid to the rebels, whose last u.s. support ran out feb. 29, and keep them together as a fighting force while they wait in cease-fire zones inside nicaragua for a long-term truce to be worked out with the sandinista government
it sends a message to the contras that they are not abandoned, that we do care about them and want to keep them healthy and a viable force,'' said rep. mickey edwards, r-okla., who participated in negotiations to draft the compromise
and it lets the sandinistas know that it's important to the united states congress that the talks that take place down there take place with good faith, and that they move toward democratization,'' edwards added
the agreement, made possible by a 60-day cease-fire reached by the two warring sides last week, broke a weeks-long deadlock in congress over whether to keep up the flow of u.s. aid. the house had killed efforts to provide new supplies to the rebels on two earlier occasions this year
in agreeing to the deal, republicans accepted wright's assurances that he would give any future request from president reagan for military aid for the rebels ``fair and orderly'' consideration
the white house apparently dropped its past insistence on an ironclad legal guarantee of an expedited vote, settling instead for the pledge contained in a letter from wright to the president and to minority leader robert michel, r-ill
wright's pledge says reagan can ask congress for additional rebel aid if nicaragua's leftist government violates the march 23 cease-fire or any later peace accord and if the contras continue to observe its terms. wright would send reagan's request to the appropriate house committee, which would have 10 days to act and return the measure to the full house for action
wright said other than the 10-day limit on committee consideration, the letter simply laid out the normal procedures of the house and in that sense represented a relatively small concession
the letter suggests, but does not require, that reagan first get advice on whether new military aid is warranted from a verification commission established by the march 23 agreement to oversee the cease-fire
the commission includes nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo, a government critic who is seen as partial to the rebels, and joao baena soares, secretary general of the organization of american states, who is aligned more with the leftist government
under the bill, $16.2 million in ``humanitarian'' aid _ defined as food, clothing, medical supplies and family support payments _ would be sent to the contras at a rate of $2.7 million a month for the next six months. it would be delivered by a neutral organization instead of the cia, which has delivered past aid when hostilities were under way
of that amount, $2.2 million is earmarked for a miskito indian contra group which already had reached its own peace accord with the sandinistas
the rebels would get another $1.5 million to buy communications gear, deemed essential to keeping contra troops in touch with their commanders during the cease-fire period. that pushes the total rebel aid to $17.7 million
an identical amount would go to create a new program of medical and humanitarian help for children who have been injured or suffered as a result of the civil war, which has claimed some 40,000 lives since 1981
in addition, the legislation provides $10 million to pay expenses of the verification commission and $2.5 million to pay administrative overhead for the state department's agency for international development, which would handle distribution of the money. with u.s. businesses paying taxes to government; picks up 11th graf pvs, ``owners of ...</note>
supermarkets, pharmacies and small shops opened for the first time in 10 days wednesday as a nationwide strike aimed at toppling gen. manuel antonio noriega began to fall apart
despite the defections, alberto boyd, president of the national council of private enterprise, said he and other strike leaders were not ending their effort to get rid of noriega
in washington, the reagan administration said it was considering new sanctions to force out noriega, but it appeared no action was imminent
the reopening of the capital's gago, rey and super 99 supermarkets signaled the first crack in a work stoppage that closed an estimated 90 percent of the nation's business and industry
later, the city's leading pharmacies reopened, as did some small clothing and other dry goods stores in the central business district
traffic, extremely light for days, began to build again on panama city's streets, with the usual jams of buses, taxis and private autos developing at major intersections
grocery stores were doing a brisk but not extraordinarily heavy business. customers were required to pay in cash and appeared to be buying mostly essentials
the government said some of the nation's banks, closed since march 3, would reopen thursday, but only to process old checks
even with a limited reopening of banks and some stores, there appeared to be no hope of a quick infusion of cash that would permit a return to normal commerce in the money-short nation
the cash crisis is due in part to u.s. economic sanctions against noriega, who is charged in the united states with drug trafficking. as chief of the 15,000-member defense forces, noriega is the real power behind panama's civilian government
some u.s. companies, including miami-based eastern airlines and harrison, n.y.-based texaco, inc., this week paid the government $5 million owed for taxes, a diplomatic source who spoke on condition of anonymity said wednesday
owners of the reopened grocery stores could not be reached for comment, but angelica guinard, a leader of the opposition national civic crusade leader, said they had been under strong government pressure to reopen
she said the pressure included threats of confiscation of their goods and personal threats against themselves and their families
however, an executive of the gago supermarket chain, the city's largest, said his company's stores opened ``because we have to pay our employees, and if we didn't open, we wouldn't have anything to do it with.''
he spoke on condition of anonymity
a woman leaving a rey supermarket in one of panama city's middle-class neighborhoods said she had bought only essentials: rice, milk, beans and soap
the kids don't understand,'' she said. ``they want to know why we don't have the kinds of things we had before.'' but she said the eldest, who turned 8 on saturday, is catching on
he said, `mommy, you can't throw a party for me because noriega won't leave,''' she said. she wouldn't give her name
felix navarro, a wholesale fruit and vegetable dealer who closed down his own business in the strike, carefully studied prices on five-pound bags of rice before choosing one
pointing to the rice and a container of cooking oil, he said, ``i had $100 in cash at the beginning of the month, and after i buy these, i'm broke.''
panama's chronic cash shortage worsened last month when noriega fired president eric arturo delvalle, touching off a panic run on the banks that eventually forced their closure
the united states aggravated the crisis by imposing a number of economic sanctions, including the freezing of millions of dollars in panamanian government funds held by u.s. banks
the reagan administration continues to recognize delvalle, who is in hiding, as panama's president
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters in washington on wednesday that ``other sanctions are being actively considered'' to force noriega's ouster
sen. alfonse m. d'amato, r-n.y., said noriega's troops have harassed and beaten panama canal employees. ``there is a continuing pattern of escalation'' in panamanian actions against the canal, he said in an interview on abc-tv's ``good morning america.'' he did not elaborate
on tuesday, noriega condemned the presence of the u.s. helicopter carrier okinawa on the pacific end of the panama canal. it passed through the canal tuesday on its way to its home port, san diego
the u.s. defense department said in washington that the passage was ``routine,'' but noriega called it ``a threat and an aggression.'' there was no immediate indication how long the vessel would stay in the area
public universities in alabama are not racially biased, despite the accusations of a u.s. justice department lawsuit, a lawyer for the major state university said wednesday
we feel the same as we always have _ that we're not guilty of segregating our schools,'' said robert l. potts, an attorney for the university of alabama system. ``when we get to the merits of the case in court, i think we'll prove that.''
the federal government suit was filed tuesday in u.s. district court. it was first filed in 1983, but had to be refiled after an appeals court ruled that the judge who heard the first case should have disqualified himself because he had participated in landmark civil rights cases as a private attorney
i would not agree that the case is starting from ground zero again,'' said nathaniel douglas of the justice department's civil rights division in washington, d.c
there have been efforts to resolve the case by negotiation, and we are ready to continue to do that.''
the refiled suit charges again that state education officials have ``perpetuated a racial dual system in public higher education.''
the justice department said two predominantly black schools, alabama a&amp;m in huntsville and alabama state in montgomery, are close to mainly white schools and were intended for black students only, while whites attended the other institutions
justice department lawyers said evidence exists of intentions by state authorities to maintain vestiges of a dual school system
federal attorneys cited a 1975 planning document of the alabama commission on higher education, one of the defendants, that said ``with alabama state and alabama a&amp;m to meet the needs of the state's negro citizens and with the university of alabama and auburn university as major state institutions, the state seemed relatively well served.''
the suit also names as defendants the state, gov. guy hunt, and several universities in the system. spokesmen for both the governor and for auburn university said they had no comment for the present
the suit said the state continues to allocate far more money to the major white schools than to the mainly black ones
state authorities contend the predominantly white and black schools in huntsville and montgomery are the result of decades-old patterns of preference by students
in 1985, u.s. district judge u.w. clemon ruled after a five-week trial that alabama maintains vestiges of a dual school system. before he could begin the remedy phase of the case, his ruling was appealed
the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals in atlanta ruled last year that clemon, alabama's first black federal judge, should have stepped down because of the rights cases he handled when he was a private attorney. `ridiculous'</head>
a planned meeting between two democratic presidential rivals collapsed wednesday, with jesse jackson saying albert gore had launched an attack on him that was ``more personal than principled.'' gore called jackson's charge ``ridiculous'' and said he was merely holding his rival to the same standard as any other candidate
the two traded charges a day after gore unleashed a broad assault on jackson's record as without experience and said he was dismayed by jackson's associations and middle east policies
in his latest remarks, gore defended his earlier criticism and said he had mentioned nothing that could be regarded as personal
there is no reason why anyone should think jesse jackson ought to be treated differently from any other candidate in this race,'' gore told reporters. ``that's not a personal attack, and i'm surprised he would see it as a personal attack.''
i think it's ridiculous,'' gore said. ``he's a major contender for the white house. is he to be immune from any questioning of his position on the issues or his approach to the campaign? it's ridiculous.''
gore commented at a news conference upon arriving in washington from a campaign trip through new york and wisconsin. only moments earlier, jackson had passed through the same private air charter terminal
the two had met on monday and, according to both campaigns, agreed to set aside time wednesday afternoon at national airport for a meeting since their schedules coincided. but late wednesday the meeting was canceled, the gore campaign saying it was jackson's move
before departing on his own trip to wisconsin, jackson told reporters the two were planning to meet
but jackson said that as a result of ``his attacks, which were more personal than principled, it's not necessary to meet at this time.''
jackson said they would meet ``at some future time.''
gore was informed of jackson's comments and responded, questioning whether anyone believed he should ``bend over backwards to not say anything that might possibly be interpreted as critical'' of jackson
is there supposed to be a separate standard?'' he asked. ``is there supposed to be some unwritten rule why jesse jackson cannot be criticized, why his positions have to be just sancrosanct and nobody can say anything about them for fear somebody will just misinterpret what your saying? i have from the start of this campaign treated him exactly the same as every other candidate in this race.''
i don't think he really wants to be treated differently, and if he thinks about it he won't really see a criticism of his positions as a personal attack.''
gore also took aim at dukakis, the delegate leader who was considered the frontrunner for the nomination, at least until his massive loss to jackson in michigan last weekend
gore faulted dukakis for what he said was a refusal to even contrast himself with jackson when asked
he was asked: `why would you make a better president?''' gore said of dukakis. ``he said, `i'm not going to answer that question.' i think that's ludicrous.''
on wednesday, however, dukakis moved cautiously to contrast some of his positions with those of jackson. he mentioned the middle east and domestic policy as points of difference, but declined to provide specifics
the chief contra military field commander, who has expressed reservations about the rebel truce with the nicaraguan sandinistas, said wednesday he supports the truce agreement and will comply with it
col. enrique bermudez, who has said he doesn't trust the sandinistas, told reporters his concerns about the truce do not mean he opposes contra leadership on the touchy issue
we understand there can be differences, but during negotiations we have to have a single position,'' he said at a news conference
as an indicator of that continuing mistrust, the contras said wednesday they have filed a formal complaint with the nicaraguan government about the way the sandinistas handled the weekend release of 100 political prisoners, a release called for in the truce agreement
contra spokeswoman marta sacasa said the rebels gave the sandinistas a list saturday of the 100 contras they wanted released, but only nine or 10 of those prisoners released were on the rebel list
she said the sandinistas had made a ``verbal agreement'' to use the contra suggestions but their response ``does not show enough good faith or trust.''
bermudez's comments wednesday came at the same time that contra directors are taking to the miami airwaves to calm opposition and fear in the nicaraguan community that the contra leadership gave up too much
fourteen nicaraguan exile leaders held a news conference in miami on monday to call for the contra leadership's resignation
sometimes it's very easy, sitting here in miami, to say, `my god, look what's been agreed to in sapoa,' without remembering that the fighting men, who are dying in the mountains of nicaragua, have been abandoned'' by congress, said director alfredo cesar, one of the leaders who helped negotiate the cease-fire. sapoa is the nicaraguan border town where the truce talks were held last week
congress has voted against continued military aid for the contras, though the house on wednesday approved a package of humanitarian aid
speaking on radio station waqi-am, cesar denied the truce was tantamount to surrender
but he said an armed guerrilla movement has been allowed to stay in place, while its leaders travel to the capital to discuss the nation's future
there is no precedent for this _ not even in guatemala, a democratic country, which requires that the communist guerrillas put down their arms before discussing the country's future,'' cesar said tuesday
a group of chinese students studying in america published an open letter this week, urging their government in beijing to abandon a new policy that will slash the number of china's students abroad
the letter, which began appearing in chinese-language newspapers on tuesday and wednesday, said the policy would be detrimental to china's drive to develop its economy
it also said the policy would force many chinese students in america to return home before obtaining their degrees
an american china expert linked the policy change to concerns in beijing that chinese students studying in the united states are becoming too westernized
the letter echoed an earlier petition, signed by 1,000 chinese students and sent to beijing in january 1987. that letter opposed conservative political policies in china
we are only asking that the right to study and complete our degrees be restored to us,'' said pei minxin, a 30-year-old doctoral candidate at harvard university. pei was one of 21 chinese ``coordinators'' who included their telephone numbers in the letter, inviting students who supported their position to call in and add their name to the list
so far, he said, more than 800 chinese students nationwide had contacted the coordinators and pledged to sign the new letter, which will be sent to beijing soon
we are not planning to use this movement as an excuse to stay here permanently,'' said pei, whose request last week to extend his passport was denied by chinese authorities. ``we just want to finish our degrees and go back to china.''
currently, about 40,000 chinese students are studying outside of china, 27,000 of them in the united states
under the new education policy, china will send only 3,000 students abroad this year, the overseas edition of the people's daily reported feb. 15
student sources in new york said chinese officials told them only 20 percent, or 600, would be sent to the united states. last year, 8,000 chinese students came to america
the policy also calls for strict limits on how long chinese students can stay abroad, according to a copy of an official document obtained from chinese sources in new york
the document says students seeking a master's degree must complete it within one or two years, and students working for a doctorate have only five years to finish it
that rule could be particularly onerous for many chinese, who come to the united states needing time to improve their english
zheng wanzhen, press councilor for the chinese embassy in washington, acknowledged that fewer students would be sent abroad but denied there was a policy change
it's just that they have been sending too many students to america,'' he said. china will send students to other countries like the soviet union, east germany, japan and western europe, he said
merle goldman, a professor of history at boston university, said the policy change marked a shift away from the liberal slant of chinese leader deng xiaoping, who opened the country to the west in the 1970s
not many students are returning to china and the chinese want them back,'' she said.the feb. 15 people's daily said of the 36,000 chinese who have come to america, only 8,817 have returned
in addition, ms. goldman said, when they do come home ``they are already infected by the political values of the united states. they absorb western political ideas and that could be troublesome for the chinese state.''
ms. goldman said premier li peng was responsible for the shift, which began last year when he took over as acting premier. israeli speakers. no pickup</note>
arab leaders and the plo bitterly condemned israel's crackdown in the occupied territories and called wednesday for an international peace conference to create an independent palestinian state
in an emergency security council meeting, israel rejected a conference and asked instead for direct negotiations with its neighbors
u.s. ambassador herbert s. okun accused the arabs of ``extreme rhetoric'' and said secretary of state george p. shultz will seek a forum in his forthcoming middle east mission that would permit direct negotiations leading to a comprehensive settlement
the 15-member council heard 10 speakers denounce israel's occupation of lands captured from the arabs and call for a u.n-sponsored peace conference involving all parties to the conflict, including israel, the plo and the five permanent members of the council
they denounced israel's sealing off the west bank and gaza, its imposition of a curfew and banning of journalists. saudi arabian and libyan envoys compared israel's treatment of palestinians to nazi persecution of jews
the council adjourned without a resolution or a vote but agreed to meet again to consider the situation in the occupied territories. since the palestinian protests began in december, the council has condemned israeli practices as violating palestinian human rights
farouk khaddoumi, the top envoy of the palestine liberation organization, told the council, ``peace can only be established through an end to israeli occupation and security can only reign if an independent palestinian state is established.''
khaddoumi is director of the plo political department, its equivalent to foreign minister. he accused the united states of supporting repression in the occupied territories and said washington encouraged prime minister yitzhak shamir of israel, whom he called ``a terrorist.''
the united states, he said, is using its veto power to prevent the security council from adopting measures that would prevent israeli ``crimes'' against palestinians
he said the palestinian people would never accept israel's proposal of autonomy as a substitute for sovereignty
the united nations recognizes the plo as the only legitimate representative of the palestinian people
israel considers the plo a terrorist organization
israeli ambassador johanan bein, the deputy permanent representative, condemned recent plo broadcasts which he said exhorted palestinians to throw rocks and attack israeli security forces with knives
the plo solution is dissolution of israel,'' bein said. ``this will not be the case. the plo has shown it will continue to fight to the last palestinian child, but this will never constitute a basis for peace, but only for violence.''
he said israel regrets the loss of life of arab or jew, ``but when confronted by unbridled mob violence, with stones, iron bars, fire bombs and even live ammunition, it has no alternative but to attempt to quell the violence and restore order.''
foreign minister ahmed taleb ibrahimi of algeria told the council ``it is high time for resolute action'' by the world community and asked for a u.n.-sponsored middle east peace conference to set up a palestinian state
there will only be peace,'' ibrahimi said, ``if there is total and unconditional evacuation of israel from all arab territories.''
ibrahimi is the leader of a high-level arab delegation visiting new york
more than 120 palestinians and one israeli soldiers have been killed since riots began dec. 8 in the west bank and gaza, which israel captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
speakers on the wednesday agenda included ibrahim massoud, minister of state for foreign affairs of saudi arabia; foreign minister farouk al-shara of syria, and chedli klibi, the arab league secretary-general
diplomats said earlier that a resolution and vote were unlikely, because resolutions critical of israel often are vetoed by the united states
two white police officers were convicted of murder wednesday in the killings of two black men said to be drug dealers
the rand supreme court convicted both sgt. robert van der merwe, 30, and capt. jack la grange, 40, on two counts of murder and one count of intent to murder after a three-week trial
van der merwe testified he shot the men because la grange duped him into believing they were linked to the african national congress guerrilla movement
i believed that what i was doing was in the national interest and it would never have occurred to me to question an order from an officer,'' he said
the blacks, who were alleged drug dealers, were killed in separate attacks last september and october
van der merwe testified he knew of ``clandestine operations'' in which security police carried out missions to kill suspected anc operatives
i realize that such actions are illegal in terms of the law, but i deem them lawful in terms of head office orders,'' he said
both van der merwe and la grange had pleaded innocent. they could face the death penalty, although there was no immediate word on sentencing
the anc is the main guerrilla group fighting apartheid, the system of racial segregation in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs and the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts and services
in other developments wednesday:
_police arrested 106 men and women demonstrating tuesday against a labor bill which would restrict union rights, according to frank meintjies, spokesman for the congress of south african trade unions, the nation's largest labor federation
police said in their daily unrest report for the preceding 24 hours that they arrested 124 people in industrial areas for gathering illegally and refusing to disperse. they gave no details, except to say they used batons and dogs to disperse one group
_authorities also reported that an unknown gunman wounded a 28-year-old municipal policeman in the chest in soweto, the black township outside johannesburg
_police said they used batons to disperse people gathered outside a court building in the mixed-race township of wynberg in cape town, but reported no injuries or arrests. no reason for the gathering was given
the star newspaper reported that the police charged a crowd of friends and relatives of 11 people on trial on treason charges in wynberg courthouse. magistrate a.s. mccarthy ordered the courtroom cleared after defendants and court spectators joined in singing a zulu anthem, ``god bless africa.''
_in pretoria, police cordoned off streets around the union buildings, where the government has its offices, and declared it an emergency area when 70 students from eight universities gathered to present petitions to president p.w. botha's office
the petitions protested last month's banning of 17 anti-apartheid organizations and recent government restrictions on protest activity on campuses
_in grahamstown, in eastern cape province, four black residents of uitenahage township were sentenced to death wednesday for the murder of a youth activist they allegedly believed had become a police informer. the sentences brought to 50 the number of people on death row for offenses connected with the three years of nationwide unrest from 1984-1987. fitzwater response to query on mrs. reagan and others wanting meese to go. picks up 13th graf pvs bgng: on tuesday ...</note>
senate majority leader robert byrd on wednesday called attorney general edwin meese iii ``the crown jewel of ... sleaze'' and urged him to quit, but meese said ``there's no reason to resign'' and president reagan reiterated his support for his old friend
meese, the focus of an 11-month criminal investigation that has sapped justice department morale, also predicted that solicitor general charles fried would not follow the path of two other officials who shook the department on tuesday by turning in their resignations
business is operating as usual at the justice department,'' meese told reporters. he said replacements were being sought for the two aides who resigned, that ``the management team is very strong and everything is going along well.''
asked by reporters whether he would quit, meese responded: ``no, not at all. there's no reason to.''
a republican, sen. bob packwood of oregon, joined other members of the senate in calling for meese to step down
deputy attorney general arnold burns and assistant attorney general william weld, who oversaw all federal criminal investigations, resigned because they were concerned that meese's continuing legal difficulties were damaging the effectiveness and credibility of the justice department, said department sources, speaking on condition of anonymity
at a meeting wednesday in meese's justice department office, fried, who ranks fourth in the justice department hierarchy, refused to give an immediate answer when meese personally urged him not to join burns and weld, the sources said
fried told the attorney general he would consider what to do in the next few days, the sources said
asked about the meeting with fried, meese said, ``i don't talk about my conversations with my top management people, but i have no doubt that mr. fried will remain a strong member of the management team.''
meese called at the white house late wednesday and met for 15 minutes with chief of staff howard baker, but spokesman marlin fitzwater said their discussion was about judicial appointments
fitzwater said meese did not meet with reagan and the two had not discussed the matter of the resignations, but he added, ``i'm sure the president will discuss it with him at some point.''
he did not say when. meese is expected to be at the white house again on thursday for a cabinet meeting
there have been reports indicating mrs. reagan is among those who want meese to go. fitzwater was asked why meese remained on the job when baker, vice president george bush and mrs. reagan were known to want him out
i don't think any of that is true,'' fitzwater replied. asked if he was denying it, he said, ``i don't know. i've never heard it said. i've never heard anybody say that.''
bush said wednesday he was troubled by the resignation of top justice department officials, but ``i'm not going to pass judgment'' on whether meese should resign. mrs. reagan has not publicly expressed an opinion on the attorney general's status
on tuesday, fried, who argues the government's position in supreme court cases, told the associated press the resignations had prompted him to reassess his own future. he said he needed time to think the matter through
congressional reaction against meese was strong the day after the resignations of burns, who is the no. 2 justice department official, and weld
mr. meese has become the crown jewel of the sleaze factor in reagan administration history,'' byrd, d-w.va., told reporters. he said that if reagan doesn't want to ask meese to quit he should find someone else to ask him
he ought to get out,'' said byrd. ``the country cannot have confidence in the justice department when the top law enforcement officer obviously has to spend an inordinate amount of his time defending himself. he should be spending his time fighting the war on drugs, crime,'' byrd said
but reagan, almost in reply, told reporters during a ceremony honoring young scientists in the white house rose garden, ``he's been a friend for over 20 years. i have every confidence in him. ... i'm not going to comment any further.''
of meese, packwood said ``you finally reach a place where there is a cloud of suspicion, a sufficient cloud of suspicion, that i think you owe it to the president to remove yourself.''
sen. arlen specter of pennsylvania, a republican member of the senate judiciary committee, declined to call for meese's resignation but said the attorney general owed the american people ``a full public explanation as to why his deputies have left.''
there's no doubt in my mind that it is very harmful to the republican party and could hurt our nominee in the fall,'' specter told reporters. ``but it is even more harmful to the country. i'm concerned as an american.''
specter accused byrd of trying to make the controversy over meese a partisan issue
when senator byrd starts to mix his metaphors and talk about crown jewels and sleaze it's totally inappropriate,'' specter said
the criminal investigation of meese launched last may 11 by independent counsel james mckay is continuing and so far has delved into his involvement through longtime friend e. robert wallach with scandal-plagued wedtech corp. and a $1 billion iraqi pipeline
mckay widened the probe this week by subpoenaing payroll records and other documents of the washington chapter of the multiple sclerosis society in connection with a $40,000-a-year job meese's wife, ursula, got with the charity in 1985. investigators are examining wallach's role in helping mrs. meese get the job
fitzwater confirmed that burns and weld had met with baker last week
the gentlemen indicated they wanted to resign, or they were disenchanted, and they were advised to talk to the attorney general about that. that's the proper way to do it, the proper course of action,'' fitzwater said
the spokesman said reagan ``has been briefed on the concerns and complaints of burns and weld. he just wanted to be kept informed.''
he said the two officials met with baker on march 16 and then again tuesday morning before they resigned. ``certainly the president was briefed on that meeting,'' fitzwater said
on capitol hill, sen. patrick leahy, d-vt., said meese ``has shown no willingness to resign, but he ought to at least step aside because he can't run the department of justice. he's lost all effectiveness.''
sen. dennis deconcini, d-ariz,. said he also is drafting a letter to meese calling on him to resign because of his ``lack of credibility and confidence.''
but sen. orrin g. hatch, r-utah, said meese should remain in office ``until the special prosecutor comes up with his conclusions.''
if he concludes there was impropriety that's another question,'' hatch said
byrd, leahy, deconcini and hatch all are members of the senate judiciary committee, which oversees operations of the justice department
jessica mcclure, whose rescue from a midland well attracted international attention, arrived wednesday to help raise funds for a boy with serious lung problems
jessica, who turned 2 last saturday, will participate in a balloon release thursday to benefit 5-year-old brennan bolin, said benefit coordinator bonnie arnold
the families of the children are acquainted and that is how jessica got involved, according to mrs. arnold
