a bomb damaged a textile plant in cordoba early wednesday and more than 20 telephoned bomb threats were received in buenos aires, police reported
bombs exploded in three buenos aires movie theaters tuesday, wounding four people, including a national policeman who lost a hand and an eye
president raul alfonsin blamed ``terrorists'' trying to ``put an end to democracy'' for the explosions
in addition to the blast at the pompas brothers plant in cordoba, an industrial city in central argentina, and the three theater explosions in the capital, 16 bombings have been carried out or attempted since january. most were in buenos aires
telephoned threats were reported throughout the day wednesday but no bombs were found, officials said. banks, hospitals, municipal buildings and shopping arcades were evacuated because of the calls
a group has left leaflets at most bombing sites carrying the initials ``o.a.s.-m.r.p.'' the meaning of the initials is not known
officials say the group is thought to be linked to former lt. col. aldo rico, 44, who led two unsuccessful rebellions in army units during the past year
rico, however, issued a communique wednesday night denying any connection with the bombings
the uprisings he led were the most serious threats to alfonsin since his civilian government took office in december 1983, ending nearly eight years of military rule
rico's communique said the bombings were ``contrary to the essence of `operation dignity,''' his effort to win pardons for officers accused of human rights violations during the government's 1976-83 campaign against suspected leftist subversives
at least 9,000 people were abducted and vanished without a trace during what became known as the ``dirty war'' under military rule in argentina, officials say
the former colonel is being held at the magdalena military prison 60 miles south of buenos aires
eighteen months before tawana brawley's alleged abduction, a schoolmate told police a markedly similar story of being kidnapped and sexually assaulted, according to broadcast and published reports
