the news service has come under increasing pressures as a fundamentalist wing gained control of denominational operations
but the executive committee said the requested investigation of stories issued over the last 10 years would be a ``prohibitive task of studying more than 9,000 releases
the 50-member administrative board of u.s. catholic bishops voted that their june meeting include a discussion of aids, about which policy had become controversial
some bishops objected to a statement issued by the board last december, saying pre-marital celibacy and martical fidelity were the only safeguards against aids, but public schools might provide information about condoms
bishops of the evangelical lutheran church in america say ``persons of homosexual orientation'' seeking ordination or who already are ordained ``are expected to refrain from homosexual pracrtice.''
the statement came after three senior seminarians at pacific lutheran theological seminary at berkeley, calif., announced they are homosexual and have been assigned as pastoral candidates in west coast synods
bishop herbert w. chilstrom, head of the denomination, said the church's ministry embraces all people, including homosexuals, but the church must set standards for those called as pastors
he said the church draws a distinction between homosexual orientation and homosexual practice, and many denominations have clergy who may be homosexually oriented, but he added:
the church will not ordain persons who engage in homosexual behavior nor will it permit such persons to be on the clergy roster if such pracrtice is discovered.''
it's the big switch, the great turn-about, a joke on death. ancient imagery has the resurrected christ confronting the devil and laughing at him about it
that's a little known aspect of easter lore, the zanily uproarious, upside down funniness of a holiday christians celebrate this weekend
blessed are you that weep now, for you shall laugh,'' jesus said, and the fellowship of merry christians seeks to restore that bubbling note of laughter to the occasion
the ``joke that god played on satan by raising jesus from the dead was indisputably the greatest and most imaginative practical joke in the history of the world,'' says carl samra
samra of box 668, kalamazoo, mich., is coordinator of the ecumenical fellowship, grown to about 10,000 members, and editor of its news-and-joke bimonthly, ``the joyful noiseletter.''
the fellowship, which sees humor and delight in faith and circulates comic anecdotes about it, wants to resurrect an old christian custom _ celebrating ``bright monday'' _ a day for merry pranks and frolic
also called ``white monday,'' it comes the day after easter, and according to the fellowship, used to be celebrated as a ``day of joy and laughter'' by roman catholic, protestant and eastern orthodox believers
it's a time for ``the laughing of the redeemed, the dancing of the liberated,'' writes noted german protestant theologian jurgen moltman
as jesus put it, ``your sorrow will turn into joy.'' he reassured his apostles ``that my joy may be in you and that your joy may be full.''
such passages inspired artist r. s. riddick of tucson, ariz., to paint his sketch of jesus smiling, ``the joyful christ.'' another painting, ``jesus laughing,'' is by willis wheatley of praise screen prints, traverse city, mich
 the fellowship of merry christians sponsors its ``holy humor month'' in april, with monday set for a day of happy festivities _ picnics, singing, dancing, telling jokes and fun
mrs. soule papademetriou, librarian at orthodoxy's holy cross school of theology in brookline, mass., says that in early greek tradition, easter monday was a ``day of joy and laughter'' at christ's triumph over death
that zest, games and high spirits continued through ``bright week,'' she says
although origins of the celebration are hazy, she says, it may have been inspired by an easter midnight sermon by fourth-century greek preacher john chrysostom who envisioned the resurrected christ laughing at the devil
hell was angered when it encountered thee (christ) in the lower regions...for it was mocked (ridiculed with laughter),'' chrysostom said
an old adage has it that the devil can't stand the sound of laughter, and slinks away from it
monsignor arthur tonne of marion, kan., a roman catholic priest of 83 and author of five volumes of ``jokes priests can tell,'' says several catholic orders have observed monday as a day of fun
the rev. francis weiser in ``the easter book,'' writes that in early christianty ``all of easter week was one continuous feast'' and easter monday remains a legal holiday in most european countries
he says in medieval times, easter monday was a time of ``special festivities,'' of ``emmaus walks'' into the woods and fields for pinics, folk dancing, singing and games
one sport was was called ``drenching,'' a good-natured game in which boys and girls in outlandish costumes doused each other or their families with buckets or bottles of water, reciting playful ditties
a protestant custom in england was ``heaving.'' groups of men carrying a chair aloft would go from house to house, getting a lady to sit in the chair, then lifting her three times, shouting hurrahs, demanding forfeit of a kiss
during this ``holy humor month,'' the fellowship urges divided christians to be, in the word's of the apostle paul, ``fools for christ,'' to see the follies of their divisions and work for christian unity
that was what jesus prayed for on the night before his crucifixion that led to his resurrection _ that ``all may be one so that the world may believe.''
at the sound of the knock, a young mutt named roody padded over to the door to look, then walked back into the kitchen and pawed at cary voorhees to get her attention
good girl, roody,'' ms. voorhees said, enthusiastically petting the dog as it led her to the door
roody, a 10-month-old stray with the spots of an australian shepherd, was undergoing training at dogs for the deaf, the oldest training center in the country for hearing-ear dogs
dogs for the deaf was founded 10 years ago on a former dairy farm near this rustic southern oregon town. each graduate earns an orange collar and leash and become the ears for a deaf person who has been waiting as long as a year
we have people tell us after they get a dog that they never realized how many people came over and they just didn't hear them at the door,'' said robin dickson, who took over running dogs for the deaf after the death of her father, roy kabat, the founder
a smart dog led kabat to start dogs for the deaf, his daughter explained
there was a deaf lady in minnesota,'' she said. ``she had a dog that had trained itself to let her know when there was a sound
the dog got hit and killed by a car. she went to her audiologist and said, `you've got to get me another dog
he contacted the american humane society in denver, and they called my dad in. he had worked for many years training dogs for movies in southern california and was retired. he became so intrigued by it that he came back here and started dogs for the deaf.''
pins in a map on the office wall show that the 300 dogs placed by dogs for the deaf are spread from coast to coast, with heavy concentrations in the big cities
we very carefully screen the applicants,'' mrs. dickson said. ``if you can hear a smoke alarm go off, you don't need a dog.''
deaf people who have someone at home who can hear are ineligible
they also have to be able to physically and financially care for a dog once they get it,'' mrs. dickson said. ``sometimes we can arrange a sponsor for a dog if a person can't afford it.''
the four trainers go to humane society shelters around oregon and northern california to find small to medium-sized dogs that are playful, alert and comfortable around people. ``if you had a great big great dane jumping up on you to let you know the phone was ringing, that wouldn't be so good,'' mrs. dickson said
the dogs mostly are mutts
so many purebreds are so inbred that their disposition and temperament are destroyed,'' mrs. dickson said
about half of the dogs flunk out before their three to six months of training is done, trainer doreen james said
stubbornness is one of the major reasons,'' she said. ``that doesn't show up for one to three months. it's lots of fun for them until they realize they have to do it all the time.''
in a one-bedroom apartment built in the loft of the old dairy barn, the dogs learn to respond to a telephone, a knock at the door, a smoke alarm, an oven buzzer and a baby's cry
trainers also take the dogs to nearby grants pass and medford to get used to the bustle of stores, being around people and riding in cars
the dogs are rewarded by praise, attention and play
you have to be really up,'' ms. voorhees said. ``some dogs take a week to learn to put their paws on the table.''
once the dog is ready, the trainer takes it to the recipient, spending five days there while they get used to each other
a fully trained dog represents an investment of $3,000, which is covered by contributions from supporters of the program
we get more people who send us donations to help the dogs than to help the deaf people,'' mrs. dickson said. ``we help save the unwanted dogs, so they want to help us.''
dogs are by no means the only aids for the deaf, who nowadays can choose from an array of mechanical devices, including smoke alarms with intense flashing lights, alarm clocks that flash or make the bed shake, and bracelets that vibrate at the sound of a baby crying
demand is also growing for telecommunications devices for the deaf, keyboards known as tdds that plug into the phone to allow people to type messages to each other, and decoders for closed-caption television
it's a very big market, and it's growing rapidly,'' said debbie ander, vice president of marketing for compu-tty, a national distributer for aids for the deaf based in fort worth, texas
anita farb, administrative assistant for the national association of the deaf in silver spring, md., said the 16 million americans with hearing problems are demanding more as they become aware of what is available
the demand for hearing-ear dogs is steadily growing, mrs. dickson said
to meet the demand, dogs for the deaf is moving to bigger quarters in central point, where there will be kennels for 60 dogs instead of 25, and four training apartments instead of one
the dogs give unconditional love,'' mrs. dickson said. ``to a lot of deaf people, this is the most important thing, because they lead such isolated lives.''
a curious new program is going out over poland's state radio every monday morning
it's called ``the west speaks,'' and it is composed entirely of excerpts of polish-language broadcasts by radio free europe, the voice of america, the british broadcasting corp. and other western radio stations
the segments are broadcast without comment or counterpoint, but since the program went on the air the polish media and officials have criticized the western broadcasts with greater frequency
the western stations always have been characterized here as hostile propaganda tools, but communist government says ``the west speaks'' is one way to counter the influence of the broadcasts that deliver a mixture of uncensored news, features and commentary
poland stopped the electronic jamming of western broadcasts jan. 1 and poles now can freely tune in to them
but government authorities have been raising the question of their fairness with western officials, including the director of the u.s. information agency, charles z. wick, who was here on a visit in march
the authorities say that in the struggle for the hearts and minds of the polish people, they cannot afford to overlook the influence of the western stations
it doesn't matter how many people listen to it when it is something very dangerous,'' government spokesman jerzy urban said in an interview. ``even if it's only 100 people, that is enough, because the report will spread.''
at one time, particularly during the cold war years in the 1950s, it was a crime to listen to the western stations
today, however, the strains of ``yankee doodle dandy,'' the sign-on tune of the voice of america, can be heard coming from apartments in housing blocks
urban said polish authorities believed that countering the broadcasts with ``polemics and arguments'' was better than continuing the jamming
a public opinion poll quoted by the official news agency pap said 80 percent of respondents approved the decision to end the jamming, but it said the number of listeners has not risen significantly
how many people actually listen remains a matter of dispute
according to a survey quoted by urban, the percentage of poles who listen to radio free europe either regularly or occasionally is 16 percent, up 2 percentage points since jamming ended. only 3 percent, or 1.2 million out of the population of 37.5 million, listen as often as once a week, he said
but the board for international broadcasting, the body that oversees radio free europe in munich, west germany, says 59 percent of poles listen to its broadcasts occasionally and nearly 14 percent at least once a week
an informal survey of half a dozen warsaw residents indicated that most preferred the voice of america or the bbc to radio free europe, known as rfe, on grounds that their information was more reliable
recent rfe broadcasts were heavy with reports of demonstrations and protests in poland, speeches and statements by leaders of the outlawed solidarity trade union and accounts of opposition activities in other countries of the soviet bloc
the west speaks'' was conceived ``to show what sort of argumentation is used by these stations,'' said witold stankowski, an executive of polish radio one
he said the show, which premiered in october, was given a time slot when ``we have a pretty good audience,'' but said he could not judge its popularity or say how long it would be continued
in recent months a drumbeat of commentaries have shown up on the pap service and in state-run newspapers disputing specific news items on the western stations. urban has made denunciations of the broadcasts almost a fixture at his weekly news conferences
in the interview, urban noted that listenership tends to rise in times of public anxiety, such as during the 1986 chernobyl nuclear accident in the soviet union
he claimed rfe's ``disgraceful methods'' frightened people in its reports on chernobyl and in its coverage of poland's announcement in late january of price increases totaling 42 percent in 1988
radio free europe presents the opinion that prices in fact will go up twice as much,'' he said. ``they want to cause, and really do cause, an increase in wage demands.''
u.s. ambassador john davis defends the broadcasts
the great bulk of what goes out seems to me to be a repetition of what already has been published in the west,'' he said. ``it is broadcast in, sometimes with comment, and comment is fair game.''
wick, the usia director who arrived in poland on march 23 for a series of talks with polish officials, said the polish side raised objections about radio free europe and the voice of america and the complaints were discussed ``very forthrightly.''
wick said the voice of america, which is part of usia, and radio free europe, which is privately operated but largely funded by the u.s. government, have charters that mandate that they be ``objective and accurate.''
i invited the authorities to give me specific instances when they were not,'' he said
he added that editorials on radio free europe and the voice of america are not intended to be objective, but to ``reflect the editorial viewpoint of the united states government.''
as such, he said, they might not be pleasing to poland
if the academy awards were based on box-office popularity, ``fatal attraction'' would eliminate its four opponents and win as best picture with ease
if oscars were based on media acclaim, ``broadcast news'' no doubt would be the winner. the funny, incisive look at how network journalists do their jobs under constant pressure captivated most critics, yet ``broadcast news'' has been a disappointment at the box office
despite mediocre attendance and mixed notices, the home-stretch favorite for best picture of 1987 is the ``the last emperor,'' a mammoth epic centering on the life of pu yi, boy emperor of china and later puppet ruler of manchuria for the japanese. bernardo bertolucci was nominated for director and co-writer, but the actors were overlooked
the thriller ``fatal attraction'' was by far the biggest moneymaker of the year, its combination of adultery and terror selling $150 million worth of tickets in the united states and canada
fatal attraction'' also picked up nominations for michael douglas, glenn close and anne archer, as well as director adrian lyne and writer james dearden
lyne, a graduate of british tv commercials, admits that he was sold on ``fatal attraction'' from the time he read the script
it was a page-turner,'' he said. ``it was sent to me when i was in france. i sat down on some steps, and two hours later i was still on the steps, finishing it off. it was something i couldn't put down. i thought if i could provide the visual equipment and not screw it up, that it had a fighting chance of being as interesting a movie.''
lyne signed on with producers stanley jaffe and sherry lansing and worked with dearden on the script. the director carries a tape recorder while preparing a film, and he made notes of matters he could use, such as his own son's attempt to demonstrate card tricks
the three leading actors of ``broadcast news'' _ william hurt, holly hunter and albert brooks _ also were nominated for awards. james l. brooks was named as writer and producer but, astoundingly, did not receive a nomination as director
i wanted to do a romantic comedy,'' brooks said. ``just through a series of circumstances i wound up being around a number of network news people.''
brooks, who once worked as a news writer for cbs news, spent months hanging around in studios of washington and new york for his research. the result is a verisimilitude that has attracted the praise of many network news people, including the curmudgeonly andy rooney
bertolucci amazed the film world by winning permission to film a movie with political overtones within china. more amazingly, he was able to shoot inside the fabled forbidden city, the shrine of chinese history
the fact that this movie exists is another proof that china is changing,'' the italian director said. ``only eight years ago it was inconceivable for the chinese to let a western filmmaker do a scene about the red guards, as at the end of the movie when you see the cultural revolution.''
nominee ``hope and glory'' is john boorman's valentine to his boyhood during the battle of britain. the writer-director-producer won triple nominations, but his actors received none. the movie's box-office performance has been less than impressive
despite the background of german bombings, the film is primarily comedic
for me as a child, the experience of the war was largely one of exhilaration, joy and fun,'' boorman said. ``this is what the film is; it's great entertainment, it's very funny. there were moments of horror, when people were killed. as a child, you forget this very quickly.''
also up for best film of the year is ``moonstruck,'' a romantic comedy about an excitable italian family in brooklyn. cher, vincent gardenia and olympia dukakis are acting nominees, as well as director norman jewison and writer john patrick shanley
moonstruck'' has been a major success at the box office, doing more than $50 million in business so far
after a pair of heavy dramas, ``a soldier's story'' and ``agnes of god,'' jewison ``was in the mood for a romantic comedy.'' his first choice to play loretta, the widow torn between two lovers, was cher
for me, there has always been something `streety' about cher, a lacking in pretension,'' the canadian director said. ``she's a very honest person _ in-person and on the screen. she looks italian, although she's part armenian and part cherokee.''
yet directors don't always get their first choice for lead performers, as was the case with ``fatal attraction.'' as right as glenn close might seem for the role of the jilted alix, director lyne said isabelle adjani was actually his first choice, since she had played a similar role in a french film
but after a few months of casting _ i like to see everyone i can _ i thought it would be more effective to go with someone who was not obviously sensual from the outset,'' he said
glenn close pursued the movie and was prepared to come in and test, which was unusual for a star. when i saw her testing with michael (douglas), it was already decided on.''
lyne had once worked with douglas as producer on ``starman,'' which he ended up not directing
i had seen michael almost every day for a year, and i saw him as a man who was infinitely charming to both men and women but was also very vulnerable,'' lyne said. ``i had never seen that in movies he had done. i had always seen more of his father _ the heroic, the macho qualities.''
doubts about ritalin, a drug used to help hyperactive children concentrate, have drawn the attention of lawyers and reporters and prompted some parents to halt treatment. but the associated press has found the firestorm is being fanned by a group with ties to the church of scientology and a history of opposition to psychiatry. in the first story of a three-day series, `r' is for ritalin, the ap examines the group's role in the ritalin furor
twelve-page pink pamphlets are being handed out on street corners across the country, sounding frightening alarms in bold-face type about ritalin, a prescription drug used for three decades to calm hyperactive children
warning: ritalin can lead to suicide
warning: ritalin can be addictive
warning: ritalin overdose can cause death
in newspaper stories, on talk shows, at medical conventions, news conferences and neighborhood meetings, the group behind the pamphlets makes other claims _ that ritalin is as dangerous as cocaine, causes delinquency and crime, is given to 80 percent of children in some maryland schools, even that psychiatrists advocate putting it in school drinking water supplies
researchers and government regulators looking into the legitimate worries about misuse or over-prescription of ritalin ridicule these ``facts'' as distortions and exaggerations of their work. because the claims are constantly recycled without qualification or context, they say, parents are panicking unnecessarily
ritalin is a safe, effective drug. i don't know of any major problems with it,'' said dr. paul leber, director of neuropharmacological products at the u.s. food and drug administration
the anti-ritalin campaign is run from a sparsely furnished second-story office here decorated with pictures of l. ron hubbard, founder of the church of scientology, and staffed by people wearing ``psychiatry kills'' sweatshirts
it is the headquarters of the citizens commission on human rights, a 19-year-old organization sponsored by the scientologists, the contentious religious group based just down the street
the campaign, complete with toll-free hotline, has made cchr's president, dennis clarke, a 41-year-old member of the scientology church, perhaps the most quoted ritalin expert in the country
it has taken the group coast to coast whenever a ritalin case catches public attention, be it a trial in massachusetts, conferences in minnesota and texas, or the filing of at least 13 lawsuits
ritalin acts as a chemical straitjacket,'' clarke said in an interview with the associated press, repeating an oft-quoted claim. ``we are not dealing with a lightweight drug, but parents are told it's like vitamins.''
what is not always clear in cchr-supplied information is the group's ties to the scientologists and that church's predisposition against the mental health profession. since its inception in 1969, cchr has attacked psychiatry, centering on treatments such as electric shock and drugs
its latest goal, clarke said, is to use lawsuits to bring about a ban on ritalin, which he calls ``one of the most dangerous and addictive substances known to man.''
this fervor, medical experts say, is slanting the debate on ritalin use
it's been wild, absolutely wild, really bizarre,'' said dr. jerry wiener, president of the american academy of child and adolescent psychiatry. ``something calls itself the citizens commission on human rights and all of a sudden it gets a lot of credibility, and they're being quoted without any kind of substantiation.''
ritalin has enjoyed success in treating children with a condition now widely known as attention deficit disorder. it reacts chemically to help calm their fidgeting, ease their impulsive, sometimes destructive behavior, and focus their attention so they do better in school
yet no one denies that ritalin, a drug classified with amphetamines, must be used carefully. although its acknowledged side effects are mostly mild and passing, doctors say children taking the drug must be closely monitored and counseled. and some share worries with cchr that ritalin is being improperly urged on parents by teachers and schools
its sharply increased use is indicated by the number of prescriptions filled, which rose 14 percent from 1983 to 1986; prescriptions for most drugs increase about 1 percent a year, according to federal statistics
i have a concern about overuse and abuse where the drug is used alone,'' wiener said. ``when any drug begins to be known as effective, you have to be careful about overuse _ like valium and librium.''
in the rush to reexamine ritalin's role, much press attention has focused on the lawsuits filed on behalf of distressed parents
but most stories fail to note that of the 13 suits in california, minnesota, massachusetts, georgia and the district of columbia, one is being handled by cchr's counsel and the others were filed by two lawyers who get ritalin data _ and sometimes clients _ through cchr
they are very efficient and a wealth of information,'' said one of those lawyers, john coale, who has represented victims of the bhopal, india, cyanide gas disaster and the dupont plaza hotel fire in puerto rico
some of the suits accuse not only pediatricians or psychiatrists of wrongdoing, but also teachers and school districts involved in children's treatment
the only thing that will turn this around is the same thing that turned around exploding pintos and thalidomide _ and that's major, major multi-million-dollar lawsuits,'' clarke said. ``unfortunately, that means suing schools as well as psychiatrists.''
at the heart of the ritalin dispute are the claims and data used by cchr. among its questioned statements:
_ clarke often says 4 million american children are taking ritalin, four times as many as estimated by the most liberal researchers. when asked for his source, clarke cited a specific newspaper story. when it was pointed out that the article makes no mention of 4 million children, clarke replied, ``i don't know how many. i just know it's too many.''
_ clarke frequently asserts that 80 percent of the students in a maryland school system are taking ritalin. asked to identify the system, he amended his assertion to just one school and said the information came from an attorney who handles ritalin suits. asked about the attorney's sources, clarke cited an unidentified parent told by an unidentified neurologist
clarke said he repeats the 80 percent figure because he believes it's true. ``there's enough of it there (in maryland) to have them all on it,'' he said
_ clarke says ritalin may have caused a 600-percent increase in child suicide over five years. he cites medical manual warnings that suicide is a complication of withdrawal from drugs such as ritalin. but doctors say the danger is minimal when the drug is used properly
i have children who go off of it every weekend,'' said dr. ralph s. smith jr., a charleston, w.va., child psychiatrist. ``i have children who go off every summer because they only need it during school.'' nevertheless, smith said, three of his add patients stopped taking ritalin after their parents read an article highlighting cchr claims
_ cchr refers to a california study which, clarke asserts, shows children treated with ritalin commit more felonies later in life. the study's author, dr. james satterfield, says that is a complete misreading
satterfield, a psychiatrist and director of the national center for hyperactive children in encino, calif., and his wife, psychologist breena satterfield, studied 130 hyperactive boys, all of whom received ritalin and 50 of whom also received therapy and behavioral advice
in general, hyperactive children exhibit higher than normal rates of misbehavior and delinquency, but the boys who received therapy as well as ritalin had lower levels of delinquency
while it is true that ritalin by itself has not been found to prevent delinquency,'' satterfield said, ``it most certainly has never been found to cause delinquency.''
eds: this sty may be considered complete in one take. for those desiring more detail, a second take follows
in a report to congress last year, agencies including the national institutes of health, the food and drug administration, the national institute of mental health and the centers for disease control said ``the side effects are minimal'' for children treated with ritalin
ritalin's manufacturer, ciba-geigy corp., is straightforward about the side effects, which include nervousness, insomnia, rashes, anorexia, nausea, headaches and weight loss. some evidence suggests it can temporarily retard growth
ciba-geigy also cautions about its use by emotionally unstable patients and the possibility of severe depression in unsupervised withdrawal from the drug
clarke complains these warnings don't reach parents and further asserts that psychiatrists have used drugs to create a self-perpetuating industry. those who dispute him, he adds, are trying to protect their business
these are the baby-druggers,'' clarke said. ``i believe i'm pretty conservative with my information. ... the whole thing does not exist because of scientology. the problem exists because children are being harmed.''
clarke defends his allegations, saying they are based on medical literature, and contends doctors who prescribe ritalin aren't acknowledging its dangers
psychiatrists, however, say cchr attacks them because of their basic philosophical difference with the church of scientology, which does not recognize mental illness as a physiological problem
scientology, founded by science fiction writer hubbard in 1954, is based on a theory called ``dianetics'' which says physical and mental problems can be solved by using an ``e-meter,'' an electric device set up much like a lie detector. members are assigned exercises and counseling to eliminate negative mental images and achieve a ``clear state.''
the church supports cchr, clarke said, because the group is ``part of the basic philosophy _ things having to do with the spiritual nature of man. you don't deal with the spirit by lobotomizing someone or using electric shock. it's not only bad science, it's harmful for the being.''
clarke is a convincing speaker with a seemingly endless catalog of ritalin horror stories. he left a successful solar heating business in hawaii in 1985 to run cchr, and travels constantly, using local issues as a platform for his crusade
just before 15-year-old rod matthews, an emotionally troubled youth who used ritalin, was tried for the murder of classmate shaun ouillette, 14, in canton, mass., clarke appeared on local talk shows. after the trial, he held a news conference to announce more lawsuits
last year, the local cchr chapter staged a demonstration in canton. the victim's mother, jeanne quinn, said a couple holding a sign reading ``ritalin killed shaun, not rod'' came to her door, asked for her and offered pamphlets on the dangers of ritalin
matthews' defense included claims that ritalin worsened his severe mental problems. the jury found him sane and convicted him of second-degree murder. he was sentenced to life in prison, eligible for parole after 15 years
ironically, the victim had taken ritalin for four years, successfully conquering his hyperactivity
they look for cases like this and grab onto it for their own purposes,'' mrs. quinn said of cchr. ``i have little respect for any of their opinions. they take small quotations and excerpts from medical books and give you their opinion. everything is out of context.''
when the university of minnesota held a conference on add last summer, cchr members staged rallies, hung signs on expressway overpasses, announced a ritalin lawsuit and staged a rock concert for a ``drug free america.''
the following week my practice received roughly 40 phone calls from parents concerned about the medication,'' said dr. jeffrey alexander, a pediatrician at minneapolis' park nicollet medical center who has about 200 patients on ritalin. three or four actually discontinued treatment, he said
experts like the satterfields say that while they are concerned that ritalin needs to be used properly, they worry that because cchr is trading on parents' fears, children not getting treatment they need
it's unfortunate that these children become the victims of special interest groups instead of being looked at for their individual requirements,'' said mrs. satterfield. ``fear doesn't contribute to good treatment of children and good medical practices.''
to calm hyperactive children, doctors give them a stimulant
the seemingly contradictory effects of stimulants on hyperactive youngsters have been known since the 1930s. when used carefully, most experts agree, they are safe and effective
the most commonly prescribed of these medicines is a mild central nervous system stimulant called ritalin. the drug, known generically as methylphenidate, was first sold in 1955 to improve mental performance in the elderly and reduce fatigue
now it is the mainstay of treatment for attention deficit disorder in children, which parents usually recognize by its most common and distressing symptom, hyperactivity
experts say as many as 80 percent of add youngsters may be helped by drug treatment, but the extent of their improvement varies
thirty percent of the kids who have attention deficit disorder do so well on the drug that the parents want to kiss you on both cheeks,'' said dr. jonathan cole of mclean hospital, a harvard-affiliated mental hospital in belmont, mass. ``other kids are sort of better or not really better at all.'' the underlying cause of the disorder and the reason stimulants calm children and help them concentrate are still mysteries
genes play some role. studies show one-third of all youngsters with add have parents with the ailment. about half the youngsters with add outgrow the problem by adolescence; the rest carry it into adulthood
this drug has been around for 50 years and marketed for 30,'' said dr. ron kartzinel of ciba-geigy, the company that makes ritalin. ``we really cannot fully explain, biochemically or physiologically, how the drug works in attention deficit disorder. there are many theories, but they are just that _ theories.''
other drugs used to treat the disorder are cylert, or pemoline, and dexedrine, or dextroamphetamine. all of them stimulate the brain to produce chemical messengers that brain cells use to alert and stimulate their neighbors. experts believe this increase in brain chemicals has something to do with the drugs' beneficial effects
the drugs do carry side effects, but most are mild and passing. some youngsters lose their appetites and have trouble falling asleep for the first week or two they take ritalin
ritalin can also slow youngsters' growth. dr. david zametkin of the national institute of mental health said doctors should monitor patients' height and weight. if growth slows, they should take them off the drug temporarily, during summer vacation, for example. the youngsters then have a growth spurt and catch up
another, but extremely rare, side effect is tics and twitches. zametkin said that when the drugs are stopped, these problems almost always go away
at ciba-geigy, kartzinel said that over the last 16 years, the company has received 17 reports of slowed growth and 10 reports of tics associated with ritalin
a few years ago, doctors feared that ritalin caused tourette's syndrome, a disorder in which people make involuntary movements and noises. however, zametkin said it now appears tourette's syndrome itself is often preceded by symptoms that resemble those for add
some youngsters who are treated with ritalin for add subsequently develop tourette's syndrome, he said, but this would have happened anyway, regardless of whether they got the drug
zametkin said the stimulants do not, as some parents fear, make children high or euphoric. instead, if they take too much, they tend to become moody and irritable
if you know anybody who ever took dexedrine to stay up and study, they got some of the same effects as these kids _ improved concentration, decreased distractability and less fatigue,'' said cole. ``it's sort of like super-coffee, although it makes you feel less jittery.''
pat robertson's presidential candidacy may have ground to a halt but his famed ``invisible army'' is still on the march, threatening in some places to take over the republican party, planting the seeds for a robertson resurgence in 1992
battles already fought or being waged this spring could leave the party machinery in part or entirely under the command of forces loyal to the former television evangelist in such states as georgia, oklahoma, south carolina, north carolina, virginia, louisiana, michigan, minnesota, iowa, nevada, hawaii and alaska
that will make things easier for robertson if he chooses, as he has hinted he will, to run again for the republican presidential nomination in four years _ even if it means challenging an incumbent republican
the robertson campaign hit the wall in the south on super tuesday, and the candidate has conceded that george bush will win the gop nomination, but his people are not giving up. they are still winning skirmishes across the map, in places where a precinct's party machinery can be seized merely by turning out a handful of loyalists to the cause
we in the evangelical right are here to stay,'' said robertson activist tom vestal, pastor of the mount olivet baptist church in raleigh, n.c., where supporters of robertson and george bush may wind up in court in a fight over the composition of the state's delegation to this summer's republican national convention
we're not trying to take over the party but we want to be an influence, to ensure that the party is an instrument of godliness, righteousness and morality,'' vestal said
robertson talks of his people running for congress and state legislatures in 1990, and of using his troops ``to maybe lay the foundations for something in 1992.''
we have hundreds of thousands of people who are right now in the republican party who have never been there before and they all, almost to a man, are saying, `we're in it for the long haul,''' robertson said in an interview
in many places in the south, a minority republican party, eager for new blood, hungrily accommodated the influx of robertson people. ideologically, the newcomers and the old timers think alike; differences are more likely to be over style and personality
but that doesn't rule out frictions
they don't want participation, they want domination,'' grumbled state legislator harry r. ``bob'' purkey, who was ousted in 1986 as district republican chairman by a religious school principal in robertson's back yard, virginia beach, va
this year, at a district convention in newport news, va., long-time party stalwarts also were thrown out by robertson supporters
said anne kincaid, head of the virginia chapter of americans for robertson: ``we will do whatever it takes, ethically and within the rules, to get pat nominated.''
terry wade, chief of staff at the republican national committee in washington, said the new blood energizes the party
he called the robertson challenges a weak echo of the party takeover by barry goldwater's people in 1964. nor does it have anything like the magnitude of ronald reagan's putsch in many places in 1976 which led to his winning the nomination four years later
if our party were to become perceived as a single issue party or one having a very narrow viewpoint of america, that would be a problem, but i don't see that happening,'' wade said
there's always going to be some dissatisfaction and disruption when new people move in, but, hey, if we're going to become the majority party, we have to grow.''
checks by associated press reporters around the country found instances in which robertson forces fit right in _ and instances in which they didn't
there were old guard complaints that the robertson people are not interested in day-to-day party work and complaints from robertson people that the regulars preferred the comforts of clubbiness to winning elections
in michigan, a year and a half of chaotic battle, in and out of court, battered the republican party and put robertson forces in the majority in the state central committee. the likely result: competing bush and robertson delegations demanding to be seated at the national convention in new orleans in august, touching off a nasty credentials fight pitting bush forces against robertson
in hawaii, where robertson swept party caucuses feb. 4, gop chairman howard chong was ousted by a robertson supporter, losing his chance to attend the party's state convention as a delegate
chong first pledged to unite the warring factions, but later called a news conference to denounce the ``lies and innuendoes'' of robertson people and announced: ``frankly speaking, i have had enough.''
under the rules, bush won all 48 delegates in georgia, but when the state's delegates are selected as many as half are expected to go robertson people. they will be bound to bush for two ballots at the national convention, but free to vote with robertson on platform issues, credentials challenges and party rules
it is our aim to see that the party is broadened,'' said attorney don johnson of marietta, ga., a robertson supporter. ``...we're either going to broaden it with them or broaden it over them.''
bob bell, former state gop chairman, said, however: ``nothing in their numbers would lead me to believe this group can take over the party.''
robertson supporters dominated many precinct meetings and county conventions in oklahoma. one likely result, says matt seward, bush's state director: the oklahomans will support a plank denouncing the arms control treaty coming before the senate for ratification even though bush vigorously supports it
bush swept the 111 national delegates available from his adopted state of texas, but robertson forces, based on their showings in county conventions in march, think they have a chance to elect their own candidate as state gop chairman in houston in june. some texas counties will send delegations that are 100 percent robertson people
if the new robertson-type people will filter out some of the biblical language and keep their principles, they can realize more of their goals,'' commented retiring texas chairman george strake, a former democrat who converted to republicanism in 1961 ``because i thought republicans were firmer against communism.''
nevada, reflecting the outcome of february's caucuses, will send a pro-robertson delegation to the national convention. robertson's state director, steve wark, said the nevadans will be in no mood to jump aboard a bush bandwagon. such a conciliatory move, he said, would be ``poisonous.''
in washington state, the only super tuesday state that went for robertson, gop executive director john meyers was asked if he saw the robertson crowd as heirs to the reagan revolution. he replied: ``i see it as an extension of the goldwater revolution.'' anti-gay, anti-united nations, pro-school prayer conservatives have run the state party for decades, even though sen. dan evans, r-wash., is characterized as moderate-to-liberal
in maine, when robertson people threatened to take over in february, forces supporting bush and bob dole buried their differences to vote them down and prevent the selection of a pro-robertson delegation to new orleans
robertson coordinator john solberg cried foul. ``the bush and dole campaigns are attempting to keep the majority silent in the democratic process,'' he complained. gov. john r. mckernan jr., a bush man, brushed off the charge. ``this is not fun and games,'' he said. ``we're talking about the next president of the united states.''
kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co., a leveraged buyout specialist, is seeking federal permission to buy up to 15 percent of texaco inc.'s stock
in announcing the move, the investment firm also said tuesday it had already acquired 11.95 million texaco shares, or about 4.9 percent of texaco's roughly 242 million outstanding shares
the move added fuel to growing market anticipation that a takeover attempt of the nation's third largest oil company is only a matter of time
federated department stores inc., seeking to end a 2-month-old takeover war, plans to weigh final offers by the two companies that want to buy the retailer
one of its suitors, campeau corp., immediately objected tuesday to the guidelines for choosing a winner, but a federal judge rebuffed its attempt to block federated's plan. the deadline for bids is wednesday
in a letter to campeau and r.h. macy &amp; co. inc., federated said its board would choose the ``best proposal'' from the final purchase offers. campeau and macy have each offered to buy federated for more than $6 billion
odyssey partners has sweetened its tender offer for j.p. stevens &amp; co. to $1.14 billion, but analysts predicted further bidding in the battle for the textile giant
west point-pepperell inc., which has made a $1.1 billion bid for stevens, is expected to compete fiercely for the crown jewels _ three state-of-the-art factories and licenses for hot designer labels that lure consumers around the world to stevens' quality sheets and towels
odyssey, a new york investment firm, said tuesday it would pay $64 for each of stevens' 17.8 million outstanding shares, up from the $61.50-a-share tender offer stevens' management accepted earlier this month
roper corp.'s board of directors have changed sides in the takeover fight for the appliance manufacturer, and are backing a bid from general electric co. instead of whirlpool corp
roper's board determined that ge's $508 million tender offer was clearly superior to whirlpool's $470 million one, the company said tuesday in withdrawing a recommendation of whirlpool made march 18
the government's chief economic forecasting gauge posted a 0.9 percent increase in february in a performance which analysts said should lay to rest fears of a 1988 recession
the 0.9 percent rise reported tuesday in the commerce department's index of leading indicators was the biggest advance since a 1 percent rise last june
the index had fallen in three of the past four months, including declines of 0.1 percent in october, 1.2 percent in november and 1.1 percent in january
new home sales broke a three-month slide by jumping 20.3 percent in february, the government says
the commerce department said tuesday that new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 628,000 units. it was the first monthly increase since a 1.4 percent rise in october, but it still left sales 14.9 percent below where they were a year ago
congress unconstitutionally singled out publisher rupert murdoch by prohibiting his continued ownership of newspapers and television stations in the same city, an appeals court says
a recently enacted provision barring the federal communications commission from extending temporary waivers from its cross-ownership rule is unconstitutional because it ``strikes at murdoch with the precision of a laser beam'' without a legitimate purpose, the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington ruled tuesday in a 2-1 opinion
murdoch recently sold the new york post so he could keep a new york television station in compliance with the law, and faces a similar choice in boston
cbs inc. has offered significantly increased pension benefits to about 11 percent of its employees if they elect to retire within the next four months
the option was offered tuesday to about 800 of the company's 7,000 workers and was described as part of the company's continuing effort to streamline operations to be competitive
american builders will be allowed to bid on japanese construction projects under a new agreement aimed at ending a trade dispute that has soured relations between the two countries
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter told a joint news conference tuesday he was pleased that the prolonged, on-and-ff talks had reached ``a fruitful conclusion,'' proving that the two countries through negotiations are able ``to manage difficult bilateral trade disputes.''
house and senate trade bill writers have defied president reagan's veto threat by approving a plan to require companies to give employees advance notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs
the action tuesday came amid new administration warnings that putting the provision in the final package could doom the 1,000-page trade bill designed to sharpen the u.s. edge in global markets
labor secretary ann mclaughlin said she hoped ``congressional leaders will find a way to drop this provision in these last days of the conference. if not, i have no recourse but to recommend a veto.''
eastern airlines has been ordered to stop the training of non-union pilots aboard its aircraft by a cargo carrier that was hired to help the company prepare for a possible strike this spring
u.s. district judge barrington d. parker granted a preliminary injunction tuesday sought by the air line pilots association to prevent eastern from leasing as many as five of its aircraft to orion lift services inc. to train 350 to 400 non-union pilots in case of a strike
the stock market shook off its recent slump and moved broadly higher tuesday as the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks climbed 18.57 to 1,998.34
the dollar moved higher in foreign exchange trading and gold prices rose
bond prices rebounded, and interest rates backed off two-month highs
platinum prices surged, but energy prices, grain and soybeans finished mixed
profit-taking by futures investors has snapped a four-day rally in oil prices
on the new york mercantile exchange tuesday, contracts for may delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude oil, settled at $16.98 per 42-gallon barrel, down 12 cents from monday's close. all other contract months also lost 12 cents a barrel
among refined oil products, the april contract for wholesale heating oil edged down 0.02 cent a gallon to 48.15 cents. unleaded gasoline for april rose, on the other hand, by 0.24 cent a gallon to 48.26 cents
analysts noted that the decline was moderate and prices moved within narrow trading ranges. the selling was led by oil companies, they said
prices are ``still showing a fair amount of resiliency,'' said john azarow, an oil futures trader for shearson lehman hutton inc
the recent strength stems from hopes that the pricing committee of the 13-nation organization of petroleum exporting countries will achieve an agreement to prop up prices, analysts say. prices have risen in eight of the last 11 trading sessions on the mercantile exchange
the opec pricing panel has announced it will hold a meeting in vienna, austria, starting april 9. the five pricing committee members are saudi arabia, nigeria, indonesia, algeria and venezuela
on the negative side, middle east economic survey, an oil industry newsletter, said some observers believe opec production has risen to about 18 million barrels a day
the newsletter said demand for opec crude, even taking into account some stockpiling, is unlikely to top 17 million barrels a day
as texaco inc. prepares to emerge from bankruptcy court protection next month, a welcoming party of takeover specialists continues to grow outside the oil giant's door
kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co., which has carried out some of the largest leveraged buyouts in u.s. history, said tuesday it is seeking federal permission to buy up to 15 percent of texaco inc.'s stock
the investment banking firm, often a management ally in its deals, said it had already acquired 11.95 million texaco shares, or about 4.9 percent of texaco's roughly 242 million outstanding shares
in filing to enlarge that stake, kohlberg kravis would join financiers carl c. icahn and t. boone pickens in announcing interest or taking substantial stakes in the nation's third-largest oil company
getty petroleum co., a product of texaco's ill-fated 1984 acquisition of getty oil co., has also filed for the same federal permission to up its stake in texaco
industry analysts viewed the latest development as another indication of the stiff challenge that texaco's management will face as it attempts to hang on to control over the company while conducting an orderly reorganization beginning next month
big shark, little shark, they all bite,'' observed frank p. knuettel, who tracks oil companies at prudential bache securities
for its part, texaco took the high road in its response
kohlberg kravis roberts has in past situations demonstrated an ability to be a constructive shareholder, which recognizes the importance of building value for the long term. we have no indication that their intentions with texaco are any different,'' the company said in a statement from its white plains, n.y., headquarters
we are hopeful that (it) will play a constructive role as texaco pursues prompt and aggressives steps to restructure the company and maximize total value and return for all our shareholders.''
investors responded enthusiastically to kohlberg kravis's announcement. in nationwide trading of new york stock exchange-listed issues, texaco jumped $3.25 a share to $48
kohlberg kravis said it had purchased its shares ``some months ago in the open market.'' ruth pachman, of the public relations firm kekst and co., which was representing the firm, said there would be no further comment
but a source close to the investment company said the filing would permit it to ``initiate discussions'' with texaco's management. the source would not elaborate
kohlberg kravis is a leader in leveraged buyouts, in which investors pay off the debt from a corporate takeover with the cash flow of the target company or by selling some or all of its assets
its $6.1 billion buyout of beatrice cos., completed in april 1986, was the largest leveraged buyout ever carried out in this country. seven months later, the firm bought safeway stores for about $4.2 billion
texaco last week received u.s. bankruptcy court permission to emerge from chapter 11 protection from its creditors with a financial reorganization plan that will become official on april 7
as part of that plan it has said it will sell at least $3 billion in assets
but analysts, who estimate the company to be worth between $50 and $60 per share, if it were broken up and sold off in pieces, have been expecting some outside move to accelerate those sales to raise the shares' value
icahn _ texaco's largest shareholder with 14.8 percent of its shares _ has been aggressively critical of texaco's management and has been widely expected to lead the charge on the company
on tuesday, he said he was ``surprised but also pleased'' to learn of the kohlberg kravis move
icahn has promised to field a slate of five candidates _ including himself _ for five board seats up for election at the company's annual meeting this spring, if texaco does not put itself up for sale. texaco officials have vowed repeatedly not to do that
pickens has received federal regulatory permission to buy up to 15 percent of texaco's shares. he has said he would support the icahn slate. on tuesday, however, david bachelder, president of pickens' mesa limited partnership would not say how many texaco shares pickens has actually accumulated
getty petroleum co., an independent marketer of petroleum products, has made a similar filing, claiming, however, that it is ``for investment only.''
philip l. dodge, an analyst at nomura securities international inc., said that ``the remaining question is whether the texaco management remains in charge of the company.''
alluding to the growing pressure on texaco, he suggested that ``provisions could be made'' for its management to participate in a leveraged buyout
i don't think they'd do it with much appetite, but (they would) if they saw it as the lesser of two evils,'' he added
cbs inc. says its special offer of increased pension benefits to about 11 percent of its employees who agree to retire within four months would help it slim down and compete in the tough broadcasting business
but one securities analyst said such offers have typically cost companies some of their better workers and could hurt cbs in the long run
these things have tended to give the best people a reason to leave and the worst people a reason not to,'' said alan gottesman, who follows media companies for the investment firm l.f. rothschild &amp; co
on wall street, cbs rose 62{ cents a share to $158.75 in trading on the new york stock exchange
cbs disclosed tuesday that it was offering the option to about 800 of the company's 7,000 workers and was described as part of the company's continuing effort to streamline operations to be competitive
a company spokeswoman, alice henderson, said the company had set no goal for how many people it hoped would take advantage of the program
the program is completely voluntary and eligible employees have until july 1 to make their decision on this offer,'' cbs said in a memo to the workers who are involved. retirement must occur no later than july 29
since laurence a. tisch took over as chief executive in the fall of 1986, cbs has sold its records, magazines and book publishing units, leaving it with a core business of broadcasting and about $3 billion in cash
but analysts say the cbs television network has been unprofitable and is likely to end the current season in last place in prime-time audience ratings, a development that could depress its advertising revenue
the special retirement program is available to cbs employees 55 years of age and older who have at least 10 years of pension vesting credit
those who accept the offer would get pension benefits calculated as if the employee were five years older and had completed an additional five years of service
as we all understand, cbs is still in the process of examining ways in which we can further streamline our operations to ensure our ability to be competitive in an increasingly competitive market,'' the memo said
we hope that the availability of this very attractive voluntary retirement option will assist us in reaching this objective,'' it said
the company offered a similar early retirement incentive plan in 1985, and a cbs source who asked not to be identified said about 500 people took advantage of it
the source said the latest plan is viewed by cbs management as a less painful way to make staff reductions than by firings
j. kendrick noble, the media analyst for the investment firm painewebber, said the offer was a cost-cutting move that reflected the corporate restructuring and the television network's dismal ratings performance
it's not that this company is fat or anything, but it is under more pressure than others to reduce costs,'' he said
rumors have circulated _ and have been denied repeatedly by cbs _ that tisch may be planning to sell the television network while holding on to its radio and television stations. rothschild's gottesman said the retirement incentive is ``consistent with the liquidation theory.''
but john reidy, a media analyst for the investment firm drexel burnham lambert inc., said he found nothing unusual about the early retirement offer
tisch felt he could do things with less people ... he wants to get an improved return on his investment. i don't see anything cosmic in any of this,'' he said
older white-collar workers face employer attitudes ranging from accommodating to hostile, and a company's financial health plays a part, a university of michigan study shows
corporations with money problems are most likely to be antagonistic toward older workers, according to the study of 25 fortune 500 companies by barbara hirshorn
she said her interviews at the 25 companies indicated factors such as the state of the economy and the industry, corporate personality, corporate leadership and organizational structure shaped company attitudes
the study also indicated corporate attitudes can change, said hirshorn, a research fellow at the university's population studies center
companies participating in the study were guaranteed confidentiality
hirshorn said attitudes toward older workers could be categorized as:
_pro-active. these companies dealt most effectively with older workers, offering more than one possible career ladder, maintaining options for the company and for workers of all ages, encouraging lateral career changes and reassigning workers to relieve stress and boredom
_performance-focused. such companies tried to ignore age and apply a reliable evaluation system to all employees. hirshorn said this tended to benefit older employees over younger ones who had to be considered more in terms of their potential
_at cross-purposes. at these companies, managers might express high regard and design some effective policies for older workers, but retain other policies that work against them. limited opportunities for promotion or lateral moves and huge, sweetened early retirement programs were examples
hirshorn said some retailers have policies at cross-purposes, voicing pride in being non-discriminatory but at the same time assuming older employees will burn out because the business is stressful and failing to offer them new opportunities
_positive means-negative ends. these were companies where coordinated planning efforts were subverted to get rid of older workers. hirshorn said such actions were often the result of new stresses from inside or outside the organization
_actively antagonistic. in a few companies, hostility showed up in a variety of policies. ``i came across one insurance company where age bias ran deeply throughout the ranks,'' hirshorn said. ``those who refused to relocate were fired, and since so few employees over 55 were promoted, many older workers left.''
some companies refused to retrain older workers, citing poor return on investment, though they did not raise the issue when retraining workers in their 30s who are more likely to leave for new jobs, she said
hirshorn said she will study 10 of the 25 companies to determine how they change or maintain their policies in reaction to external and internal stresses over time
the dollar rose against most major currencies in sluggish european trading this morning as volume tapered off before the easter break. gold prices eased
dealers predicted volume would remain thin through good friday and the dollar would likely trade around its present levels until after the easter weekend
the bank of japan intervened for the second straight day to support the dollar, but traders in frankfurt said the market reacted mildly because the amount of dollars purchased by japan's central bank was apparently small
traders said, however, the intervention served its purpose by reviving market fears of concerted central bank intervention
there are a lot of traders around who want to sell dollars but are afraid to do so,'' said a dealer at a major west german bank in frankfurt
traders said the dollar gained some support from recent statistics that indicate the u.s. economy is robust
the underlying sentiment is still certainly bearish on the dollar, but not aggressively so,'' said one trader with a major european commercial bank in milan
in tokyo, where trading ends before europe's business day begins, the dollar rose 1.06 yen to a closing 125.43 japanese yen. later, in london, it fell back to 125.28 yen
other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late tuesday's rates, included: 1.6705 west german marks, up from 1.6610; 1.3790 swiss francs, up from 1.3735; 5.6587 french francs, up from 5.6280; 1.8764 dutch guilders, up from 1.8690; 1,236.50 italian lire, up from 1,232.50; 1.2362 canadian dollars, down from 1.2363
in london, the dollar rose against the british pound. it cost $1.8615 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8705 late tuesday
gold opened in london at a bid price of $454.50 a troy ounce and at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $454.00. both were down from tuesday's late bid of $454.75
in zurich, the bid price was $454.00, down from $455.00 late tuesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold fell $1.09 to close at a bid of $455.79
silver bullion eased in london to a bid price of $6.675 a troy ounce, down from $6.69 late tuesday
gains on overseas markets helped boost the dollar in tokyo today, while the stock market's key index closed at a post-crash high
trading on the foreign exchange market was quiet, with many corporate customers staying on the sidelines until the end of japan's fiscal year on thursday, dealers said
the dollar opened at 125.75 yen, up 1.38 yen from tuesday's close of 124.37 yen. it began edging down in the afternoon and ended trading at 125.43 yen, up 1.06 yen. the u.s. currency ranged between 125.40 and 125.78 yen, with spot volume totaling $5.3 billion
the gain came after the dollar had lost a total of 2.78 yen over four trading days
the tokyo stock exchange enjoyed its third consecutive day of healthy gains in heavy trading. the 225-stock nikkei average rose 366.89 points, or 1.41 percent, ending the day at 26,319.98
it was the first time the key index had closed above the 26,000-level since the october market crash. the closing was less than 327 points from the index's all-time closing high of 26,646.43
traders said stock prices were boosted by the stronger dollar, gains on the new york and london markets on tuesday, and typical enthusiasm marking the start of the new japanese fiscal year
sentiment is very positive. we might see a new historical high this week, as long as new york (wall street) and the yen behave,'' a trader said
on the foreign exchange market, traders said many participants continued to cover dollar-short positions as they had on tuesday, when the dollar temporarily touched 123.87 yen, its lowest level since the first week of january
they attributed the u.s. currency's higher opening today to overnight gains on overseas markets and unconfirmed reports of greater intervention in support of the dollar by the u.s. federal reserve
also adding to the u.s. currency's strength was a denial today by japanese insurance companies that they were planning to begin dumping dollars after the start of the new fiscal year
rumors had been circulating that the companies, a major influence in currency markets, would discontinue their recent support for the dollar, said to have been aimed at defending the value of their holdings for accounting purposes
but many analysts said bullish sentiments toward the yen remain in the market because of healthly japanese economic fundamentals
prices on the london stock exchange were up slightly wednesday amid little buying interest
the financial times-stock exchange 100-stock index was up 1.7 points, or 0.1 percent, at 1,766.8 at midday. the index was up more than 10 points in earlier trading
solid gains in tokyo and new york overnight gave london a modestly bullish start. but the london market failed to sustain a recovery begun tuesday
traders reiterated that little would happen regardless of enthusiasm elsewhere ahead of the easter holiday and thursday's end to the british fiscal year
consumer prices in the 12-nation european economic community rose 0.3 percent in february from january and 3 percent from the year-earlier month, the eec reported
the common market's 3 percent year-on-year inflation rate in february remained unchanged from january, eurostat, the eec statistical office, said wednesday. that compares with inflation rates of 0.9 percent in japan and 3.9 percent in the united states
the 0.3 percent february rate continues the trend of moderate price increases established at the beginning of 1987, eurostat said
it said inflation was modest in all eec countries except portugal and denmark, which recorded monthly increases of 1.4 percent and 0.8 percent, respectively
a group of japanese life insurance companies have denied rumors that they plan to sell off u.s. dollars after april 1, a move that would send the currency into a tailspin
a new accounting law requiring life insurance companies to report currency losses of 15 percent or more when the current fiscal year ends march 31 has sparked speculation that the companies would try to support the dollar at an artificially high level and then retreat from u.s. financial markets soon after the close of the fiscal year
large-scale dollar selling here would push the u.s. currency lower. fears that the japanese might dump dollars has caused jitters in currency markets worldwide, with some traders selling the u.s. currency as a hedge against more widespread dollar sales
but a statement issued tuesday by yasuyuki wakahara, chairman of the japan life insurers association, called such speculation ``absolutely groundless.'' he noted that stable exchange rates are vital to japanese life insurance companies, which often invest in currencies other than the yen
this association hopes more than anyone else for a stable yen-dollar exchange rate,'' the statement said
tatsuo nakata, an association executive, told reporters at a news conference that dollar selling by the insurance companies would be like ``strangling yourselves.''
i think it's prudent to take the statement at face value,'' said david gerstenhaber, senior economist with morgan stanley &amp; co. in tokyo, who said he would be surprised if the life insurance companies pulled out of dollar-denominated investments in april
they have so much paper, that the value of what's left would be lowered by the impact of small sales,'' gerstenhaber said
life insurance companies were given some leeway on the 15 percent rule when the japanese government decided to allow the closing dollar rate for fiscal 1987 to be the average closing in tokyo for all of march, not the daily closing on march 31, as some analysts believed
the ministry of finance has allowed companies to use the month's average in order to alleviate strain from the crash in october, so people now are back above water,'' said bruce babcock of prudential-bache securities inc
in its statement, the life insurers association also criticized what it called growing instability caused by speculation in the market, an indirect reference to the weakness earlier this week of the dollar, which traded briefly tuesday below the 124-yen level, a three-month low. it rebounded wednesday to close in tokyo at 125.43 yen. trading</head>
the philadelphia stock exchange is expanding its night session trading list with the addition of futures and options on the british pound and the swiss franc
the exchange announced tuesday it will open trading in the new currencies, april 14
night trading at the stock exchange began sept. 16 with transactions in american and european-style options on australian dollars, deutsche marks and japanese yen. it averages about 5,000 contracts a night
futures in all five currencies also will be offered by the philadelphia board of trade, a subsidiary of the exchange
the night trading session, which runs from 7 p.m. to 11 p.m. est sunday through thursday. the daytime session runs monday through friday from 8 a.m. to 2:30 p.m
options are traded on the night currencies plus canadian dollars, french francs and european currency units
publisher rupert murdoch could still have trouble obtaining a government extension allowing him to keep both his newspaper and television station in boston, because both properties are making money
the possibility of an extension was opened tuesday by a federal appeals court. the panel ruled that congress unconstitutionally singled out murdoch when it barred the federal communications commission from extending temporary waivers of a rule forbidding common ownership of newspapers and tv stations in the same city
under existing fcc cross-owership rules, murdoch would have to show that either the boston herald or wfxt-tv is financially distressed. however, both properties are making money
unless the commission were to make some tremendous change in the criteria for granting a waiver, he doesn't qualify and we will oppose it,'' said andrew schwartzman, executive director of media access project, a washington, d.c.-based public interest law firm
diane killory, fcc general counsel, said temporary waivers are granted to give the owner of a newspaper-tv combination time to sell one of the properties for a fair price and avoid forcing a distress sale
if someone were willing to pay fair market value, it would be tough to argue it would be a distress sale, and that's the criteria we use when a temporary waiver is justified,'' she said
for a permanent waiver, an owner must show that common ownership was necessary to keep both the newspaper and tv station afloat financially, she said
lawrence kessler, general counsel for murdoch's news america publishing inc., acknowledged that the herald could survive without the tv station's revenues, but he said the company will argue that the issue is fairness
the hardship would be if we were forced to dispose of another asset and then the fcc modified the rule (to allow common ownership), that would be a hardship in and of itself,'' he said
kessler noted fcc precedents for granting further time for murdoch. the commission last year granted capital cities-abc inc. and general electric co. waivers of orders to sell radio stations while it decides whether to eliminate the cross-ownership rule barring common ownership of radio and tv stations in the same city
murdoch received temporary waivers from the fcc's cross-ownership rule after he bought the boston tv station and new york station wnyw-tv in 1986. he was given until march 6 to sell either wnyw or the new york post, and june 30 to sell wfxt or the boston herald
murdoch had been widely expected to request extensions of his waivers, but sens. ernest hollings, d-s.c., and edward kennedy, d-mass., cut short that option. late last year, they slipped through congress a measure prohibiting the fcc from extending any outstanding waivers. the measure also forbids the agency from considering any changes in the rule
in a 2-1 decision tuesday, the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington ruled that the law is unconstitutional because it targeted a specific individual for no legitimate purpose
though the ruling opens the possibility that murdoch could keep both boston properties at least temporarily, it won't affect the new york post, since he sold the newspaper earlier this month for $37 million to real estate developer peter kalikow
murdoch and others had said the ban by congress was an attempt to silence his newspapers' criticism of kennedy. kennedy and hollings, however, said they were merely trying to preserve the cross-ownership rules and force murdoch to comply with them
the court did not address the section of the provision that prevents the fcc from considering whether the cross-ownership rule should be abolished. therefore, that prohibition remains in effect until oct. 1, when the authority under the spending bill to which the measure was attached expires
kessler said murdoch will ask the fcc to extend its waiver for six months after the fcc makes a final decision on its cross-ownership rule
congress could forestall such a decision by continuing to prohibit the fcc from considering the issue
whether congress would do that would depend on ``many factors, including whether the commission grants murdoch a waiver,'' said tom cohen, a staff attorney for the senate commerce subcommittee on communications
the chairman of american stores co. warned lucky stores inc. against making a ``defensive acqusition'' that would thwart american's $1.74 billion tender offer for the grocery store company
in a letter to lucky's board of directors tuesday, american stores chairman l.s. skaggs said there have been ``various reports'' that lucky may be considering an acquisition that could interfere with his company's bid
american launched a $45-a-share tender offer for the dublin, calif.-based company on monday and said it was prepared to increase the offer to $50 a share, or about $1.93 billion, if a friendly deal can be worked out
in a brief statement issued tuesday, lucky acknowledged that it is reviewing both proposals. the company has urged shareholders not to tender until its directors make a recommendation
skaggs warned in his letter that any attempt by lucky to ``frustrate the choice given to your shareholders through a defensive acquisition'' would affect american's willingness to increase its tender offer to $50 a share
he also reiterated that american would consider divesting stores in order to mitigate any antitrust concerns that may exist
the combination of american, the nation's third-largest grocery retailer with 1,700 stores and annual sales of $15 billion, and lucky, the sixth-largest with 480 stores and sales of $7 billion, could produce the biggest grocery retailer in the nation, analysts say
documents filed monday at the security and exchange commission hinted that american may be positioning itself for a hostile takeover of lucky, which resisted such an effort from takeover specialist asher edelman 16 months ago. in return for edelman dropping the effort, lucky agreed to pay his $2.8 million in legal bills
american's sec documents include a copy of the lawsuit the company filed friday in delaware, which alleges lucky and its executive officers have breached their fiduciary duties by ``following a course of conduct directed towards entrenching themselves in control of lucky stores.''
as part of the defensive measures dating back to the edelman bid, lucky voted senior management lucrative ``golden parachute'' contracts and announced a restructuring plan that included changing the company's state of incorporation from california to delaware and a buy-back of 27 percent of its outstanding shares, the suit contends
the company has noted that its bylaws also contain a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover provision limiting the voting power of any shareholder who acquires more than 10 percent of lucky's stock
the stock market headed higher today, following through on tuesday's rally
