an offer by the long island power authority to purchase long island lighting co. for $971 million was termed ``ridiculous'' by some industry analysts
the state agency's decision to attempt a takeover was made after a study showed electric rates on long island would be 12 percent lower under a publicly-operated utility
lilco had not yet received the offer, made tuesday in a letter to lilco chairman william catacosinos and the utility's board of directors, said james lois, a lilco spokesman
should an offer come in we would seriously evaluate it, and inform our shareholders of the offer,'' lois said
the proposal contemplates that lipa would acquire through a friendly merger transaction all 111 million outstanding shares of lilco common stock at $8.75 per share
lilco stock was trading at $9 a share, down 12{ cents, in early new york stock exchange trading today
the proposal also contemplates that lipa would acquire all outstanding shares of lilco preferred stock
financing is expected to be provided through the sale of approximately $7.45 billion of long-term, tax-exempt bonds, officials said
it was not known if lipa's offer, which is open until april 15, would be considered at a previously scheduled lilco board meeting today
gary f. hovis, a utility analyst at argus research corp., called the offer ``somewhat funny or ridiculous.''
obviously, the board of directors of lilco won't even think about accepting this offer,'' he said
he said it was so far below the true value of the company that even the less sophisticated investors would quickly reject it if it were ever approved by the lilco board and sent to the 118,000 shareholders for a vote
that is a number that is well below what was generally expected,'' said analyst paul parshley at donaldson, lufkin &amp; jenrette securities inc. ``i would certainly expect the company would reject the bid and that would begin a bargaining process.''
he and other analysts said an offer was not likely to be seriously considered until it reaches at least $12 per share
lipa's nine-member board of trustees met for several hours in closed session tuesday before voting to attempt the takeover at what mack called the average trading price of lilco stock over the past 30 days
lipa is an independent state agency formed in january 1987 by gov. mario cuomo and the legislature to decide if a takeover of lilco would lower rates. lipa also is trying to prevent lilco's shoreham nuclear plant from operating
the $5.2 billion plant, one of the most expensive ever built, is currently licensed by the nuclear regulatory commission to operate at up to 5 percent of full power
lilco officials have continued to press for a full operating license for the plant, contending it is needed to meet the growing electric demands on long island
cuomo and local officials have argued against granting a full operating license to shoreham, saying long island could not be safely evacuated in the event of an accident at the plant, located on the island's north shore about 50 miles from manhattan
federal law requires that an approved evacuation plan be in place before a nuclear power plant can be granted a license
eastman kodak co. and fuqua industries inc., wasting no time after a favorable court decision, announced today they had merged their photofinishing operations
the new company, qualex inc., was formed on tuesday immediately after the u.s. circuit court of appeals in new orleans reversed a federal court injunction that had blocked the merger since feb. 22
qualex combines fuqua's photofinishing subsidiary, colorcraft corp., with kodak-owned laboratories, forming the country's largest wholesale photofinishing operation. it has 94 processing labs around the country
we've been delayed in doing this by the lawsuit so we wanted to get it done as soon as we could. our target date for having this merger completed had been feb. 1,'' said paul allen, a kodak spokesman
the company will be based in durham, n.c., the home of colorcraft. colorcraft's former chairman, d. carl hamill, will serve as chief executive officer
allen said the court of appeals granted permission for the merger to go ahead immediately, even though a lawsuit trying to prevent it is still being argued
the court noted that a merger can always be undone at a later date,'' allen said
a small wholesale photofinisher, phototron corp. of san bernardino, calif., filed the lawsuit to block the merger because phototron officials claimed it would create unfair competition in the market
a federal judge in fort worth, texas, where the lawsuit was filed, issued an injunction feb. 22 preventing the merger, but that decision was reversed tuesday in new orleans
that lawsuit is expected to continue, allen said
