most livestock and meat futures settled lower on tuesday
the government announced that the nation's economy grew a tiny 1.4 percent last year, recovering from a steep recession that had hobbled the economy in 1986
the office of president miguel de la madrid delivered late tuesday to the federal legislature its report on the state of the economy in 1987
the advances reached with the (government's economic) plan and its programs were substantial,'' it said
the report said non-oil exports soared 24 percent, giving the nation a surplus of $4.2 billion in the 1987 current account, which is the broadest measure of a country's trading position. mexico recorded a deficit of $1.3 billion in its current account in 1986
it said unemployment declined by 3.2 percent last year, according to its surveys of the nation's 16 major cities
private analysts estimate about 18 percent of the labor force of 25 million is out of work
the economy contracted at an inflation-adjusted 4.0 percent in 1986
the government previously had reported that inflation soared a record 159.2 percent last year. since '81</head>
maytag corp. said today it will suspend all production and some support operations for one week at its newton plant, the first such shutdown since november 1981
about 2,000 workers will be affected next week at the plant that manufactures washers, dryers, dishwashers and in-sink food waste disposers
very strong first-quarter merchandising programming resulted in dealers buying ahead and the short-term correction is needed to bring factory and dealer inventories back into line,'' the company said in its announcement
spokesman ron krajnovich said the merchandising program involved discounted sales to dealers as an incentive to buy maytag appliances
the company said the vast majority of the production employees affected will receive unemployment compensation and supplemental unemployment benefit payments during the period
it said production would resume april 11
maytag is coming off its best year ever, with a profit of $152.7 million on sales of $1.92 billion in 1987
but when the company released its annual report earlier this month, maytag chairman daniel j. krumm noted 1987 was the fourth consecutive record year for the appliance industry
the industry's growth cycle is mature, and i believe demand will relax slightly in 1988,'' krumm said at the time. but he also said he expected maytag to outperform the industry as a whole
stock prices showed some modest gains today, following through on tuesday's rally
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up 18.57 on tuesday, rose 3.15 to 2,001.49 by noontime today on wall street
gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 766 up, 530 down and 476 unchanged
analysts said the market's drop last week apparently attracted some buyers who had been waiting for a chance to get in on the rally in stock prices that began late last year
they also noted that the dollar had shown signs of steadying again in foreign exchange. that sparked a rebound in bond prices in tuesday's activity
wall streeters were generally pleased with the government's report tuesday that the index of leading economic indicators rose 0.9 percent in february
that was taken as a signal that the economy was neither weak nor dangerously strong
the market's advance tailed off as the session passed, however. brokers said traders seemed reluctant to expand their holdings with a long holiday weekend approaching
the market will be closed in observance of good friday
texaco rose ] to 48] on top of a 3\-point jump tuesday, when kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co. said it would seek regulatory clearance to buy as much as 15 percent of the company's stock
j.c. penney added 1[ to 48]. the company raised its quarterly dividend from 37 cents a share to 50 cents a share
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained .28 to 147.50. at the american stock exchange, the market value index was up 1.19 at 295.52
volume on the big board came to 74.81 million shares at noontime, against 72.98 million at the same point tuesday
the reagan administration's top trade official says that the u.s. tariffs on canadian plywood won't be lowered until the two countries have developed ``common standards'' that would allow american-manufactured plywood to be used north of the border
in a letter to oregon republican sen. bob packwood, u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said the administration will propose that u.s. and canadian experts from two forest research laboratories develop and draft construction standards for the use of plywood in both countries
under this scheme, reductions in the u.s. tariff on plywood and other panel products would not be phased in until we get a satisfactory solution to the technical trade problems,'' said yeutter
packwood told reporters he was optimistic that a joint-standard could be negotiated
this ought to solve our plywood problems with canada,'' packwood said
the proposed u.s.-canada free trade agreement calls for elimination of the 20 percent u.s. tariff on canadian plywood and the 15 percent tariff on american plywood over a 10-year period
but the treaty linked elimination of the tariffs to changes in the canadian construction codes
canadians have insisted that american plywood was not sturdy enough to withstand the harsher climate of canada, a claim the american plywood industry has said is unfounded
earlier this month, the canadian mortgage and housing commission (cmhc) refused to revise its building code that has essentially blocked imports of u.s. plywood
the government-controlled mortgage authority rejected the changes without even making a technical review of u.s.-manufactured plywood
northwest lawmakers, including packwood, were outraged
oregon is the leading plywood producing state and washington ranks no. 4. together, the two states produce about 40 percent of the plywood manufactured domestically
yeutter said that he was ``disappointed'' with the cmhc rejection
i believe that cmhc's action does not conform with provisions of the free trade agreement,'' yeutter wrote. ``my expectations of cmhc have not been met.''
yeutter said that after common standards were developed and implemented, ``then tariff reductions envisioned in the free trade agreement could take effect.''
packwood said that adoption of joint construction standards should ensure that u.s.-manufactured plywood will have access to canadian markets
plywood made in eugene, salem or vancouver, british columbia, will all be made to the same standard,'' said packwood
cash-rich companies have replaced corporate raiders of the bust-'em-up style on the merger trail, lassoing businesses that will increase their market share and make long-term economic sense
takeover activity, often of the hostile variety, has resumed with a new frenzy as initial jitters about the economy have subsided in the wake of october's stock market calamity
despite nagging fears that the new wave will further restrict competition in some industries and leave many businesses awash in debt, the urge to merge seems ever stronger among companies bent on raising their standing in the global marketplace
lured by battered stock prices, corporations are shedding their inhibitions about making overtures that are ``unsolicited,'' a euphemism for hostile bids
fears that taking the role of aggressor could tarnish the old corporate image are subsiding along with concerns about the disruptive effect an unwanted takeover might have on the target firm's work force _ from top management defections to a sense of alienation among the rank-and-file
lately, ``it's become respectable for quality corporate buyers to make unsolicited offers,'' said michael b. hoffman, co-director of mergers and acquisitions at smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
that general respectability is allowing people to come in and do something they haven't done in the past,'' he said
among the unsolicited offers is american store co.'s nearly $2 billion bid for lucky stores inc., a combination that would create the nation's biggest supermarket chain. elsewhere in the retail arena, campeau corp. and r.h. macy &amp; co. have both bid more than $6 billion for federated department stores inc
some companies are so intent to jump on the acquisition bandwagon, they're launching tender offers after a target company has signed an agreement with another suitor
general electric corp., which analysts are quick to note has never pursued an unfriendly deal, launched a $507 million tender offer for roper corp. after the appliance and lawn equipment maker agreed to be acquired by whirlpool corp
smithkline beckman corp. went after international clinical laboratories inc. to beef up its lab network even though the company already had agreed to be acquired by corning glass works
acquiring another company is a quicker and often cheaper way of broadening product lines and gaining market share. instead of building a factory from the foundation up over the course of several years, corporations can expand their distribution channels instantly by snapping up a competitor
even eastman kodak co.'s megapurchase of sterling drug inc. for $5.1 billion _ the largest completed deal so far this year _ is not a wild diversification move for the camera maker, some argue
large companies also are aiming to outgun their foreign counterparts
market share is being divided up _ and u.s. companies are consolidating to meet foreign competition coming in,'' said robert willard, managing director and head of mergers and acqusitions at prudential-bache securities inc
to the extent that companies are leading the effort as opposed to raiders, the latest wave ``is clearly healthier,'' said willard, who noted that the recent combinations not only ``make economic sense ... but probably at the end of the day there is less dislocation in terms of employees forming stronger economic units to be competitive on worldwide basis.''
but hoffman said it is ``definitely not clear that these are somehow better than the mergers of the past.'' it's difficult to argue whether campeau or macy would be an inherently better partner for federated, he said
still, an increasing percentage of transactions ``are not bust-up or junk-bond driven; they appear to be driven by synergistic ideals,'' said stephen fraidin, a partner of fried, frank, harris, shriver &amp; jacobson, a leading mergers-and-acquisition law firm
changes in tax laws have made the breaking up of companies not as attractive for raiders who must sell off parts of targets just to finance the actual acquisition
corporations have an opportunity to display their natural advantage in winning deals _ namely, they have deep pockets and can borrow cheaper than raiders relegated to the high-yield but risky junk-bond markets
and there's no question that corporations are in a strong cash position right now. buoyed by a weaker dollar that has made american exports more attractive, corporations' after-tax profits shot up 8.4 percent in last year to $137.4 billion for the first increase since 1984, according to commerce department figures
while the number of takeover deals announced seems to have slowed, the dollar value has increased steadily. in december, 484 deals were announced for a total dollar value of $16.1 billion. but the 364 deals announced in february carried a combined price tag of $32.7 billion
experts say the pace will wear on. ``all the forces in place that have contributed to the first three months (of 1988 activity) we see as continuing into the forseeable future,'' said j. tomilson hill, co-head of mergers and acquisitons at shearson lehman hutton inc
banks are fully prepared to provide a substantial amount of credit, there's bridge financing from the investment banks,'' and while there are fewer bargains in terms of stock prices now than a few months ago, ``prices nevertheless are still on average below their highs'' he said
ironically, mergers are now providing some support for stocks as takeover issues dominate the play on an otherwise dull wall street
on the downside looms the specter of an economy constrained by too much debt and too little competition
in the concrete and construction materials business alone, three major takeover attempts are under way, two of which are being spearheaded by foreign firms. beazer plc of britain has made a bid for koppers co.; brierly investments ltd. of new zealand is seeking to acquire calmat co.; while moore mccormack resources inc. has rebuffed an offer from southdown inc
ultimately, the bill for such combinations will have to be paid
there's the danger of getting into a situation where companies are so highly leveraged that it becomes a question whether they can survive an economic downturn,'' said jay lorsch, a professor at harvard business school
some experts criticize restructuring in the face of a takeover as too short sighted. to fend off a hostile bidder, companies often take on debt to make themselves less attractive. or as an alternative defensive move, companies sell off assets that may be weak at the moment without considering their long-term potential
it's like the hong kong race track _ everybody's betting on the short term and not that the earnings of a company will rise'' over the long haul, lorsch said
in an office park in this seattle suburb, a staff of 92 people is kept busy answering questions like, ``when i'm in the legend of zelda, how do i find the tri-force in level seven underworld labyrinth?''
in most customer service departments, that would stop 'em cold
but for executives at the home office of nintendo of america inc., the 40,000 to 50,000 children who call each week with such arcane inquiries about nintendo's home video games are a reassuring sign their toy is still tops
a little over 18 months ago, nintendo, a 99-year-old japanese playing card manufacturer and maker of the popular arcade game ``donkey kong,'' jumped headlong into home video games, an american market most thought was stone dead
today, the wholly owned subsidiary of nintendo co. ltd. of japan claims to have captured 70 percent of a u.s. market that should hit $1.9 billion in 1988
for 1987, nintendo of america had sales of $750 million out of a $1.1 billion market. that helped push profits for nintendo ltd. to $172.8 million on sales of $987 million for fiscal year 1987, ending aug. 31, compared with profits of $113.1 million on sales of $829.5 million in fiscal 1986
without question they're the preeminent force in the video game industry,'' said rick anguilla, editor of toy &amp; hobby world, a trade publication that has ranked the nintendo entertainment system as the top-selling toy for the past six months
they learned from the mistakes that were made the first time around and they had the foresight to see that the american consumers were not the ones who stopped playing video games,'' anguilla said. ``it was more a case of american and japanese manufacturers putting so much bad product in the marketplace that it sort of ruined it for everybody.''
at the height of the video craze, $3 billion in games were sold in 1982, nintendo says. but by 1985 the fad appeared over, with sales just $100 million and manufacturers unloading $35 game cartridges for $5 or less
about that time, nintendo began test-marketing its entertainment system _ a small computer that played game cartridges, and two sets of control panels. add in a light gun and foot-high robot that would act out some games and the list price was $199.95
you really have to admire the nerve to walk into a lot of retailers in 1985 and ask if they wanted to buy a video game,'' anguilla said
but bill white, nintendo advertising and public relations director, said the product had been wildly successful in japan, selling more than 10 million units since 1983, with games in 30 percent of all japanese homes
we liked it right from the start,'' said michael goldstein, chief financial officer for the retailing giant toys r us. the more detailed and higher-quality games made consumers feel they were getting their money's worth, he said
if there's been a problem, goldstein said, it's been supply. ``when you have something that's hot, it sells out,'' he said
for last christmas, the game packages were reconfigured, eliminating the robot, and sold for around $100
white said that nearly four months later, nintendo still has trouble keeping up with demand. it shipped 3 million entertainment systems last year, and recently upped its 1988 forecast from 5 million to 7 million
steven eisenberg, leisure industry analyst for bear, stearns &amp; co. in new york, said he doubts such growth can be sustained. but he said the video game industry has re-established its stability and should see long-term gowth of 12 percent to 15 percent a year
competitors atari corp., with about 16 percent of the market, and tonka co.'s sega, with about 10 percent, may make some inroads, but are far from challenging nintendo's dominance, eisenberg said
what brought video games back from the dead, eisenberg said, were nintendo's elaborate graphics, sharp resolution and high-quality sound. also, notes anguilla, there's a factor toymakers call ``play value'' _ what laymen call ``fun.''
the old-style games often had plots as simple as eradicating space bugs flitting around the screen. but nintendo games are intricate. the top seller, a sword-and-sorcery yarn called ``the legend of zelda,'' leads players through 700 scenes in which they defeat wizards, solve mazes and eventually rescue the princess zelda _ a process that can take up to 90 hours, and then be played all over again
nintendo maintains strict control, awarding licenses to game makers to produce five new titles a year each. nintendo gets final say on content
among the 55 existing or planned titles are a souped-up version of ``donkey kong'' called ``super mario bros.;'' ``rad racer,'' a car-race game, ``ice hockey,'' and ``mike tyson's punch-out,'' a boxing game promoted by the heavyweight champ
howard phillips is nintendo's product analysis manager, in charge of approving the games. he's more widely known, however, as president of the fun club, a fan organization with more than 1 million on its magazine's mailing list
phillips says nintendo is looking at expanding beyond its initial target market of boys 8-15, with more adventure games and versions of the tv shows ``jeopardy'' and ``wheel of fortune'' that should appeal to adults
in japan, the nintendo box has been used to provide stock market quotes, home shopping and even to power a knitting machine, he said
phillips also oversees the phone bank of game counselors, who, he says, get asked the zelda and the tri-force question about 5,000 times a week
the answer? ``go to the tip of the nose and defeat all the wall masters and push all the blocks, and a secret passage will appear,'' he said
the kids will know all about that.''
while legions of wall streeters have headed for the unemployment lines since october's market crash, some high-rolling investment bankers, takeover lawyers and acquisition hand-holders have shifted into fifth gear
we've been intensely busy for a long time; now we are, perhaps, intensely busier,'' said stephen fraidin, a partner of fried, frank, harris, shriver &amp; jacobson, a new york law firm that handles takeovers
some of the more entrepreneurial members of this inner sanctum have shifted out of old-line establishments altogether to set up their own shops, otherwise known as ``boutiques.''
indeed, some of the hottest talk on wall street of late surrounded the string of defections from first boston corp.'s mergers and acquisitions department. superstars bruce wasserstein and joseph r. perella, who ran the highly successful operation, announced in february they were leaving to form their own firm, taking a score of staffers with them
first boston was wiped out in that department,'' one wall street insider said. wasserstein and perella took the 20 best people, ``and they are the business,'' he added
these boutiques are not merely high-class consulting firms. with huge pools of international money available from pension funds, insurance companies and the like, they have access to enough capital to spin their own deals
and boutiques are counting big players as clients. the blackstone group advised japan's bridgestone corp. on its proposed venture with firestone tire &amp; rubber co., while wasserstein, perella &amp; co. is counseling campeau corp. in its battle against r.h. macy &amp; co. for federated department stores inc
one senior mergers and acquisitions banker said boutiques have created ``a second force'' in an industry that has evolved into a veritable ``oligopoly.''
there are three firms among us that are capturing probably 80 percent of the takeover market,'' he said in reference to shearson lehman hutton inc., goldman, sachs &amp; co. and morgan stanley &amp; co
boutiques are vying hard for that remaining 20 percent
this banker predicted that the recent wave of takeover activity could push first-quarter profits to record heights at the three major houses
merger activity is carrying over to the results of the overall firm,'' he said
but that may be the very reason boutiques are popping up
since the m and a people are on top at the moment, they want it all for themselves and do not want to carry everybody else. so they start their own boutiques,'' said robert pirie, president of rothschild inc., which has advised sir james goldsmith, the anglo-french financier. worldwide; inserts 5 grafs after 11th graf, moreover there...' to explain layoffs and unbundling; subs 3rd graf from end to correct comtex sted contex; adds 1 graf to identify fnn ownership; also moving on general news wires</note>
united press international will continue as a 24-hour-a-day worldwide wire service and will reduce its staff and seek joint ventures with other companies, the firm's new owners said today
upi chairman earl w. brian and president paul steinle said they were committed to seeing the 81-year-old wire service, which is losing $2 million a month, survive into the 21st century
the upi officials, in a statement released at a news conference, said their new business plan calls for ``continuation of the company as a full-service, 24-hour-a-day, worldwide supplier of news and information.''
to accomplish these goals, upi will lay off as many as 150 staffers worldwide, but fewer than 100 of those will be from the editorial side, steinle said. ``at this time we do not anticipate further cutbacks,'' he said. to assist the departing staffers, upi will provide a benefits package and help them find new jobs
steinle said the wire service's operators, who took control of the company in february, had conducted a market survey based on interviews with 500 senior executives in the news industry
as a result we are making major changes in the way we design and deliver our products and are instituting procedures to ensure that we are constantly sensitive to what our customers want,'' he said
steinle said upi's development will start at the ``grass roots'' and will focus on strengthening state and regional reporting. he said the wire service also will stress technical reporting
this includes an increased emphasis on business and financial news and analysis and its effect on the consumer, plus more and better reporting in areas such as health, science, law and medicine,'' he said
many of the changes will be phased in over the next several months, but upi clients should see immediate improvements as a result of staff training programs to develop greater writing clarity and succinctness, the announcement said
the statement said the wire service expects to save $10 million in the first year through administrative cost controls. additional savings will come from pooling resources with other companies that offer joint venture potential for upi in the information industry
moreover, there will be ``a gradual unbundling of upi products'' over the next year, which will give the company an opportunity to reprice products and expand those sought by customers
brian said the people targeted for layoffs were notified personally today, and about 35 were offered early retirement. the staff reductions amount to 14 percent of upi's employees, he said
asked how upi hoped to improve coverage with fewer people, steinle said the staff will be ``not as large but more focused.''
for instance, he said, efforts are being made to improve productivity by reprogramming computers to perform routine functions, such as automatic pronouncers for broadcast copy
additionally, the spanish-language translation desk will be moved from washington to central or latin america, upi announced
brian said the unbundling of upi's products will allow customers to buy the services they want without having to purchase unwanted services. this type of unbundling, he said, should help upi sales with non-media clients, who are expected to make up more of the wire service's client base in the future
brian, the new chairman, said, ``i estimate approximately $15 million in permanent equity financing will be required by the time we have completed the second phase of the business plan.''
the first phase of the business plan, expected to take three to six months, is designed to stabilize the company. the second phase will redirect the company into new and expanded lines of business
all told, the two-year business plan should bring upi to profitability in two years, brian said
until equity financing is in place, bridge financing will be made available by wnw group inc. and infotechnology inc
brian is chairman of wnw, a media investment group formed to take control of upi, and infotechnology, a new york-based information technology and venture capital firm
we know how to operate companies within their means and we have links to other companies with significant future joint venture potential for upi in the information industry,'' brian said
as an example of joint-venture possibilities, brian cited a new electronic news and information product called dbc supernews, created by financial news network, data broadcasting corp. _ an fnn subsidiary _ and comtex scientific corp. dbc supernews allows anyone with a personal computer at over 28 million cable tv sites to receive real-time news on any subject gathered from upi and other major news sources by comtex
supernews will be available at very low cost because fnn can deliver it by satellite as part of its regular television signal
brian and infotechnology own about 20 percent of fnn
president reagan today urged congressional approval of his request for $365 million to begin construction of the superconducting super collider, saying the technology it represents is ``changing the way we live.''
i know that some people may question the practical applications of the superconducting super collider,'' the president said. ``the strange world of subatomic particles, they may think, will never be more than an arcane interest to a few highly specialized scientists.''
but the truth is the practical applications of this new technology are already changing the way we live,'' the president told a gathering of science students and others in the rose garden
every time someone turns on his desk computer, makes a phone call or plays a video game, he is plugging into that mysterious world of quantum physics,'' reagan said. ``the superconducting super collider is the doorway to that new world of quantum change.''
the superconducting super collider will investigate the origin and nature of matter by whirling beams of protons into each other at an energy 20 times greater than is now possible in a 53-mile-around underground tunnel
the students in the audience were part of a program established in 1985 that gives top students from each state an opportunituy to work for two weeks in the summer at national laboratories in the washington area
reagan approved construction of the collider, the world's largest energy particle accelerator, in january 1987. the department of energy asked for site proposals in april 1987, and 36 of the 43 proposals received were judged qualified
the national academy of sciences and the national academy of engineering selected eight as the best qualified. the sites were in arizona, colorado, illinois, michigan, new york, north carolina, tennessee and texas
secretary of energy john s. herrington is sheduled to recommend a preferred site in july and the final site is to be chosen in january after an environmental imnpact study
some scientists oppose the project, saying it would be too expensive and drain money from more desirable scientific projects
however, six nobel laureates, four of whom were present for the ceremony, wrote reagan that the project ``represents america's commitment to the pursuit of excellence in basic scientific research.''
although reagan spoke seriously of his dedication to the project, he opened his remarks with a joke about it
when i first heard about this place where things go round and round at great speeds and then crash into each other, i thought tney were talking about a presidential campaign,'' the president said
thursday is the last day to qualify for the big airlines' triple-mileage programs and travelers have been flocking to the skies to beat the deadline
this is their time to strike,'' said suzanne jensen, a spokeswoman for uniglobe travel (international) inc., a large travel agency franchiser based in richmond, british columbia
to drum up business in the slow winter months, the major airlines offered to triple all mileage credits accumulated by participants in frequent-flier programs this year _ if the member took at least one round-trip or two one-way flights on that carrier between by the end of the day thursday
the deadline, coupled with the approach of easter and school vacations, seems to have touched off a flying spree _ with many travelers taking short, relatively cheap flights in order to qualify for the bonus mileage
the rush has mainly caught up ordinary consumers rather than frequent business travelers, who qualified earlier in the year for triple credits
there may be some short hops out there being taken for qualifying trips,'' said alan loflin, a spokesman for pan am corp. ``we were extremely heavy this weekend all over the (pan am) system.''
he said traffic was especially thick on pan am's northeast corridor shuttle service and on pan am express _ both short-haul operations for the international carrier. pan am express serves about a dozen cities in the northeast and feeds into the airline's main hub in new york, while the shuttle links new york, washington and boston
uniglobe's jensen reported an especially big flurry of business in the west and midwest _ with a lot of western customers booking short trips from los angeles, for example, to las vegas, san francisco or san diego
launched at the start of the year by delta air lines, the triple-mileage marketing weapon was quickly embraced by other major carriers hoping to bolster business during the first quarter, which is traditionally the slowest for leisure travel
triple mileage is an extension of the popular frequent-flier programs, which reward passengers with free tickets or upgrades to first class after they have flown a set number of miles
we've had some very heavy passenger loads the past few days,'' said dan sheehy, a spokesman for united airlines. ``it looks like people are rushing to qualify for triple mileage.''
united, the nation's largest airline, saw passengers board its planes in record numbers last weekend on its 400 or so daily flights out of its hub at chicago's o'hare international airport, sheehy reported. boardings on friday, saturday and sunday ranged from around 45,000 to more than 49,000 a day _ compared with united's average rate of 30,000 to 35,000
second-ranked american airlines had a similar increase in passenger traffic last weekend, spokeswoman mary o'neill said
eastern airlines also has experienced a ``travel frenzy'' recently, spokeswoman paula musto said, citing the twin factors of easter and the triple-mileage deadline
observers said most major airlines are reaping the same last-minute windfall _ with one notable exception. delta, which started the triple-mileage competition, did not impose a deadline for eligibility, spokesman neil monroe said
delta's frequent-flier program, including the triple mileage feature, is also unique in that all tickets must be charged on an american express card
the japanese government hailed the u.s.-japan accord on access to japan's construction market, but japanese construction executives expressed wariness about the agreement wednesday
since this agreement came about when japanese firms are still barred from the u.s. public works market, i am dissatisfied,'' hajime sako, president of the japan federation of construction contractors, said in a statement
washington banned japanese companies from u.s. public works projects last year because of japan's restrictive policies
it is good that the two countries were able to reach an agreement,'' prime minister noboru takeshita told reporters
construction minister ihei ochi said he was satisfied that japan had done enough to help american companies take part in japanese construction projects, long seen as representing continued closure of japan's markets
japan will honor the agreement and with the cooperation of japan's construction industry, ``i hope things will go smoothly in the future,'' ochi said
japanese and u.s. negotiators agreed japan will encourage foreign participation in major public works projects financed by the japanese government and other projects carried out by japanese companies with funding from both the central and local governments
the united states had threatened to invoke a law calling for retaliation unless negotiations this week produced an accord allowing u.s. companies to bid on an equal footing with japanese firms for hundreds of millions of dollars of work in large public works projects in japan
such projects include airports and airport terminals _ particularly the planned kansai international airport in western japan _ plus conference halls, expressways and bridges
keizo obuchi, chief cabinet secretary and takeshita's top aide, told a press conference the successful conclusion of the washington talks was a victory over protectionism, and said he hoped the agreement will have a ``favorable influence'' over deliberations in the u.s. congress on various trade bills
on the tokyo stock exchange, construction company stocks were boosted by the progress of the talks and announcement of the accord, possibly because investors believed it would lead the united states to drop restrictions on them
since monday, shimizu construction surged 33 yen to 934 yen $7.42) per share, while taisei corp. rose 22 yen to 969 yen ($7.75) and kajima corp. jumped 40 yen to 1,550 yen ($12.40)
japanese construction executives, however, expressed caution
sako said he was happy japan has been able to prevent u.s. retaliation, but said it was unavoidable that japan had to compromise to bring about a resolution to the deadlock
teruzo yoshino, president of shimizu construction, thanked the government wednesday for reaching a conclusion without u.s. retaliation, but stopped short of endorsing the accord
from now, i hope the japanese industry discusses the issue fully ... to develop a policy,'' yoshino said in a statement
the european economic community charged the japan-u.s. agreement ignores other countries
the ec has repeatedly warned against bilateral deals on trade and public procurement and particularly against this tendency between japan and the u.s.,'' said michael lake, a counsellor at the ec delegation in tokyo
european firms have shown more practical interest than american firms in the kansai airport,'' he said. ``we do not regard any u.s.-japan deal as infringing on our rights to pursue our own interests in this market.''
a french firm's design was chosen for the kansai airport's terminal, and european firms are hoping to follow with actual construction contracts
contracting for future construction projects jumped 10 percent in february, recouping january's 8 percent decline, according to a report published thursday
the survey, by the f.w. dodge division of mcgraw-hill information systems co., estimated the annualized value of all newly started construction projects in february at $249.7 billion, the highest level since last october
while the february increase was paced by a 14 percent surge in nonresidential building, the construction information service said housing and public works also contributed to the advance
the gain in nonresidential construction was concentrated in commercial and industrial buildings, up 32 percent, while institutional construction projects declined 11 percent
f.w. dodge said its seasonally adjusted index of construction contracting rose to 159 in february from 145 in january, which was its lowest level in two years. the index is based on a level of 100 for 1982
because construction activity can be notoriously erratic during the winter months, february's welcome gain in contracting needs to be paired with january's sharp decline,'' said george a. christie, vice president and chief economist for f.w. dodge
taken together, he said, january and february showed the rate of new construction contracting to be 5 percent below the fourth quarter of last year, extending a gentle decline from the peak rate reached in the third quarter of 1987
contracting for residential buildings rose 9 percent in february to an annualized value of $120.2 billion, according to the report. it noted, however, that the improvement was limited to multi-family housing and hotels and motels, while the single-family sector showed little change
public works and utility construction in february was valued at $43.4 billion, up 3 percent from january but 5 percent below the average level in 1987
maxwell communication corp. plc, a group controlled by british publisher robert maxwell, said wednesday that its pre-tax profit more than doubled in 1987, boosted by strong gains in publishing, printing and from property sales
the company said its pre-tax profit for the year came to 166 million pounds, or $309 million, compared with 80.3 million pounds, or $149 million, in 1986
at the same time, maxwell said the company was close to acquiring an australian newspaper, the melbourne age, from australian media group john fairfax ltd
maxwell added that he expected to reach and agreement with fairfax on the acquisition in two weeks. the age is part of a package of properties, which include the british weekly the spectator, which fairfax is offering for sale
maxwell communication said its profit after taxes also more than doubled to 134.3 million pounds, or $250 million, from 64.4 million pounds, or $120 million
sales spurted 91 percent to 884.1 million pounds, or $1.64 billion, from 461.7 million pounds, or $859 million
the company didn't break out quarterly or half-year results. it isn't required to under british law
a new agriculture department analysis of last year's trade situation helps point the direction for u.s. farm exports in 1988 and beyond, if a year or two can be called the beginning of a trend
basically, the report showed that the value of agricltural exports in the 1988 calendar year rose, while imports of agricultural commodities declined. that resulted in a larger trade balance in favor of american farmers
the periodic report is called fatus, which stands for foreign agricultural trade of the united states. it was issued last week by the department's economic research service
a bit of background may be useful
one of the quirks of usda agencies that sometimes confuses as well as informs is the practice of compiling statistics for different time periods. there is the fiscal year, which begins each oct. 1, and the calender year, which commences on jan. 1
then there are crop years, which vary according to the commodity, and the marketing year, which is just as confusing and can include livestock as well as crops. international trade figures often are reported for years beginning on july 1
under most circumstances, the most popular usda farm trade figures are those for the fiscal year running fr     4.5  0   iowa         15    0       3    0      26    0    kans.        18    0      16    0       6    0    mich.        52    0      72    0      24    0    minn.         1    0       1    0       4
