stock prices turned downward today after an early advance faded
the dow jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points in early trading, was down 9.12 at 1,989.22 by 2 p.m. today on wall street
losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally of new york stock exchange-listed issues, with 610 up, 766 down and 508 unchanged
analysts noted that the dollar had shown signs of steadying in foreign exchange. that sparked a rebound in bond prices in tuesday's activity
wall streeters were generally pleased with the government's report tuesday that the index of leading economic indicators rose 0.9 percent in february
that was taken as a signal that the economy was neither weak nor dangerously strong
the market's advance tailed off as the session passed, however. brokers said traders seemed reluctant to expand their holdings with a long holiday weekend approaching
the market will be closed in observance of good friday, when the government is scheduled to report on the employment situation for march
technology stocks were notably weak. digital equipment fell 3\ to 102[; international business machines 1 to 104~, and apple computer 2 to 39 in the over-the-countyer market
texaco rose ] to 48] on top of a 3\-point jump tuesday, when kohlberg kravis roberts &amp; co. said it would seek regulatory clearance to buy as much as 15 percent of the company's stock
j.c. penney added 1 to 48\. the company raised its quarterly dividend from 37 cents a share to 50 cents a share
fur vault, traded on the american stock exchange, fell ] to 2\. the company reported sharply lower quarterly earnings and suspended its dividend
the nyse's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost .48 to 146.74. at the amex, the market value index was off .16 at 294.17
volume on the big board came to 111.28 million shares with two hours to go
hugh a. barker has announced plans to retire as chairman and chief executive officer of public service indiana early next year
barker, who made his announcement to psi officers and management staff wednesday morning, had informed the utility's board of directors of his intentions on march 16, said psi spokesman michael goss
barker, 62, has served as chief executive of psi, the state's largest utility, since 1977
goss said vice president darrell v. menscer would assume on an interim basis the utility's operating responsibilities, other than the implementation of a new holding company structure
psi currently is working under a four-year agreement that alllows the utility to increase rates and write off part of its loss on the marble hill nuclear power plant, which was canceled in 1984 after $2.7 billion was spent on its construction
the utility had been near default before the rate agreement was approved in march 1986 by state regulators, but creditors granted psi a reprieve after the agreement was negotiated
psi serves about 542,000 customers in 69 indiana counties
the british pound has jumped to its highest level in two years, boosted by a strong economy, britain's relatively high interest rates and prime minister margaret thatcher's unrelenting grip on inflation
sterling held relatively steady for 12 months and was uncapped when the conservative government decided earlier this month to ease central bank intervention and allow the pound to rise above a previous target against the west german mark
it is a currency renaissance,'' said keith skeoch, chief economist at the london investment firm james capel and co. ``what we're beginning to see is the transition of sterling from being one of the weaker brethren among the international currencies to one of the stronger.''
jonathan lopatin, vice president for foreign exchange dealing at goldman sachs &amp; co. in london, said, ``the authorities decided to allow sterling exchange rates to rise.''
the bank of england's index measuring the pound's trade-weighted value against 17 currencies finished at 77.7 on wednesday, unchanged from tuesday, when it rose 0.6 point to reach its highest level since closing at 78 on jan. 16, 1986
on wednesday, the pound rose to $1.8790 from $1.8705, and to 3.1225 west german marks from 3.1069 marks
in the past seven years, the pound has hit a low of $1.0470, in february 1985, and a high of $2.4525 in november 1980
until taking the rein off the pound this month, the government, through the bank of england's sale of pounds and purchase of west german marks, had closely guarded a rate of 3 marks. it also has controlled sterling by signaling changes in interest rates
but that ceiling was lifted because there was a great deal of market pressure pushing sterling up. at that rate, more people wanted to buy it than sell it,'' lopatin said
it certainly has been made clear in the eye of the foreign exchange market and investors that the government is more concerned about the threat of inflation than they are at holding the exchange rate at any particular level.''
mrs. thatcher's priority has been to control inflation, now running at an annual rate of 3.3 percent compared with a 18 percent in 1980
that means the government is less likely to cut interest rates further for fear of reigniting inflation
britain's high interest rates, compared with the rates of other major industrialized nations, make pound-denominated investments more attractive and create demand for sterling
the british commercial banks' base lending rate _ a benchmark interest rate _ stands at 8.5 percent
the strong economy, however, is the underlying factor pushing up the pound
britain's gross domestic product _ its total output of goods and services _ is expected to grow 3 percent in 1988, faster than any of its major trading partners except japan. that will be the economy's seventh consecutive year of expansion
other pro-pound factors are a fiscal budget surplus, the first in nearly 20 years, announced march 15, political stability and a conservative government
they all are the hallmarks of a basically hard currency,'' skeoch said
the trade deficit is forecast to widen sharply with the strong currency, which can hurt exports and encourage imports
on tuesday, the pound also was boosted by rumors that chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson had resigned, even though the treasury issued a denial, and by a later statement from mrs. thatcher that she and her finance minister weren't split on policy
the pound would be allowed to find its own level under a new chancellor, dealers first speculated. then they decided the authorities won't step in to restrain the pound, even if he stayed
both mr. lawson and i put downward pressure on inflation as top-most priority. both of us think interest rate stability can be very useful to industry,'' mrs. thatcher said in response to a question in the house of commons
mrs. thatcher and lawson have expressed differing views in recent weeks _ he for restraining the pound and she being more concerned about inflation
meanwhile, the analysts expect the pound to continue to move upward. skeoch said he expected the pound to reach 3.20 marks within a few months and $2.04 later in the year
political opponents attacked prime minister margaret thatcher's plan to inject 800 million pounds into automaker rover group plc when the government sells it off, calling it an amazing giveaway
the rover plan, criticized tuesday in parliament, would come to the aid of the automaker with the equivalent of $1.49 billion in government funds
the plan, part of mrs. thatcher's huge and ongoing privatization program, also is likely to create controversy in the european economic community's executive commission, without whose approval the plan cannot proceed
british aerospace plc announced tuesday that it had reached an agreement to acquire rover from the government for 150 million pounds, or about $279 million, a cheaper price than had been expected. the government would make the cash injection to reduce rover's debt, british aerospace said
labor party legislator bryan gould, who serves as a spokesman on industrial issues for the opposition party, said the british aerospace announcement was astonishing and attacked the plan as an ``easter giveaway.''
lord williams, also a member of the opposition, said british aerospace shareholders ``will no doubt think christmas has come rather early this year.''
gould claimed that the government was paying british aerospace 650 million pounds, enough to raise the government's child benefit by 1 pound a week, ``to persuade them to walk away with net assets worth 770 million'' pounds
gould demanded a full house of commons debate on the issue after the easter recess
trade secretary lord young countered: ``this is not a knock-down price,'' and described the package as ``the deal of the decade.''
rover chairman graham day said the sale was good for the company and its employees
british aerospace chairman roland smith promised to develop the combined company and ``not to destroy it.''
one condition the government has attached to the rover sale is that british aerospace must not dispose of any of the business within five years
the conservative party's large majority in the house of commons guarantees passage of mrs. thatcher's policies
rover group, which is made up of automaker austin rover and land rover, which produces utility vehicles, recently announced a 1987 profit before taxes of 27.9 million pounds, or about $52 million. that compared with a loss of 355.6 million pounds, or around $661 million, in 1986
mrs. thatcher has sold 16.5 billion pounds worth of state-owned companies since she came to power in 1979 as part of her ``capitalist revolution.'' her goals have been to make those companies more competitive as well as to get more shares into the hands of the british public
companies are increasingly demanding concessionary contracts as a tactic for provoking strikes in an effort to drive unions out of their plants, a house subcommittee was told wednesday
labor leaders for now are combatting the effort by instructing their members to keep working after a contract expires and wages and benefits are unilaterally cut by an employer
but through an orchestrated series of congressional hearings, they also are trying to build a case for lauching another attempt to change the nation's labor laws if a democrat is elected president next fall so that it would be more difficult from companies to hire strikebreakers
local union officials at paper, chemical and meatpacking plants complained wednesday to a sympathetic subcommittee of the house education and labor committee that the national labor relations act has been turned againt them
rep. william clay, d-mo., chairman of the committee's labor-management relations subcommittee, said the growing anti-union tactics adopted by employers and approved by the national labor relations board threatens the future of collective bargaining
what was once the workers' weapon of last resort _ the strike _ is now being used as a tool by employers to terminate bargaining relationships,'' clay said. ``employers are purposely adopting bargaining positions intended to drive their workers out on the picket line.''
ken tritz, president of a paperworkers union local in missoula, mont., said its members have been working at a stone container corp. paper mill the past seven months without a contract after the company tried to provoke a strike
as a result, he said, his members have been losing premium, vacation and holiday pay incentives as well as some of the fringe benefits they formerly had. he estimated the lost wages and benefits for each worker at about $7,000 a year
the company was so convinced that it would succeed in provoking a strike and breaking a strike ... that it prepared a manual for strikebreakers,'' tritz said. ``we chose to work without a contract at this time because the alternatives were even more obnoxious. would you rather be shot or hung? some choice.''
no stone container officials testified at tuesday's hearing. but a vice president of another paper company locked in a lengthy strike at three plants with the paperworkers union testifed that union officials and their members were repeatedly warned that replacements for them would be hired
competition _ both domestic and foreign _ is real, serious and does not allow a labor strike `time out,''' said john nevin, a vice president of international paper co. ``if we are not producing, one of our competitors will gladly take our place.''
reynolds metals co., celebrating the 20th anniversary of the first aluminum can recycling, said wednesday it is expanding its network of company-operated recylcing installations
more than 650 units will be operating by the middle of the year, compared with about 500 last year and about 600 now, company officials said at a news conference
since reynolds began buying used cans in los angeles in 1968, the first in the industry to do so, it has bought 88 billion cans to melt into aluminum ingots in its furnaces
the industry has bought 270 billion cans, the company estimates, and is recycling about half of current production. reynolds itself is recycling more than 100 percent of can production _ it buys more cans than it sells
scrap aluminum is the cheapest source of raw material, in part because aluminum manufacture is energy-intensive. it takes 6.5 kilowatt-hours of electricity to make a can from ore and only about 5 percent of that energy to make a can from scrap
reynolds started out paying 8 cents per pound. the price fluctuates according to the world market, and currently reynolds pays 42 cents to 46 cents for a pound of cans, about 26 cans, or 1.6 cents to 1.8 cents per can
a brewer or other bottler pays about 7.5 cents for a can with a label printed on it
reynolds estimates the handling costs double that before the metal is in a form equivalent to what would result from smelting the ore. at that price, scrap-derived aluminum is still cheaper than ore-derived, but the company declines to release exact figures
prices have been rising recently, and aluminum trades on the london metal exchange at about $1.31 a pound in the form of 19\-ton ingots
can production is rising at better than a 6 percent annual rate, by about 5 billion cans a year. william o. bourke, reynolds' president and chief executive officer, said the company believes 80 percent can be recycled by the year 2000 as more and more cities turn to recycling programs to ease thir waste-handling problems and the shortage of landfill space
but he opposed as ``not cost-effective'' the so-called ``bottle bills'' that some states have enacted to require refundable deposits on beverage containers
manufacturers of competing containers ``should make it possible for people to return the bottles for cash,'' he said. but he conceded that those companies would find it difficult since their materials are not as valuable as scrap aluminum
reynolds spokesman bob shaffer said later the company opposed bottle bills also to retain the good will of its bottler customers
wheat futures closed slightly higher wednesday on the chicago board of trade while corn and soybean prices retreated in light trading
wheat was supported by expectations that the soviet union would bid thursday for 500,000 metric tons of u.s. wheat, analysts said. acceptance of the bid by the agriculture department would complete a soviet purchase of 1 million metric tons of wheat recently offered under the usda's export enhancement program
the slight downward movement of soybeans and the other grains reflected position-evening by traders ahead of the usda's thursday afternoon reports on spring planting intentions and u.s. grain stocks, said joel karlin, research analyst for research department inc. in chicago
there wasn't a whole lot of activity,'' he said. ``everybody's sitting on their hands before the reports.''
