five japanese automakers have been dumping small trucks on the u.s. market, costing u.s. workers jobs and the u.s. auto industry $500 million in lost wages, sales and profits, a study released wednesday claimed
the 42-page study was commissioned by the u.s. motor vehicle manufacturers association on behalf of general motors corp., ford motor co. and chrysler corp
the study analysts concluded that the effect of this dumping margin was something on the order of 140,000 lost units of production to u.s. manufacturers,'' said mvma president thomas hanna
the investigation, by the washington, d.c. law firm wilmer, cutler &amp; pickering, found that the five japanese companies are selling compact pickup trucks for 10 percent to 48 percent less in the united states than they charge in their japanese home market
dumping is illegal under trade agreements between the united states and its foreign partners. the companies charged with dumping by the mvma are toyota motor corp., nissan motor co., mazda motor corp., isuzu motor co. and mitsubishi motors corp
toyota immediately denied the charges in statement by robert mccurry, senior vice president of toyota motor sales u.s.a
any assertions that japanese compact trucks are injuring or threatening to injure the u.s. industry ring hollow,'' mccurry said. ``first, u.s. producers are enjoying their greatest success in history, collectively continuing to set records for sales and profits
second, japanese truck sales continue to decline and presently represent the smallest share of the u.s. market since compact trucks were introduced by the japanese,'' he said
mccurry has been the most outspoken japanese auto company executive in denying charges leveled this year, particularly by chrysler corp. executives
in previous defenses, mccurry and executives for other japanese auto companies have said that the strength of the japanese yen against other currencies has made it cheaper for them to buy raw materials
in addition, japanese automakers have worked aggressively to cut production costs, they said
in a letter accompanying the study, which was hand-delivered to commerce secretary william verity's office tuesday afternoon, the mvma asked that the u.s. government begin negotiating with the japanese government to end the dumping
however, claire buchan, a commerce department spokeswoman, said the u.s. government has only initiated a dumping investigation once, in a semi-conductor case
in the vast majority of dumping cases, she said, it is up to the u.s. industry involved to file petitions with the commerce department and the international trade commission
if the two agencies find dumping has occurred and has injured a u.s. industry, then the government assesses a duty on the imported product that is equal to the difference between the prices charged here and in the product's home market
john greenwald, an attorney with the firm that conducted the study, said negotiations between the two countries would eliminate the need for lengthy and costly litigation involved in filing the petitions
the white paper was prepared ... in hopes they would go to japanese government and say dumping is causing us problems, not only in compact pickups but in other products, and preventing the exchange-rate realignment from curing the trade deficit,'' greenwald said
automotive products account for about half of the nearly $60 billion u.s. trade deficit with japan. greenwald said continued dumping and denials of dumping would push the value of the dollar down further against the yen
the mvma study found the truck dumping prevented u.s. makers from fully using factory space, from moving car workers to truck production jobs instead of laying them off or from earning healthy returns on production and sales of small pickups
it estimated the cost to the u.s. auto industry and its workers at $500 million in lost wages, profits and sales
for example, according to the study, toyota charges $3,988 at the factory for a small pickup destined for the u.s. market and $5,313 for the same truck destined for sale in its home market
the study's authors wrote that when the japanese yen began to appreciate against the dollar two years ago, the japanese producers lost the price advantage that had enabled them to undersell american makers
faced with the choice between surrendering the gains in import levels or dumping, they decided to dump,'' the study said
the authors also called japanese makers' response that the dumping has caused no harm ``absurd.''
ab volvo of sweden announced that it has bought the bus division of british leyland, making the major scandinavian automaker a leading bus manufacturer in western europe
the purchase was announced wednesday in london and goteborg, sweden. volvo acquired the bus division from leyland's management, which took over the company from state-owned rover group plc in january 1987
under the deal, volvo acquires leyland's two plants in farington and workington in northwestern england with a total of 1,850 employees. the plants make the well-known red double-decker buses
volvo, sweden's largest and most profitable industrial company which has diversified into food and trading, has already taken over general motors corp.'s truck division. volvo's latest purchase makes it the world's second- largest bus maker after daimler-benz ag of west germany
volvo did not disclose the price it paid for leyland's bus division, which will boost volvo's bus production by 40 percent, to about 5,500 units a year. volvo's bus output rose by 16 percent to a record 3,920 units last year, hitting maximum capacity at its main swedish plant and a smaller facility in sao paulo, brazil
the british bus subsidiary will continue to operate as an independent entity although volvo plans to build about 1,000 of its own buses at the leyland plants by 1990, a volvo spokesman said
volvo's main markets are scandinavia, central europe and south america, while leyland buses are mostly marketed in britain and in british commonwealth countries
volvo's bus division last year accounted for 2 billion swedish kronor, around $340 million, or only 2.2 percent of the company's total sales of 92.5 billion kronor, or $15.7 billion. leyland is expected to show a small profit for 1987 on sales of roughly 1 billion kronor, or about $170 million
the stock market retreated today, yielding to afternoon selling after an early advance faltered
analysts noted that the dollar had shown signs of steadying in foreign exchange, which sparked a rebound in bond prices in tuesday's activity
wall streeters were generally pleased with the government's report tuesday that the index of leading economic indicators rose 0.9 percent in february
that was taken as a signal that the economy was neither weak nor dangerously strong
the market weakened as the session passed, however. brokers said traders seemed reluctant to hold onto big positions with a long holiday weekend approaching
the market will be closed in observance of good friday. the government is scheduled to report on the employment situation for march that day, but stock and bond traders will have to wait until monday to respond to it if it contains any surprises
eastman kodak co. and fuqua industries inc. said wednesday they had combined their photofinishing operations, although a lawsuit challenging the merger is still being argued
kodak and the atlanta-based fuqua wasted no time in completing the deal tuesday after the u.s. circuit court of appeals in new orleans reversed a lower court's injunction that had blocked the merger since feb. 22
qualex inc. combines fuqua's photofinishing subsidiary, colorcraft corp., with kodak-owned laboratories, to form the country's largest wholesale photofinishing operation. it has 94 processing labs around the country
paul allen, a kodak spokesman, said the target date for the merger had been feb. 1
the court of appeals decided that phototron corp., a small san bernardino, calif.-based photofinisher, had no right to try to block the merger, although it may continue pursuing its lawsuit, allen said
phototron sued kodak over the photo giant's colorwatch photofinishing system, claiming it violates antitrust laws because it is forcing non-colorwatch processing labs out of business, said joseph alioto, a photron lawyer
alioto said phototron is seeking between $100 million and $150 million in damages because of colorwatch. the merger, he said, will just increase that range
nonetheless, alioto said wednesday that he plans to ask the supreme court to issue a temporary injunction preventing the merger until he can file a request for the court to consider the matter
as far as we're concerned, the supreme court should get a look at this thing prior to the scrambling of the eggs,'' alioto said
as far as kodak and fuqua are concerned, the eggs have already been scrambled
the company will be based in durham, n.c., the home of colorcraft, and colorcraft's former chairman, d. carl hamill, will serve as chief executive officer
the lawsuit filed by phototron is being heard in u.s. district court in fort worth, texas, and is expected to continue regardless of the status of the injunction blocking the merger
