the federal trade commission has decided not to intervene in general electric co.'s bid to acquire roper corp., ge said in a brief statement wednesday
ge is battling with whirlpool corp. for control of roper, an augusta, ga.-based appliance maker
ge's sweetened $54-a-share tender offer is valued at $507 million; whirlpool is offering $470 million, or $50 a share
roper's directors initially supported the whirlpool offer, but tuesday urged stockholders to accept the ge offer
ge said in its statement that the ftc had decided not to block a ge-roper combination because of antitrust concerns
roper employs about 4,750 people, 3,000 of them in four georgia plants. in addition to electric and gas appliances, the company manufactures tillers, lawn mowers and lawn and garden tractors. its customers include sears roebuck &amp; co., the nation's largest retailer
it also manufactures some gas ranges for ge, and the fairfield-based company has said its interest in roper stems from that association
the rising british pound continued to take center stage in foreign exchange wednesday at the expense of the dollar, which lost ground against most key currencies despite reports of central bank intervention
gold prices edged higher after falling overseas. republic national bank of new york said gold was bid at $456.25 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up $1 from late tuesday
currency traders said the dollar was hurt by sterling's strength, although it managed to gain some ground in europe. trading was said to be generally quiet everywhere in anticipation of the upcoming easter and passover holidays
british chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson, speaking to a committee in parliament, said wednesday that the pound has moved higher recently only as a result of tight monetary policy, not due to an adjustment in any specific targeting by the government
one trader at a major british bank said such comments represented ``nothing new, but it is taken as a confirmation'' the government was unlikely to tamper with the pound in its current, higher range and could allow it to appreciate further
nigel lawson implied ... that the rise in sterling was something that was still in the spirit of the louvre accord of currency stabilization,'' said james t. mcgroarty, a trader and vice president at discount corp
the traders took that to mean that the (central) bank had decided to let it go. i don't buy that. i think there may be some action to slow the sterling's rise.''
still, many traders said that with prime minister margaret thatcher, bank of england governor robin leigh-pemberton and lawson backing a low-inflation stragtegy and paying less attention to the pound, that currency could advance until the middle of next month
in london, the british pound jumped to $1.8790 from $1.8705 tuesday. sterling fetched $1.8780 in new york, up from 1.86425
earlier, in tokyo, the dollar closed at 125.43 japanese yen, up from 124.37, but it fell in london to 124.75 yen
traders said the federal reserve bought a small amount of dollars and sold yen late wednesday in new york. the dollar closed at 125.025 yen, down from 125.255 yen
other dollar rates late wednesday in new york, compared with late tuesday, included: 1.66285 west german marks, down from 1.66925; 1.37215 swiss francs, down from 1.37675; 1.23575 canadian dollars, down from 1.2360; 5.6330 french francs, down from 5.6505; and 1,232.175 italian lire, down from 1,236
