platinum futures prices soared wednesday for the second consecutive session on the new york mercantile exchange on rumors of increased japanese buying and an improving economic outlook
on other markets, copper and precious metals futures advanced; energy futures were higher; livestock and meat prices retreated; grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index futures fell back
platinum settled $12.10 a troy ounce to $13.80 an ounce higher on the nymex with the contract for delivery in april at $532.50 an ounce
platinum prices have gained about $75 a troy ounce in the past two months as economic data have increasingly dispelled fears of a recession and pointed toward higher inflation
gold prices have also advanced on inflation concerns but platinum has an edge because of its strong industrial-use component, analysts said
although there was no fresh positive economic news on wednesday, rumors that japanese firms planned to increase their purchases of platinum gave the market a boost, said stephen w. platt, an analyst in chicago with dean witter reynolds inc
heightened racial tensions in south africa, the source of most of the refined platinum on the market, also underpinned the rise in prices, platt said
copper futures also posted strong gains wednesday on new york's commodity exchange, with the april contract settling 3.95 cents higher at $1.0795 a pound
a sustained rally in industrial-metals prices likely would be perceived as inflationary, which could push gold and silver prices higher as well, said analyst craig sloane of smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
on the comex, gold settled $1.50 to $2.20 higher with april at $457.80 a troy ounce; silver was 4.7 cents to 5.5 cents higher with april at $6.757 a troy ounce
unleaded gasoline led energy futures prices higher on the new york mercantile exchange
the buying stemmed from a strong increase in demand reflected by tuesday's weekly american petroleum institute report showing a 4.22-million-barrel drawdown in gasoline stocks to 230 million barrels
that's 15.6 million barrels behind last year,'' said andrew lebow, an analyst in new york with e.d.&amp; f. man international futures inc. ``we're seeing very strong demand for gasoline and that seems to be dragging the other markets up.''
lebow said higher speed limits have resulted in greater consumption of gasoline. a sharp increase in wholesale demand in the past two weeks may have reflected dealer stockpiling ahead of the easter-passover weekend, he said
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 11 cents higher with may at $17.08 a barrel; heating oil was .32 cent to .45 cent higher with april at 48.60 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .11 cent to .53 cent higher with april at 48.65 cents a gallon
cattle futures retreated on the chicago mercantile exchange on fears that consumer demand for beef will drop when recent price increases in the cash cattle market reach grocery stores in the form of higher beef prices, said chuck levitt, an analyst in chicago with shearson lehman hutton inc
pork futures prices fell as traders squared their positions ahead of thursday afternoon's 10-state hogs and pigs report from the agriculture department, he said
live cattle were .05 cent to .62 cent lower with april at 75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .78 cent lower with march at 82.75 cents a pound; hogs were .58 cent lower to .07 cent higher with april at 45.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were unchanged to .28 cent lower with may at 55.90 cents a pound
