spurred by greatly reduced minimum prices, 84 oil companies bid almost $593 million dollars wednesday for leases of federal waters in the gulf of mexico
successful high bids totalled $404.6 million, according to eileen angelico, spokeswoman for the minerals management service of the interior department
atlantic richfield co. submitted the highest bid of any of the companies _ $18.2 million for a single 5,000-acre block, identified as west cameron block 248
shell offshore submitted the largest number of bids, 250, said angelico
angelico said 931 bids on 684 different tracts had been submitted for wednesday's bid opening. a breakdown of how many tracts were leased to each successful bidder was unavailable wednesday afternoon, she said
at a similar lease sale a year ago, about 300 bids were received. angelico the increase in bids was probably due in large part to the interior department's drastic drop in the minimum price per acre _ from $150 to $25
we think that helped the number of bids,'' said angelico. ``one thing it did was provide an opportunity for more small companies to compete in the sale.''
interior secretary donald hodel said last month that the minimum bid was dropped to stimulate interest in the lease sale during a period of low oil prices
the lease sale was announced in february, when 6,265 unleased blocks _ each about 5,000 acres _ went up for sale. the blocks are anywhere from three miles to 220 miles offshore, angelico said
southland corp., the parent company of 7-eleven convenience stores, on wednesday reported a net loss of around $59 million for 1987 because of interest expenses and other costs related to its leveraged buyout
however, the company said that in the seven months prior to going private it earned $90.1 million on revenues of $4.9 billion. southland said it lost $149.7 million in the first five months of its new operating structure
in 1986, southland earned $200.4 million on revenues of $7.8 billion
southland's operating performance for the year was quite strong, especially considering that the company undertook the most extensive reorganization and cost-reduction program in its history during the fourth quarter,'' said jere w. thompson, southland president and chief executive officer
in december, southland completed its $4.9 billion leveraged buyout by merging with jt acquisition corp., an affiliate of the thompson co., the investment firm of the founding family
in a leveraged buyout, a company is bought primarily with borrowed funds that are repaid with funds generated by the acquired company's operations or through asset sales
southland owns about 7,000 7-eleven stores and is the nation's largest independent gasoline retailer with 50 percent interest in citgo petroleum corp
in reporting 1987 earnings, southland divided the seven months preceding the company's buyout and merger activities from the five months at the end of the year
the company warned a clear comparison between the two earnings periods is impossible because of the changed structure and different accounting bases
southland said it does not expect to report a net profit ``for some time'' because of interest costs to service the lbo-related debt and other factors
a new york man is suing first republicbank corp., accusing the financially troubled bank holding company of financial misrepresentation, an attorney said wednesday
attorneys for martin theodores, a new york investor, filed the suit in federal district court in dallas on tuesday
in the class action suit, theodores seeks compensatory and punitive damages, said james malone, attorney in the haverford, pa. firm of greenfield and chimicles, which is representing theodores
malone said the suit claims first republicbank inflated and misstated the collectability and security of its assets
that has an overall effect of making the bank's balance sheets and statements look better than they are,'' malone said
theodores' investment in first republicbank, which involved about $5,000 to $10,000 in bonds, shrank as the company posted a $656.8 million loss last year. but malone says it is too early to tell how much in damages will be sought
first republicbank had no comment on the suit and would not discuss pending litigation, said spokesman joe bowles
first republicbank received a $1 billion loan from the federal deposit insurance corp. earlier this month after asking the federal insuror for advice on restructuring. business</head>
allied signal aerospace company announced wednesday it has completed the consolidation of its bendix and garrett units and will sell three of its divisions to focus on commercial and military aircraft contracts
the company, a unit of allied-signal inc., also announced that its streamlining efforts in the past year have cut about 2,000 jobs, including 200 administrative posts
the company, based in morris township, n.j., is going to sell its environmental systems division of towson, md; fluid power division of utica, n.y.; and oceanics division of sylmar, calif
the combined annual sales of the businesses are about $200 million, about four percent of the company's total sales
allied-signal inc. runs businesses in aerospace, automotive products and engineered materials
these actions will consolidate the company's efforts in those markets where we are established leaders,'' said robert l. kirk, chairman and chief executive officer of allied aerospace
one half of our sales will continue to come from the military market, with the other 50 percent from commercial customers,'' kirk said
the board of directors of harcourt brace jovanovich inc. on wednesday elected ralph d. caulo as president and chief operating officer and retained longtime hbj boss william jovanovich as chairman and chief executive
caulo, 53, had been one of several executive vice presidents who constituted the office of president of the company, which has major interests in publishing, theme parks and insurance
caulo's new post indicates he will take over more of the day-to-day operations, but officials of the orlando-based company either were unavailable or would not comment on a brief statement issued after the directors' meeting. caulo will continue to oversee hbj's textbook publishing and related operations, according to the statement
jovanovich, 68, has run the company since 1955 and there were no indications that he was relinquishing any of his control
calmat co., a major cement supplier in western markets, said wednesday its board has rejected as inadequate an offer from investor ronald brierley to take the company private for $40 a share
new zealand-born brierley already owns 19 percent of calmat's 30.6 million shares, which values his bid at about $990 million for the remainder. he controls two of the 15 seats on the company's board
calmat said its directors voted unanimously against the offer, which brierley made last week
calmat rose 25 cents to $44 a share on the new york stock exchange wednesday, indicating investors expect the bidding to go higher. the stock was trading at $31.875 a share before brierley made his offer a week ago
calmat's chief executive, a.f. gerstell, said the board decided ``a sale is not in the best interest at this time given efforts to maximize shareholder values.''
two years ago calmat embarked on a strategy to boost shareholder value by selling unprofitable or marginally profitable assets and concentrating instead on its high-margin operations
gerstell said the plan has ``show substantial results, and we expect continuing increases in value.''
previously, gerstell has said that management is working with its investment banker on ``additional, more aggressive steps the company can take to continue this ongoing process.''
calmat's core businesses are in making cement, ready-mixed concrete, aggregate and hot-mixed asphalt. it also has valuable real estate holdings in california and arizona
in 1986, the company netted $44.1 million on revenues of $619 million. in the first nine months of last year, it earned $78.1 million on sales of $658.9 million
calmat was formed four years ago the merger of california portland cement co. and conrock co
as penn square bank moved toward its 1982 collapse, top officials seemed bent on expanding its energy-loan portfolio in a bid for growth that had ``no rhyme or reason,'' a former vice president testified wednesday
it appeared to be unrestrained growth for growth's sake,'' john baldwin of oklahoma city told a u.s. district court jury
baldwin's testimony focused on william patterson, 37, who was in charge of penn square energy loans when the oklahoma city bank went under
patterson is one of three men being tried on charges of improper loan activity that may have played a part in the near-collapse of chicago-based continental illinois national bank &amp; trust co. in 1984
all have pleaded innocent
federal officials have said continental participated with penn square in more than $1 billion in uncollectible loans _ most of them energy loans. the chicago bank was saved from collapse in 1984 by a $4.5 billion federal bailout
baldwin testified wednesday at patterson should have been aware of the bank's agreement not to sell off parts of loans that had been questioned by federal bank examiners
patterson violated the pact in 1982 by taking part in the sale of at least $5 million in problem loans to continental, he said
baldwin also said patterson didn't seem to care about continental's buying loans that carried inordinate risk, and was concerned only with dumping the penn square energy loans on the chicago bank
the sales shifted virtually the entire burden of risk for those loans to continental
defendant john r. lytle, 52, of suburban northfield, who once headed continental's oklahoma oil and gas lending operation, is accused of buying millions of dollars in poor-quality loans from penn square in exchange for nearly $600,000 in personal, unsecured loans
patterson is accused of arranging the personal loans, which prosecutors characterize as kickbacks
the third defendant, tulsa drilling contractor jere sturgis, is accused of making payments to lytle in an attempt to obtain loans from continental
prosecutors hope to show that lytle knew or should have known he was buying up problem loans for his bank, and that patterson knew he was dumping off a bad product on lytle
baldwin told the court that while he was at penn square, from july 1981 through its closing, top bank officials seemed intent on expanding their loans to independent oil and gas concerns
in my opinion, the bank's ... growth had no rhyme or reason to it,'' he said, calling penn square ``severely understaffed.''
lawyers said they expected the trial, which began march 9 before u.s. district judge milton shadur, will last about three more weeks
hilton hotels corp. chairman and chief executive barron hilton won a major court ruling wednesday in a nine-year legal battle over his father's estate
the court fight has, in effect, pitted hilton against several orders of catholic nuns devoted to helping the poor who were singled out as beneficiaries of the estate of the late conrad hilton
the california court of appeal reversed los angeles county probate judge's decision and concluded that a stock-purchase option granted by the father to the son covers all 6.78 million of the estate's shares. that is 27 percent of hilton hotel's shares
the stock was given to the conrad n. hilton foundation after the hotel magnate died in 1979 at age 91. the foundation's directors were instructed by the elder hilton's will to promote world peace and ``shelter little children with the umbrella of your charity.''
nuns as far away as italy were beneficiaries of the estate's largesse
the father's will also gave barron hilton an option to buy stock that couldn't be properly held by the foundation
the dispute centered on a 1969 internal revenue service rule prohibiting private foundations from owning more than 20 percent of any public company
barron hilton claimed that since the rule was violated, he could exercise his option to buy all the stock at $24 per share, or $163 million, its value at the time of his father's death
the stock today is worth about $598 million
to avoid the stock-ownership rule, the charitable foundation reclassified itself as a public-support organization. last april, a probate judge ruled that action was proper and that the foundation didn't need to divest itself of the stock
barron hilton appealed, resulting in wednesday's ruling that remanded the case to probate court to determine terms of selling the stock to barron hilton, who now owns only about 4 percent of the company
he said he was ``very pleased'' with the action, adding, ``it validates the positon i have taken since my father's death, and i regard this as a significant victory.''
the head of hte foundation, donald hubbs, said he would meet soon with the organization's directors ``to determine what action to take, but i presume we will appeal to the california supreme court.''
batus inc.'s challenge of a 19-year-old nevada law in its hostile $4.5 billion bid for farmers insurance group was upheld wednesday by a judge who labeled the law unconstitutional
batus has offered $63 for each of farmers' outstanding shares. in over-the-counter trading wednesday, farmers closed at $58.12{, down $1.37{
u.s. district court judge howard mckibben said that the law, which allows stockholders only 60 days to decide whether to sell their shares in a tender offer, violates the constitution
batus argued the nevada law conflicts with the federal williams act, which gives shareholders the right to participate in tender offers at will. ``the investors ultimately suffer because they they are required to deposit shares within the 60-day period without complete information on regulatory approvals,'' mckibben wrote in his ruling
los angeles-based farmers has been resisting takeover overtures by batus since january. batus is the american subsidiary of london-based bat industries inc. plc
bat is a tobacco, retailing and paper-goods conglomerate that for some time has been seeking a foothold in the u.s. financial services market
farmers, with about $11 billion in assets, is the nation's third largest home and auto insurer, and the seventh largest property and casualty insurer
